184 VOID
185 IopAbortRequest(
186  IN PKAPC Apc
187  )
188 
189 /*++
190 
191 Routine Description:
192 
193  This routine is invoked to abort an I/O request. It is invoked during the
194  rundown of a thread.
195 
196 Arguments:
197 
198  Apc - Pointer to the kernel APC structure. This structure is contained
199  within the I/O Request Packet (IRP) itself.
200 
201 Return Value:
202 
203  None.
204 
205 --*/
206 
207 {
208  PAGED_CODE();
209 
210  //
211  // Invoke the normal special kernel APC routine.
212  //
213 
214  IopCompleteRequest( Apc,
215  &Apc->NormalRoutine,
216  &Apc->NormalContext,
217  &Apc->SystemArgument1,
218  &Apc->SystemArgument2 );
219 }
220 
221 NTSTATUS
222 IopAcquireFileObjectLock(
223  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
224  IN KPROCESSOR_MODE RequestorMode,
225  IN BOOLEAN Alertable,
226  OUT PBOOLEAN Interrupted
227  )
228 
229 /*++
230 
231 Routine Description:
232 
233  This routine is invoked to acquire the lock for a file object whenever
234  there is contention and obtaining the fast lock for the file failed.
235 
236 Arguments:
237 
238  FileObject - Pointer to the file object whose lock is to be acquired.
239 
240  RequestorMode - Processor access mode of the caller.
241 
242  Alertable - Indicates whether or not the lock should be obtained in an
243  alertable manner.
244 
245  Interrupted - A variable to receive a BOOLEAN that indicates whether or
246  not the attempt to acquire the lock was interrupted by an alert or
247  an APC.
248 
249 Return Value:
250 
251  The function status is the final status of the operation.
252 
253 --*/
254 {
255  NTSTATUS status;
256 
257  PAGED_CODE();
258 
259  //
260  // Assume that the function will not be interrupted by an alert or an
261  // APC while attempting to acquire the lock.
262  //
263 
264  *Interrupted = FALSE;
265 
266  //
267  // Loop attempting to acquire the lock for the file object.
268  //
269 
270  InterlockedIncrement ((PLONG) &FileObject->Waiters);
271 
272  for (;;) {
273  if (!FileObject->Busy) {
274 
275  //
276  // The file object appears to be un-owned, try to acquire it
277  //
278 
279  if ( InterlockedExchange( (PLONG) &FileObject->Busy, (ULONG) TRUE ) == FALSE ) {
280 
281  //
282  // Object was acquired. Remove our count and return success
283  //
284 
285  ObReferenceObject(FileObject);
286  InterlockedDecrement ((PLONG) &FileObject->Waiters);
287  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
288  }
289  }
290 
291  //
292  // Wait for the event that indicates that the thread that currently
293  // owns the file object has released it.
294  //
295 
296  status = KeWaitForSingleObject( &FileObject->Lock,
297  Executive,
298  RequestorMode,
299  Alertable,
300  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
301 
302  //
303  // If the above wait was interrupted, then indicate so and return.
304  // Before returning, however, check the state of the ownership of
305  // the file object itself. If it is not currently owned (the busy
306  // flag is clear), then check to see whether or not there are any
307  // other waiters. If so, then set the event to the signaled state
308  // again so that they wake up and check the state of the busy flag.
309  //
310 
311  if (status == STATUS_USER_APC || status == STATUS_ALERTED) {
312  InterlockedDecrement ((PLONG) &FileObject->Waiters);
313 
314  if (!FileObject->Busy && FileObject->Waiters) {
315  KeSetEvent( &FileObject->Lock, 0, FALSE );
316 
317  }
318  *Interrupted = TRUE;
319  return status;
320  }
321  }
322 }

324 
325 VOID
326 IopAllocateIrpCleanup(
327  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
328  IN PKEVENT EventObject OPTIONAL
329  )
330 
331 /*++
332 
333 Routine Description:
334 
335  This routine is invoked internally by those system services that attempt
336  to allocate an IRP and fail. This routine cleans up the file object
337  and any event object that has been references and releases any locks
338  that were taken out.
339 
340 Arguments:
341 
342  FileObject - Pointer to the file object being worked on.
343 
344  EventObject - Optional pointer to a referenced event to be dereferenced.
345 
346 Return Value:
347 
348  None.
349 
350 --*/
351 
352 {
353  PAGED_CODE();
354 
355  //
356  // Begin by dereferencing the event, if one was specified.
357  //
358 
359  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( EventObject )) {
360  ObDereferenceObject( EventObject );
361  }
362 
363  //
364  // Release the synchronization semaphore if it is currently held and
365  // dereference the file object.
366  //
367 
368  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_SYNCHRONOUS_IO) {
369  IopReleaseFileObjectLock( FileObject );
370  }
371 
372  ObDereferenceObject( FileObject );
373 
374  return;
375 }
376 
377 PIRP
378 IopAllocateIrpMustSucceed(
379  IN CCHAR StackSize
380  )
381 
382 /*++
383 
384 Routine Description:
385 
386  This routine is invoked to allocate an IRP when there are no appropriate
387  packets remaining on the look-aside list, and no memory was available
388  from the general non-paged pool, and yet, the code path requiring the
389  packet has no way of backing out and simply returning an error. There-
390  fore, it must allocate an IRP. Hence, this routine is called to allocate
391  that packet.
392 
393 Arguments:
394 
395  StackSize - Supplies the number of IRP I/O stack locations that the
396  packet must have when allocated.
397 
398 Return Value:
399 
400  A pointer to the allocated I/O Request Packet.
401 
402 --*/
403 
404 {
405  PIRP irp;
406  LONG numTries;
407  LARGE_INTEGER interval;
408 
409  //
410  // Attempt to allocate the IRP normally and failing that,
411  // wait a second and try again.
412  //
413 
414  numTries = IO_INFINITE_RETRIES;
415 
416  irp = IoAllocateIrp(StackSize, FALSE);
417 
418  while (!irp && numTries) {
419 
420  interval.QuadPart = -1000 * 1000 * 10; // 10 Msec.
421  KeDelayExecutionThread(KernelMode, FALSE, &interval);
422  irp = IoAllocateIrp(StackSize, FALSE);
423  if (numTries != IO_INFINITE_RETRIES) {
424  numTries--;
425  }
426  }
427 
428 
429  return irp;
430 }

432 VOID
433 IopApcHardError(
434  IN PVOID StartContext
435  )
436 
437 /*++
438 
439 Routine Description:
440 
441  This function is invoked when we need to do a hard error pop-up, but the
442  Irp's originating thread is at APC level, ie. IoPageRead. We in a special
443  purpose thread that will go away when the user responds to the pop-up.
444 
445 Arguments:
446 
447  StartContext - Startup context, contains a IOP_APC_HARD_ERROR_PACKET.
448 
449 Return Value:
450 
451  None.
452 
453 --*/
454 
455 {
456  PIOP_APC_HARD_ERROR_PACKET packet;
457 
458  packet = StartContext;
459 
460  IopRaiseHardError( packet->Irp, packet->Vpb, packet->RealDeviceObject );
461 
462  ExFreePool( packet );
463 }

465 
466 VOID
467 IopCancelAlertedRequest(
468  IN PKEVENT Event,
469  IN PIRP Irp
470  )
471 
472 /*++
473 
474 Routine Description:
475 
476  This routine is invoked when a synchronous I/O operation that is blocked in
477  the I/O system needs to be canceled because the thread making the request has
478  either been alerted because it is going away or because of a CTRL/C. This
479  routine carefully attempts to work its way out of the current operation so
480  that local events or other local data will not be accessed once the service
481  being interrupted returns.
482 
483 Arguments:
484 
485  Event - The address of a kernel event that will be set to the Signaled state
486  by I/O completion when the request is complete.
487 
488  Irp - Pointer to the I/O Request Packet (IRP) representing the current request.
489 
490 Return Value:
491 
492  None.
493 
494 --*/
495 
496 {
497  KIRQL irql;
498  LARGE_INTEGER deltaTime;
499  BOOLEAN canceled;
500 
501  PAGED_CODE();
502 
503  //
504  // Begin by blocking special kernel APCs so that the request cannot
505  // complete.
506  //
507 
508  KeRaiseIrql( APC_LEVEL, &irql );
509 
510  //
511  // Check the state of the event to determine whether or not the
512  // packet has already been completed.
513  //
514 
515  if (KeReadStateEvent( Event ) == 0) {
516 
517  //
518  // The packet has not been completed, so attempt to cancel it.
519  //
520 
521  canceled = IoCancelIrp( Irp );
522 
523  KeLowerIrql( irql );
524 
525  if (canceled) {
526 
527  //
528  // The packet had a cancel routine, so it was canceled. Loop,
529  // waiting for the packet to complete. This should occur almost
530  // immediately.
531  //
532 
533  deltaTime.QuadPart = - 10 * 1000 * 10;
534 
535  while (KeReadStateEvent( Event ) == 0) {
536 
537  KeDelayExecutionThread( KernelMode, FALSE, &deltaTime );
538 
539  }
540 
541  } else {
542 
543  //
544  // The packet did not have a cancel routine, so simply wait for
545  // the event to be set to the Signaled state. This will save
546  // CPU time by not looping, since it is not known when the packet
547  // will actually complete. Note, however, that the cancel flag
548  // is set in the packet, so should a driver examine the flag
549  // at some point in the future, it will immediately stop
550  // processing the request.
551  //
552 
553  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( Event,
554  Executive,
555  KernelMode,
556  FALSE,
557  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
558 
559  }
560 
561  } else {
562 
563  //
564  // The packet has already been completed, so simply lower the
565  // IRQL back to its original value and exit.
566  //
567 
568  KeLowerIrql( irql );
569 
570  }
571 }
572 
573 NTSTATUS
574 IopCheckGetQuotaBufferValidity(
575  IN PFILE_GET_QUOTA_INFORMATION QuotaBuffer,
576  IN ULONG QuotaLength,
577  OUT PULONG_PTR ErrorOffset
578  )
579 
580 /*++
581 
582 Routine Description:
583 
584  This routine checks the validity of the specified get quota buffer to
585  guarantee that its format is proper, no fields hang over, that it is
586  not recursive, etc.
587 
588 Arguments:
589 
590  QuotaBuffer - Pointer to the buffer containing the get quota structure
591  array to be checked.
592 
593  QuotaLength - Specifies the length of the quota buffer.
594 
595  ErrorOffset - A variable to receive the offset of the offending entry
596  in the quota buffer if an error is incurred. This variable is only
597  valid if an error occurs.
598 
599 Return Value:
600 
601  The function value is STATUS_SUCCESS if the get quota buffer contains a
602  valid, properly formed list, otherwise STATUS_QUOTA_LIST_INCONSISTENT.
603 
604 --*/
605 
606 {
607 
608 #define GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( CurrentSid, SidBase ) ( (ULONG) ((PCHAR) CurrentSid - (PCHAR) SidBase) )
609 
610  LONG tempLength;
611  LONG entrySize;
612  PFILE_GET_QUOTA_INFORMATION sids;
613 
614  PAGED_CODE();
615 
616  //
617  // Walk the buffer and ensure that its format is valid. That is, ensure
618  // that it does not walk off the end of the buffer, is not recursive, etc.
619  //
620 
621  sids = QuotaBuffer;
622  tempLength = QuotaLength;
623 
624  for (;;) {
625 
626  //
627  // Ensure that the current entry is valid.
628  //
629 
630  if ((tempLength < (LONG) (FIELD_OFFSET(FILE_GET_QUOTA_INFORMATION, Sid.SubAuthority) +
631  sizeof (sids->Sid.SubAuthority))) ||
632  !RtlValidSid( &sids->Sid)) {
633 
634  *ErrorOffset = GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( sids, QuotaBuffer );
635  return STATUS_QUOTA_LIST_INCONSISTENT;
636  }
637 
638  //
639  // Get the size of the current entry in the buffer.
640  //
641 
642  entrySize = FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_GET_QUOTA_INFORMATION, Sid ) + RtlLengthSid( (&sids->Sid) );
643 
644  if (sids->NextEntryOffset) {
645 
646  //
647  // There is another entry in the buffer and it must be longword
648  // aligned. Ensure that the offset indicates that it is. If it
649  // isn't, return an invalid parameter status.
650  //
651 
652  if (entrySize > (LONG) sids->NextEntryOffset ||
653  sids->NextEntryOffset & (sizeof( ULONG ) - 1)) {
654  *ErrorOffset = GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( sids, QuotaBuffer );
655  return STATUS_QUOTA_LIST_INCONSISTENT;
656 
657  } else {
658 
659  //
660  // There is another entry in the buffer, so account for the
661  // size of the current entry in the length and get a pointer
662  // to the next entry.
663  //
664 
665  tempLength -= sids->NextEntryOffset;
666  if (tempLength < 0) {
667  *ErrorOffset = GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( sids, QuotaBuffer );
668  return STATUS_QUOTA_LIST_INCONSISTENT;
669  }
670  sids = (PFILE_GET_QUOTA_INFORMATION) ((PCHAR) sids + sids->NextEntryOffset);
671  }
672 
673  } else {
674 
675  //
676  // There are no other entries in the buffer. Simply account for
677  // the overall buffer length according to the size of the current
678  // entry and exit the loop.
679  //
680 
681  tempLength -= entrySize;
682  break;
683  }
684  }
685 
686  //
687  // All of the entries in the buffer have been processed. Check to see
688  // whether the overall buffer length went negative. If so, return an
689  // error.
690  //
691 
692  if (tempLength < 0) {
693  *ErrorOffset = GET_OFFSET_LENGTH( sids, QuotaBuffer );
694  return STATUS_QUOTA_LIST_INCONSISTENT;
695  }
696 
697  //
698  // The format of the get quota buffer was correct, so simply return a
699  // success status code.
700  //
701 
702  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
703 }

705 
706 VOID
707 IopCompleteUnloadOrDelete(
708  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
709  IN BOOLEAN OnCleanStack,
710  IN KIRQL Irql
711  )
712 
713 /*++
714 
715 Routine Description:
716 
717  This routine is invoked when the reference count on a device object
718  transitions to a zero and the driver is mark for unload or device has
719  been marked for delete. This means that it may be possible to actually
720  unload the driver or delete the device object. If all
721  of the devices have a reference count of zero, then the driver is
722  actually unloaded. Note that in order to ensure that this routine is
723  not invoked twice, at the same time, on two different processors, the
724  I/O database spin lock is still held at this point.
725 
726 Arguments:
727 
728  DeviceObject - Supplies a pointer to one of the driver's device objects,
729  namely the one whose reference count just went to zero.
730 
731  OnCleanStack - Indicates whether the current thread is in the middle a
732  driver operation.
733 
734  Irql - Specifies the IRQL of the processor at the time that the I/O
735  database lock was acquired.
736 
737 Return Value:
738 
739  None.
740 
741 --*/
742 
743 {
744  PDRIVER_OBJECT driverObject;
745  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
746  PDEVICE_OBJECT baseDeviceObject;
747  PDEVICE_OBJECT attachedDeviceObject;
748  PDEVOBJ_EXTENSION deviceExtension;
749 
750  BOOLEAN unload = TRUE;
751 
752  driverObject = DeviceObject->DriverObject;
753 
754  if (DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags & DOE_REMOVE_PENDING) {
755 
756  //
757  // Run some tests to determine if it is an appropriate time to notify
758  // PnP that all file objects in the attachment chain have gone away.
759  //
760 
761  baseDeviceObject = IopGetDeviceAttachmentBase( DeviceObject );
762  deviceExtension = baseDeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension;
763 
764  ASSERT(deviceExtension->DeviceNode != NULL);
765 
766  //
767  // baseDeviceObject is a PDO, this is a PnP stack. See if
768  // an IRP_MN_REMOVE_DEVICE is pending.
769  //
770 
771  //
772  // PnP wants to be notified as soon as all refcounts on all devices in
773  // this attachment chain go away.
774  //
775 
776  attachedDeviceObject = baseDeviceObject;
777  while (attachedDeviceObject != NULL) {
778 
779  if (attachedDeviceObject->ReferenceCount != 0) {
780 
781  //
782  // At least one device object in the attachment chain has
783  // an outstanding open.
784  //
785 
786  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, Irql );
787 
788  return;
789  }
790  attachedDeviceObject = attachedDeviceObject->AttachedDevice;
791  }
792 
793  //
794  // Now one more time changing DOE_REMOVE_PENDING to
795  // DOE_REMOVE_PROCESSED.
796  //
797 
798  attachedDeviceObject = baseDeviceObject;
799  while (attachedDeviceObject != NULL) {
800 
801  deviceExtension = attachedDeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension;
802 
803  deviceExtension->ExtensionFlags &= ~DOE_REMOVE_PENDING;
804  deviceExtension->ExtensionFlags |= DOE_REMOVE_PROCESSED;
805 
806  attachedDeviceObject = attachedDeviceObject->AttachedDevice;
807  }
808 
809  //
810  // It is time to give PnP the notification it was waiting for. We have
811  // to release the spinlock before doing so.
812  //
813 
814  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, Irql );
815 
816  IopChainDereferenceComplete( baseDeviceObject, OnCleanStack );
817 
818  return;
819  }
820 
821  if (DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags & DOE_DELETE_PENDING) {
822 
823  if ((DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags &
824  DOE_UNLOAD_PENDING) == 0 ||
825  driverObject->Flags & DRVO_UNLOAD_INVOKED) {
826 
827  unload = FALSE;
828  }
829 
830  //
831  // If another device is attached to this device, inform the former's
832  // driver that the device is being deleted.
833  //
834 
835  if (DeviceObject->AttachedDevice) {
836  PFAST_IO_DISPATCH fastIoDispatch = DeviceObject->AttachedDevice->DriverObject->FastIoDispatch;
837  PDEVICE_OBJECT attachedDevice = DeviceObject->AttachedDevice;
838 
839  //
840  // Increment the device reference count so the detach routine
841  // does not recurse back to here.
842  //
843 
844  DeviceObject->ReferenceCount++;
845 
846  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, Irql );
847 
848  if (fastIoDispatch &&
849  fastIoDispatch->SizeOfFastIoDispatch > FIELD_OFFSET( FAST_IO_DISPATCH, FastIoDetachDevice ) &&
850  fastIoDispatch->FastIoDetachDevice) {
851  (fastIoDispatch->FastIoDetachDevice)( attachedDevice, DeviceObject );
852  }
853 
854  Irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
855 
856  //
857  // Restore the reference count value.
858  //
859 
860  DeviceObject->ReferenceCount--;
861 
862  if (DeviceObject->AttachedDevice ||
863  DeviceObject->ReferenceCount != 0) {
864 
865 
866  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, Irql );
867  return;
868  }
869  }
870 
871  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, Irql );
872 
873  //
874  // Deallocate the memory for the security descriptor that was allocated
875  // for this device object.
876  //
877 
878  if (DeviceObject->SecurityDescriptor != (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL) {
879  ObDereferenceSecurityDescriptor( DeviceObject->SecurityDescriptor, 1 );
880  }
881 
882  //
883  // Remove this device object from the driver object's list.
884  //
885 
886  IopInsertRemoveDevice( DeviceObject->DriverObject, DeviceObject, FALSE );
887 
888  //
889  // Finally, dereference the object so it is deleted.
890  //
891 
892  ObDereferenceObject( DeviceObject );
893 
894  //
895  // Return if the unload does not need to be done.
896  //
897 
898  if (!unload) {
899  return;
900  }
901 
902  //
903  // Reacquire the spin lock make sure the unload routine does has
904  // not been called.
905  //
906 
907  Irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
908 
909  if (driverObject->Flags & DRVO_UNLOAD_INVOKED) {
910 
911  //
912  // Some other thread is doing the unload, release the lock and return.
913  //
914 
915  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, Irql );
916  return;
917  }
918  }
919 
920  //
921  // Scan the list of device objects for this driver, looking for a
922  // non-zero reference count. If any reference count is non-zero, then
923  // the driver may not be unloaded.
924  //
925 
926  deviceObject = driverObject->DeviceObject;
927 
928  while (deviceObject) {
929  if (deviceObject->ReferenceCount || deviceObject->AttachedDevice ||
930  deviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags & (DOE_DELETE_PENDING | DOE_REMOVE_PENDING)) {
931  unload = FALSE;
932  break;
933  }
934  deviceObject = deviceObject->NextDevice;
935  }
936 
937  //
938  // If this is a base filesystem driver and we still have device objects
939  // skip the unload.
940  //
941 
942  if (driverObject->Flags & DRVO_BASE_FILESYSTEM_DRIVER && driverObject->DeviceObject) {
943  unload = FALSE;
944  }
945 
946  if (unload) {
947  driverObject->Flags |= DRVO_UNLOAD_INVOKED;
948  }
949 
950  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, Irql );
951 
952  //
953  // If the reference counts for all of the devices is zero, then this
954  // driver can now be unloaded.
955  //
956 
957  if (unload) {
958  LOAD_PACKET loadPacket;
959 
960  KeInitializeEvent( &loadPacket.Event, NotificationEvent, FALSE );
961  loadPacket.DriverObject = driverObject;
962 
963  if (OnCleanStack) {
964 
965  IopLoadUnloadDriver(&loadPacket);
966 
967  } else {
968 
969  ExInitializeWorkItem( &loadPacket.WorkQueueItem,
970  IopLoadUnloadDriver,
971  &loadPacket );
972  ExQueueWorkItem( &loadPacket.WorkQueueItem, DelayedWorkQueue );
973  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &loadPacket.Event,
974  Executive,
975  KernelMode,
976  FALSE,
977  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
978  }
979 
980  ObMakeTemporaryObject( driverObject );
981  ObDereferenceObject( driverObject );
982  }
983 }
984 
985 VOID
986 IopCompletePageWrite(
987  IN PKAPC Apc,
988  IN PKNORMAL_ROUTINE *NormalRoutine,
989  IN PVOID *NormalContext,
990  IN PVOID *SystemArgument1,
991  IN PVOID *SystemArgument2
992  )
993 
994 /*++
995 
996 Routine Description:
997 
998  This routine executes as a special kernel APC routine in the context of
999  the Modified Page Writer (MPW) system thread when an out-page operation
1000  has completed.
1001 
1002  This routine performs the following tasks:
1003 
1004  o The I/O status is copied.
1005 
1006  o The Modified Page Writer's APC routine is invoked.
1007 
1008 Arguments:
1009 
1010  Apc - Supplies a pointer to kernel APC structure.
1011 
1012  NormalRoutine - Supplies a pointer to a pointer to the normal function
1013  that was specified when the APC was initialized.
1014 
1015  NormalContext - Supplies a pointer to a pointer to an arbitrary data
1016  structure that was specified when the APC was initialized.
1017 
1018  SystemArgument1 - Supplies a pointer to an argument that contains an
1019  argument that is unused by this routine.
1020 
1021  SystemArgument2 - Supplies a pointer to an argument that contains an
1022  argument that is unused by this routine.
1023 
1024 Return Value:
1025 
1026  None.
1027 
1028 --*/
1029 
1030 {
1031  PIRP irp;
1032  PIO_APC_ROUTINE apcRoutine;
1033  PVOID apcContext;
1034  PIO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
1035 
1036  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( NormalRoutine );
1037  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( NormalContext );
1038  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( SystemArgument1 );
1039  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( SystemArgument2 );
1040 
1041  //
1042  // Begin by getting the address of the I/O Request Packet from the APC.
1043  //
1044 
1045  irp = CONTAINING_RECORD( Apc, IRP, Tail.Apc );
1046 
1047  //
1048  // If this I/O operation did not complete successfully through the
1049  // dispatch routine of the driver, then drop everything on the floor
1050  // now and return to the original call point in the MPW.
1051  //
1052 
1053  if (!irp->PendingReturned && NT_ERROR( irp->IoStatus.Status )) {
1054  IoFreeIrp( irp );
1055  return;
1056  }
1057 
1058  //
1059  // Copy the I/O status from the IRP into the caller's I/O status block.
1060  //
1061 
1062  *irp->UserIosb = irp->IoStatus;
1063 
1064  //
1065  // Copy the pertinent information from the I/O Request Packet into locals
1066  // and free it.
1067  //
1068 
1069  apcRoutine = irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine;
1070  apcContext = irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcContext;
1071  ioStatus = irp->UserIosb;
1072 
1073  IoFreeIrp( irp );
1074 
1075  //
1076  // Finally, invoke the MPW's APC routine.
1077  //
1078 
1079  apcRoutine( apcContext, ioStatus, 0 );
1080 
1081  return;
1082 }
1083 
1084 
1085 VOID
1086 IopCompleteRequest(
1087  IN PKAPC Apc,
1088  IN PKNORMAL_ROUTINE *NormalRoutine,
1089  IN PVOID *NormalContext,
1090  IN PVOID *SystemArgument1,
1091  IN PVOID *SystemArgument2
1092  )
1093 
1094 /*++
1095 
1096 Routine Description:
1097 
1098  This routine executes as a special kernel APC routine in the context of
1099  the thread which originally requested the I/O operation which is now
1100  being completed.
1101 
1102  This routine performs the following tasks:
1103 
1104  o A check is made to determine whether the specified request ended
1105  with an error status. If so, and the error code qualifies as one
1106  which should be reported to an error port, then an error port is
1107  looked for in the thread/process. If one exists, then this routine
1108  will attempt to set up an LPC to it. Otherwise, it will attempt to
1109  set up an LPC to the system error port.
1110 
1111  o Copy buffers.
1112 
1113  o Free MDLs.
1114 
1115  o Copy I/O status.
1116 
1117  o Set event, if any and dereference if appropriate.
1118 
1119  o Dequeue the IRP from the thread queue as pending I/O request.
1120 
1121  o Queue APC to thread, if any.
1122 
1123  o If no APC is to be queued, then free the packet now.
1124 
1125 
1126 Arguments:
1127 
1128  Apc - Supplies a pointer to kernel APC structure.
1129 
1130  NormalRoutine - Supplies a pointer to a pointer to the normal function
1131  that was specified when the APC was initialized.
1132 
1133  NormalContext - Supplies a pointer to a pointer to an arbitrary data
1134  structure that was specified when the APC was initialized.
1135 
1136  SystemArgument1 - Supplies a pointer to an argument that contains the
1137  address of the original file object for this I/O operation.
1138 
1139  SystemArgument2 - Supplies a pointer to an argument that contains an
1140  argument that is used by this routine only in the case of STATUS_REPARSE.
1141 
1142 Return Value:
1143 
1144  None.
1145 
1146 --*/
1147 {
1148 #define SynchronousIo( Irp, FileObject ) ( \
1149  (Irp->Flags & IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API) || \
1150  (FileObject == NULL ? 0 : FileObject->Flags & FO_SYNCHRONOUS_IO) )
1151 
1152  PIRP irp;
1153  PMDL mdl, nextMdl;
1154  PETHREAD thread;
1155  PFILE_OBJECT fileObject;
1156  NTSTATUS status;
1157 
1158  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( NormalRoutine );
1159  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( NormalContext );
1160 
1161  //
1162  // Begin by getting the address of the I/O Request Packet. Also, get
1163  // the address of the current thread and the address of the original file
1164  // object for this I/O operation.
1165  //
1166 
1167  irp = CONTAINING_RECORD( Apc, IRP, Tail.Apc );
1168  thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
1169  fileObject = (PFILE_OBJECT) *SystemArgument1;
1170 
1171  IOVP_COMPLETE_REQUEST(Apc, SystemArgument1, SystemArgument2);
1172 
1173  //
1174  // Ensure that the packet is not being completed with a minus one. This
1175  // is apparently a common problem in some drivers, and has no meaning
1176  // as a status code.
1177  //
1178 
1179  ASSERT( irp->IoStatus.Status != 0xffffffff );
1180 
1181  //
1182  // See if we need to do the name transmogrify work.
1183  //
1184 
1185  if ( *SystemArgument2 != NULL ) {
1186 
1187  PREPARSE_DATA_BUFFER reparseBuffer = NULL;
1188 
1189  //
1190  // The IO_REPARSE_TAG_MOUNT_POINT tag needs attention.
1191  //
1192 
1193  if ( irp->IoStatus.Status == STATUS_REPARSE &&
1194  irp->IoStatus.Information == IO_REPARSE_TAG_MOUNT_POINT ) {
1195 
1196  reparseBuffer = (PREPARSE_DATA_BUFFER) *SystemArgument2;
1197 
1198  ASSERT( reparseBuffer->ReparseTag == IO_REPARSE_TAG_MOUNT_POINT );
1199  ASSERT( reparseBuffer->ReparseDataLength < MAXIMUM_REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER_SIZE );
1200  ASSERT( reparseBuffer->Reserved < MAXIMUM_REPARSE_DATA_BUFFER_SIZE );
1201 
1202  IopDoNameTransmogrify( irp,
1203  fileObject,
1204  reparseBuffer );
1205  }
1206  }
1207 
1208  //
1209  // Check to see whether there is any data in a system buffer which needs
1210  // to be copied to the caller's buffer. If so, copy the data and then
1211  // free the system buffer if necessary.
1212  //
1213 
1214  if (irp->Flags & IRP_BUFFERED_IO) {
1215 
1216  //
1217  // Copy the data if this was an input operation. Note that no copy
1218  // is performed if the status indicates that a verify operation is
1219  // required, or if the final status was an error-level severity.
1220  //
1221 
1222  if (irp->Flags & IRP_INPUT_OPERATION &&
1223  irp->IoStatus.Status != STATUS_VERIFY_REQUIRED &&
1224  !NT_ERROR( irp->IoStatus.Status )) {
1225 
1226  //
1227  // Copy the information from the system buffer to the caller's
1228  // buffer. This is done with an exception handler in case
1229  // the operation fails because the caller's address space
1230  // has gone away, or it's protection has been changed while
1231  // the service was executing.
1232  //
1233 
1234  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
1235 
1236  try {
1237  RtlCopyMemory( irp->UserBuffer,
1238  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer,
1239  irp->IoStatus.Information );
1240  } except(IopExceptionFilter(GetExceptionInformation(), &status)) {
1241 
1242  //
1243  // An exception occurred while attempting to copy the
1244  // system buffer contents to the caller's buffer. Set
1245  // a new I/O completion status.
1246  // If the status is a special one set by Mm then we need to
1247  // return here and the operation will be retried in
1248  // IoRetryIrpCompletions.
1249  //
1250 
1251  if (status == STATUS_MULTIPLE_FAULT_VIOLATION) {
1252  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = fileObject; /* Wiped out by APC overlay */
1253  irp->Flags |= IRP_RETRY_IO_COMPLETION;
1254  return;
1255  }
1256  irp->IoStatus.Status = GetExceptionCode();
1257  }
1258  }
1259 
1260  //
1261  // Free the buffer if needed.
1262  //
1263 
1264  if (irp->Flags & IRP_DEALLOCATE_BUFFER) {
1265  ExFreePool( irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer );
1266  }
1267  }
1268 
1269  irp->Flags &= ~(IRP_DEALLOCATE_BUFFER|IRP_BUFFERED_IO);
1270 
1271  //
1272  // If there is an MDL (or MDLs) associated with this I/O request,
1273  // Free it (them) here. This is accomplished by walking the MDL list
1274  // hanging off of the IRP and deallocating each MDL encountered.
1275  //
1276 
1277  if (irp->MdlAddress) {
1278  for (mdl = irp->MdlAddress; mdl != NULL; mdl = nextMdl) {
1279  nextMdl = mdl->Next;
1280  IoFreeMdl( mdl );
1281  }
1282  }
1283 
1284  irp->MdlAddress = NULL;
1285 
1286  //
1287  // Check to see whether or not the I/O operation actually completed. If
1288  // it did, then proceed normally. Otherwise, cleanup everything and get
1289  // out of here.
1290  //
1291 
1292  if (!NT_ERROR( irp->IoStatus.Status ) ||
1293  (NT_ERROR( irp->IoStatus.Status ) &&
1294  irp->PendingReturned &&
1295  !SynchronousIo( irp, fileObject ))) {
1296 
1297  PVOID port = NULL;
1298  PVOID key = NULL;
1299  BOOLEAN createOperation = FALSE;
1300 
1301  //
1302  // If there is an I/O completion port object associated w/this request,
1303  // save it here so that the file object can be dereferenced.
1304  //
1305 
1306  if (fileObject && fileObject->CompletionContext) {
1307  port = fileObject->CompletionContext->Port;
1308  key = fileObject->CompletionContext->Key;
1309  }
1310 
1311  //
1312  // Copy the I/O status from the IRP into the caller's I/O status
1313  // block. This is done using an exception handler in case the caller's
1314  // virtual address space for the I/O status block was deleted or
1315  // its protection was changed to readonly. Note that if the I/O
1316  // status block cannot be written, the error is simply ignored since
1317  // there is no way to tell the caller that something went wrong.
1318  // This is, of course, by definition, since the I/O status block
1319  // is where the caller will attempt to look for errors in the first
1320  // place!
1321  //
1322 
1323  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
1324 
1325  try {
1326 
1327  //
1328  // Since HasOverlappedIoCompleted and GetOverlappedResult only
1329  // look at the Status field of the UserIosb to determine if the
1330  // IRP has completed, the Information field must be written
1331  // before the Status field.
1332  //
1333 
1334 #if defined(_WIN64)
1335  PIO_STATUS_BLOCK32 UserIosb32;
1336 
1337  //
1338  // If the caller passes a 32 bit IOSB the ApcRoutine has the LSB set to 1
1339  //
1340  if (IopIsIosb32(irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine)) {
1341  UserIosb32 = (PIO_STATUS_BLOCK32)irp->UserIosb;
1342 
1343  UserIosb32->Information = (ULONG)irp->IoStatus.Information;
1344  KeMemoryBarrierWithoutFence ();
1345  *((volatile NTSTATUS *) &UserIosb32->Status) = irp->IoStatus.Status;
1346  } else {
1347  irp->UserIosb->Information = irp->IoStatus.Information;
1348  KeMemoryBarrierWithoutFence ();
1349  *((volatile NTSTATUS *) &irp->UserIosb->Status) = irp->IoStatus.Status;
1350  }
1351 #else
1352  irp->UserIosb->Information = irp->IoStatus.Information;
1353  KeMemoryBarrierWithoutFence ();
1354  *((volatile NTSTATUS *) &irp->UserIosb->Status) = irp->IoStatus.Status;
1355 #endif /*_WIN64 */
1356 
1357  } except(IopExceptionFilter(GetExceptionInformation(), &status)) {
1358 
1359  //
1360  // An exception was incurred attempting to write the caller's
1361  // I/O status block. Simply continue executing as if nothing
1362  // ever happened since nothing can be done about it anyway.
1363  // If the status is a multiple fault status, this is a special
1364  // status sent by the Memory manager. Mark the IRP and return from
1365  // this routine. Mm will call us back later and we will retry this
1366  // operation (IoRetryIrpCompletions)
1367  //
1368  if (status == STATUS_MULTIPLE_FAULT_VIOLATION) {
1369  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = fileObject; /* Wiped out by APC overlay */
1370  irp->Flags |= IRP_RETRY_IO_COMPLETION;
1371  return;
1372  }
1373  }
1374 
1375 
1376  //
1377  // Determine whether the caller supplied an event that needs to be set
1378  // to the Signaled state. If so, then set it; otherwise, set the event
1379  // in the file object to the Signaled state.
1380  //
1381  // It is possible for the event to have been specified as a PKEVENT if
1382  // this was an I/O operation hand-built for an FSP or an FSD, or
1383  // some other types of operations such as synchronous I/O APIs. In
1384  // any of these cases, the event was not referenced since it is not an
1385  // object manager event, so it should not be dereferenced.
1386  //
1387  // Also, it is possible for there not to be a file object for this IRP.
1388  // This occurs when an FSP is doing I/O operations to a device driver on
1389  // behalf of a process doing I/O to a file. The file object cannot be
1390  // dereferenced if this is the case. If this operation was a create
1391  // operation then the object should not be dereferenced either. This
1392  // is because the reference count must be one or it will go away for
1393  // the caller (not much point in making an object that just got created
1394  // go away).
1395  //
1396 
1397  if (irp->UserEvent) {
1398  (VOID) KeSetEvent( irp->UserEvent, 0, FALSE );
1399  if (fileObject) {
1400  if (!(irp->Flags & IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API)) {
1401  ObDereferenceObject( irp->UserEvent );
1402  }
1403  if (fileObject->Flags & FO_SYNCHRONOUS_IO && !(irp->Flags & IRP_OB_QUERY_NAME)) {
1404  (VOID) KeSetEvent( &fileObject->Event, 0, FALSE );
1405  fileObject->FinalStatus = irp->IoStatus.Status;
1406  }
1407  if (irp->Flags & IRP_CREATE_OPERATION) {
1408  createOperation = TRUE;
1409  irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine = (PIO_APC_ROUTINE) NULL;
1410  }
1411  }
1412  } else if (fileObject) {
1413  (VOID) KeSetEvent( &fileObject->Event, 0, FALSE );
1414  fileObject->FinalStatus = irp->IoStatus.Status;
1415  if (irp->Flags & IRP_CREATE_OPERATION) {
1416  createOperation = TRUE;
1417  irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine = (PIO_APC_ROUTINE) NULL;
1418  }
1419  }
1420 
1421  //
1422  // If this is normal I/O, update the transfer count for this process.
1423  //
1424 
1425  if (!(irp->Flags & IRP_CREATE_OPERATION)) {
1426  if (irp->Flags & IRP_READ_OPERATION) {
1427  IopUpdateReadTransferCount( (ULONG) irp->IoStatus.Information );
1428  } else if (irp->Flags & IRP_WRITE_OPERATION) {
1429  IopUpdateWriteTransferCount( (ULONG) irp->IoStatus.Information );
1430  } else {
1431  //
1432  // If the information field contains a pointer then skip the update.
1433  // Some PNP IRPs contain this.
1434  //
1435 
1436  if (!((ULONG_PTR) irp->IoStatus.Information & IopKernelPointerBit)) {
1437  IopUpdateOtherTransferCount( (ULONG) irp->IoStatus.Information );
1438  }
1439  }
1440  }
1441 
1442  //
1443  // Dequeue the packet from the thread's pending I/O request list.
1444  //
1445 
1446  IopDequeueThreadIrp( irp );
1447 
1448  //
1449  // If the caller requested an APC, queue it to the thread. If not, then
1450  // simply free the packet now.
1451  //
1452 
1453 #ifdef _WIN64
1454  //
1455  // For 64 bit systems clear the LSB field of the ApcRoutine that indicates whether
1456  // the IOSB is a 32 bit IOSB or a 64 bit IOSB.
1457  //
1458  irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine =
1459  (PIO_APC_ROUTINE)((LONG_PTR)(irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine) & ~1);
1460 #endif
1461 
1462  if (irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine) {
1463  KeInitializeApc( &irp->Tail.Apc,
1464  &thread->Tcb,
1465  CurrentApcEnvironment,
1466  IopUserCompletion,
1467  (PKRUNDOWN_ROUTINE) IopUserRundown,
1468  (PKNORMAL_ROUTINE) irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine,
1469  irp->RequestorMode,
1470  irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcContext );
1471 
1472  KeInsertQueueApc( &irp->Tail.Apc,
1473  irp->UserIosb,
1474  NULL,
1475  2 );
1476 
1477  } else if (port && irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcContext) {
1478 
1479  //
1480  // If there is a completion context associated w/this I/O operation,
1481  // send the message to the port. Tag completion packet as an Irp.
1482  //
1483 
1484  irp->Tail.CompletionKey = key;
1485  irp->Tail.Overlay.PacketType = IopCompletionPacketIrp;
1486 
1487  KeInsertQueue( (PKQUEUE) port,
1488  &irp->Tail.Overlay.ListEntry );
1489 
1490  } else {
1491 
1492  //
1493  // Free the IRP now since it is no longer needed.
1494  //
1495 
1496  IoFreeIrp( irp );
1497  }
1498 
1499  if (fileObject && !createOperation) {
1500 
1501  //
1502  // Dereference the file object now.
1503  //
1504 
1505  ObDereferenceObjectDeferDelete( fileObject );
1506  }
1507 
1508  } else {
1509 
1510  if (irp->PendingReturned && fileObject) {
1511 
1512  //
1513  // This is an I/O operation that completed as an error for
1514  // which a pending status was returned and the I/O operation
1515  // is synchronous. For this case, the I/O system is waiting
1516  // on behalf of the caller. If the reason that the I/O was
1517  // synchronous is that the file object was opened for synchronous
1518  // I/O, then the event associated with the file object is set
1519  // to the signaled state. If the I/O operation was synchronous
1520  // because this is a synchronous API, then the event is set to
1521  // the signaled state.
1522  //
1523  // Note also that the status must be returned for both types
1524  // of synchronous I/O. If this is a synchronous API, then the
1525  // I/O system supplies its own status block so it can simply
1526  // be written; otherwise, the I/O system will obtain the final
1527  // status from the file object itself.
1528  //
1529 
1530  if (irp->Flags & IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API) {
1531  *irp->UserIosb = irp->IoStatus;
1532  if (irp->UserEvent) {
1533  (VOID) KeSetEvent( irp->UserEvent, 0, FALSE );
1534  } else {
1535  (VOID) KeSetEvent( &fileObject->Event, 0, FALSE );
1536  }
1537  } else {
1538  fileObject->FinalStatus = irp->IoStatus.Status;
1539  (VOID) KeSetEvent( &fileObject->Event, 0, FALSE );
1540  }
1541  }
1542 
1543  //
1544  // The operation was incomplete. Perform the general cleanup. Note
1545  // that everything is basically dropped on the floor without doing
1546  // anything. That is:
1547  //
1548  // IoStatusBlock - Do nothing.
1549  // Event - Dereference without setting to Signaled state.
1550  // FileObject - Dereference without setting to Signaled state.
1551  // ApcRoutine - Do nothing.
1552  //
1553 
1554  if (fileObject) {
1555  if (!(irp->Flags & IRP_CREATE_OPERATION)) {
1556  ObDereferenceObjectDeferDelete( fileObject );
1557  }
1558  }
1559 
1560  if (irp->UserEvent &&
1561  fileObject &&
1562  !(irp->Flags & IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API)) {
1563  ObDereferenceObject( irp->UserEvent );
1564  }
1565 
1566  IopDequeueThreadIrp( irp );
1567  IoFreeIrp( irp );
1568  }
1569 }
1570 
1571 VOID
1572 IopConnectLinkTrackingPort(
1573  IN PVOID Parameter
1574  )
1575 
1576 /*++
1577 
1578 Routine Description:
1579 
1580  This routine is invoked to connect to the user-mode link tracking service's
1581  LPC port. It makes a connection which establishes a handle to the port,
1582  and then creates a referenced object pointer to the port.
1583 
1584 Arguments:
1585 
1586  Parameter - Pointer to the link tracking packet.
1587 
1588 Return Value:
1589 
1590  None.
1591 
1592 
1593 --*/
1594 
1595 {
1596  #define MESSAGE_SIZE ( (2 * sizeof( FILE_VOLUMEID_WITH_TYPE )) + \
1597  sizeof( FILE_OBJECTID_BUFFER ) + \
1598  sizeof( GUID ) + \
1599  sizeof( NTSTATUS ) + \
1600  sizeof( ULONG ) )
1601 
1602  PLINK_TRACKING_PACKET ltp;
1603  HANDLE serviceHandle;
1604  NTSTATUS status;
1605 
1606  PAGED_CODE();
1607  //
1608  // Begin by getting a pointer to the link tracking packet.
1609  //
1610 
1611  ltp = (PLINK_TRACKING_PACKET) Parameter;
1612 
1613 
1614  //
1615  // Ensure that the port has not already been opened.
1616  //
1617 
1618  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
1619  if (!IopLinkTrackingServiceObject) {
1620 
1621  UNICODE_STRING portName;
1622  ULONG maxMessageLength;
1623  SECURITY_QUALITY_OF_SERVICE dynamicQos;
1624 
1625  if (KeReadStateEvent( IopLinkTrackingServiceEvent )) {
1626 
1627  //
1628  // Attempt to open a handle to the port.
1629  //
1630 
1631  //
1632  // Set up the security quality of service parameters to use over the
1633  // port. Use the most efficient (least overhead) which is dynamic
1634  // rather than static tracking.
1635  //
1636 
1637  dynamicQos.ImpersonationLevel = SecurityImpersonation;
1638  dynamicQos.ContextTrackingMode = SECURITY_DYNAMIC_TRACKING;
1639  dynamicQos.EffectiveOnly = TRUE;
1640 
1641  //
1642  // Generate the string structure for describing the port.
1643  //
1644 
1645  RtlInitUnicodeString( &portName, L"\\Security\\TRKWKS_PORT" );
1646 
1647  status = NtConnectPort( &serviceHandle,
1648  &portName,
1649  &dynamicQos,
1650  (PPORT_VIEW) NULL,
1651  (PREMOTE_PORT_VIEW) NULL,
1652  &maxMessageLength,
1653  (PVOID) NULL,
1654  (PULONG) NULL );
1655  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
1656  if (maxMessageLength >= MESSAGE_SIZE) {
1657  status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle( serviceHandle,
1658  0,
1659  LpcPortObjectType,
1660  KernelMode,
1661  &IopLinkTrackingServiceObject,
1662  NULL );
1663  NtClose( serviceHandle );
1664  } else {
1665  NtClose( serviceHandle );
1666  status = STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
1667  }
1668  }
1669 
1670  } else {
1671 
1672  //
1673  // The service has not been started so the port does not exist.
1674  //
1675 
1676  status = STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_NOT_FOUND;
1677  }
1678  }
1679 
1680 
1681  //
1682  // Return final status and wake the caller up.
1683  //
1684  ltp->FinalStatus = status;
1685  KeSetEvent( &ltp->Event, 0, FALSE );
1686 }
1687 
1688 VOID
1689 IopDisassociateThreadIrp(
1690  VOID
1691  )
1692 
1693 /*++
1694 
1695 Routine Description:
1696 
1697  This routine is invoked when the I/O requests for a thread are being
1698  cancelled, but there is a packet at the end of the thread's queue that
1699  has not been completed for such a long period of time that it has timed
1700  out. It is this routine's responsibility to try to disassociate that
1701  IRP with this thread.
1702 
1703 Arguments:
1704 
1705  None.
1706 
1707 Return Value:
1708 
1709  None.
1710 
1711 --*/
1712 
1713 {
1714  KIRQL irql;
1715  KIRQL spIrql;
1716  PIRP irp;
1717  PETHREAD thread;
1718  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
1719  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
1720  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
1721  PIO_ERROR_LOG_PACKET errorLogEntry;
1722 
1723  //
1724  // Begin by ensuring that the packet has not already been removed from
1725  // the thread's queue.
1726  //
1727 
1728  KeRaiseIrql( APC_LEVEL, &irql );
1729 
1730  thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
1731 
1732  //
1733  // If there are no packets on the IRP list, then simply return now.
1734  // All of the packets have been fully completed, so the caller will also
1735  // simply return to its caller.
1736  //
1737 
1738  if (IsListEmpty( &thread->IrpList )) {
1739  KeLowerIrql( irql );
1740  return;
1741  }
1742 
1743  //
1744  // Get a pointer to the first packet on the queue, and begin examining
1745  // it. Note that because the processor is at raised IRQL, and because
1746  // the packet can only be removed in the context of the currently
1747  // executing thread, that it is not possible for the packet to be removed
1748  // from the list. On the other hand, it IS possible for the packet to
1749  // be queued to the thread's APC list at this point, and this must be
1750  // blocked/synchronized in order to examine the request.
1751  //
1752  // Begin, therefore, by acquiring the I/O completion spinlock, so that
1753  // the packet can be safely examined.
1754  //
1755 
1756  spIrql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoCompletionLock );
1757 
1758  //
1759  // Check to see whether or not the packet has been completed (that is,
1760  // queued to the current thread). If not, change threads.
1761  //
1762 
1763  entry = thread->IrpList.Flink;
1764  irp = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, IRP, ThreadListEntry );
1765 
1766  if (irp->CurrentLocation == irp->StackCount + 2) {
1767 
1768  //
1769  // The request has just gone through enough of completion that
1770  // queueing it to the thread is inevitable. Simply release the
1771  // lock and return.
1772  //
1773 
1774  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoCompletionLock, spIrql );
1775  KeLowerIrql( irql );
1776  return;
1777  }
1778 
1779  //
1780  // The packet has been located, and it is not going through completion
1781  // at this point. Switch threads, so that it will not complete through
1782  // this thread, remove the request from this thread's queue, and release
1783  // the spinlock. Final processing of the IRP will occur when I/O
1784  // completion notices that there is no thread associated with the
1785  // request. It will essentially drop the I/O on the floor.
1786  //
1787  // Also, while the request is still held, attempt to determine on which
1788  // device object the operation is being performed.
1789  //
1790 
1791  IopDeadIrp = irp;
1792 
1793  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = (PETHREAD) NULL;
1794  entry = RemoveHeadList( &thread->IrpList );
1795 
1796  // Initialize the thread entry. Otherwise the assertion in IoFreeIrp
1797  // called via IopDeadIrp will fail.
1798  InitializeListHead (&(irp)->ThreadListEntry);
1799 
1800  irpSp = IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation( irp );
1801  if (irp->CurrentLocation <= irp->StackCount) {
1802  deviceObject = irpSp->DeviceObject;
1803  } else {
1804  deviceObject = (PDEVICE_OBJECT) NULL;
1805  }
1806  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoCompletionLock, spIrql );
1807  KeLowerIrql( irql );
1808 
1809  //
1810  // If a device object could be identified then try to write to the event log about this
1811  // device object.
1812  //
1813 
1814  if (deviceObject) {
1815  errorLogEntry = IoAllocateErrorLogEntry(deviceObject, sizeof(IO_ERROR_LOG_PACKET));
1816  if (errorLogEntry) {
1817  errorLogEntry->ErrorCode = IO_DRIVER_CANCEL_TIMEOUT;
1818  IoWriteErrorLogEntry(errorLogEntry);
1819  }
1820  }
1821 
1822  return;
1823 }
1824 
1825 VOID
1826 IopDeallocateApc(
1827  IN PKAPC Apc,
1828  IN PKNORMAL_ROUTINE *NormalRoutine,
1829  IN PVOID *NormalContext,
1830  IN PVOID *SystemArgument1,
1831  IN PVOID *SystemArgument2
1832  )
1833 
1834 /*++
1835 
1836 Routine Description:
1837 
1838  This routine is invoked to deallocate an APC that was used to queue a
1839  request to a target thread. It simple deallocates the APC.
1840 
1841 Arguments:
1842 
1843  Apc - Supplies a pointer to kernel APC structure.
1844 
1845  NormalRoutine - Supplies a pointer to a pointer to the normal function
1846  that was specified when the APC was initialized.
1847 
1848  NormalContext - Supplies a pointer to a pointer to an arbitrary data
1849  structure that was specified when the APC was initialized.
1850 
1851  SystemArgument1, SystemArgument2 - Supplies a set of two pointers to
1852  two arguments that contain untyped data.
1853 
1854 Return Value:
1855 
1856  None.
1857 
1858 --*/
1859 
1860 {
1861  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( NormalRoutine );
1862  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( NormalContext );
1863  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( SystemArgument1 );
1864  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( SystemArgument2 );
1865 
1866  PAGED_CODE();
1867 
1868  //
1869  // Free the APC.
1870  //
1871 
1872  ExFreePool( Apc );
1873 }
1874 
1875 VOID
1876 IopDropIrp(
1877  IN PIRP Irp,
1878  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject
1879  )
1880 
1881 /*++
1882 
1883 Routine Description:
1884 
1885  This routine attempts to drop everything about the specified IRP on the
1886  floor.
1887 
1888 Arguments:
1889 
1890  Irp - Supplies the I/O Request Packet to be completed to the bit bucket.
1891 
1892  FileObject - Supplies the file object for which the I/O Request Packet was
1893  bound.
1894 
1895 Return Value:
1896 
1897  None.
1898 
1899 --*/
1900 
1901 {
1902  PMDL mdl;
1903  PMDL nextMdl;
1904 
1905  //
1906  // Free the resources associated with the IRP.
1907  //
1908 
1909  if (Irp->Flags & IRP_DEALLOCATE_BUFFER) {
1910  ExFreePool( Irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer );
1911  }
1912 
1913  if (Irp->MdlAddress) {
1914  for (mdl = Irp->MdlAddress; mdl; mdl = nextMdl) {
1915  nextMdl = mdl->Next;
1916  IoFreeMdl( mdl );
1917  }
1918  }
1919 
1920  if (Irp->UserEvent &&
1921  FileObject &&
1922  !(Irp->Flags & IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API)) {
1923  ObDereferenceObject( Irp->UserEvent );
1924  }
1925 
1926  if (FileObject && !(Irp->Flags & IRP_CREATE_OPERATION)) {
1927  ObDereferenceObjectEx( FileObject, 1 );
1928  }
1929 
1930  //
1931  // Finally, free the IRP itself.
1932  //
1933 
1934  IoFreeIrp( Irp );
1935 }
1936 
1937 LONG
1938 IopExceptionFilter(
1939  IN PEXCEPTION_POINTERS ExceptionPointer,
1940  OUT PNTSTATUS ExceptionCode
1941  )
1942 
1943 /*++
1944 
1945 Routine Description:
1946 
1947  This routine is invoked when an exception occurs to determine whether or
1948  not the exception was due to an error that caused an in-page error status
1949  code exception to be raised. If so, then this routine changes the code
1950  in the exception record to the actual error code that was originally
1951  raised.
1952 
1953 Arguments:
1954 
1955  ExceptionPointer - Pointer to the exception record.
1956 
1957  ExceptionCode - Variable to receive actual exception code.
1958 
1959 Return Value:
1960 
1961  The function value indicates that the exception handler is to be executed.
1962 
1963 --*/
1964 
1965 {
1966  //
1967  // Simply check for an in-page error status code and, if the conditions
1968  // are right, replace it with the actual status code.
1969  //
1970 
1971  *ExceptionCode = ExceptionPointer->ExceptionRecord->ExceptionCode;
1972  if (*ExceptionCode == STATUS_IN_PAGE_ERROR &&
1973  ExceptionPointer->ExceptionRecord->NumberParameters >= 3) {
1974  *ExceptionCode = (LONG) ExceptionPointer->ExceptionRecord->ExceptionInformation[2];
1975  }
1976 
1977  //
1978  // Translate alignment warnings into alignment errors.
1979  //
1980 
1981  if (*ExceptionCode == STATUS_DATATYPE_MISALIGNMENT) {
1982  *ExceptionCode = STATUS_DATATYPE_MISALIGNMENT_ERROR;
1983  }
1984 
1985  return EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER;
1986 }
1987 
1988 VOID
1989 IopExceptionCleanup(
1990  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
1991  IN PIRP Irp,
1992  IN PKEVENT EventObject OPTIONAL,
1993  IN PKEVENT KernelEvent OPTIONAL
1994  )
1995 
1996 /*++
1997 
1998 Routine Description:
1999 
2000  This routine performs generalized cleanup for the I/O system services when
2001  an exception occurs during caller parameter processing. This routine
2002  performs the following steps:
2003 
2004  o If a system buffer was allocated it is freed.
2005 
2006  o If an MDL was allocated it is freed.
2007 
2008  o The IRP is freed.
2009 
2010  o If the file object is opened for synchronous I/O, the semaphore
2011  is released.
2012 
2013  o If an event object was referenced it is dereferenced.
2014 
2015  o If a kernel event was allocated, free it.
2016 
2017  o The file object is dereferenced.
2018 
2019 Arguments:
2020 
2021  FileObject - Pointer to the file object currently being worked on.
2022 
2023  Irp - Pointer to the IRP allocated to handle the I/O request.
2024 
2025  EventObject - Optional pointer to a referenced event object.
2026 
2027  KernelEvent - Optional pointer to an allocated kernel event.
2028 
2029 Return Value:
2030 
2031  None.
2032 
2033 --*/
2034 
2035 {
2036  PAGED_CODE();
2037 
2038  //
2039  // If a system buffer was allocated from nonpaged pool, free it.
2040  //
2041 
2042  if (Irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer != NULL) {
2043  ExFreePool( Irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer );
2044  }
2045 
2046  //
2047  // If an MDL was allocated, free it.
2048  //
2049 
2050  if (Irp->MdlAddress != NULL) {
2051  IoFreeMdl( Irp->MdlAddress );
2052  }
2053 
2054  //
2055  // Free the I/O Request Packet.
2056  //
2057 
2058  IoFreeIrp( Irp );
2059 
2060  //
2061  // Finally, release the synchronization semaphore if it is currently
2062  // held, dereference the event if one was specified, free the kernel
2063  // event if one was allocated, and dereference the file object.
2064  //
2065 
2066  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_SYNCHRONOUS_IO) {
2067  IopReleaseFileObjectLock( FileObject );
2068  }
2069 
2070  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( EventObject )) {
2071  ObDereferenceObject( EventObject );
2072  }
2073 
2074  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( KernelEvent )) {
2075  ExFreePool( KernelEvent );
2076  }
2077 
2078  ObDereferenceObject( FileObject );
2079 
2080  return;
2081 }
2082 
2083 VOID
2084 IopFreeIrpAndMdls(
2085  IN PIRP Irp
2086  )
2087 
2088 /*++
2089 
2090 Routine Description:
2091 
2092  This routine frees the specified I/O Request Packet and all of its Memory
2093  Descriptor Lists.
2094 
2095 Arguments:
2096 
2097  Irp - Pointer to the I/O Request Packet to be freed.
2098 
2099 Return Value:
2100 
2101  None.
2102 
2103 --*/
2104 
2105 {
2106  PMDL mdl;
2107  PMDL nextMdl;
2108 
2109  //
2110  // If there are any MDLs that need to be freed, free them now.
2111  //
2112 
2113  for (mdl = Irp->MdlAddress; mdl != (PMDL) NULL; mdl = nextMdl) {
2114  nextMdl = mdl->Next;
2115  IoFreeMdl( mdl );
2116  }
2117 
2118  //
2119  // Free the IRP.
2120  //
2121 
2122  IoFreeIrp( Irp );
2123  return;
2124 }
2125 
2126 NTSTATUS
2127 IopGetDriverNameFromKeyNode(
2128  IN HANDLE KeyHandle,
2129  OUT PUNICODE_STRING DriverName
2130  )
2131 
2132 /*++
2133 
2134 Routine Description:
2135 
2136  Given a handle to a driver service list key in the registry, return the
2137  name that represents the Object Manager name space string that should
2138  be used to locate/create the driver object.
2139 
2140 Arguments:
2141 
2142  KeyHandle - Supplies a handle to driver service entry in the registry.
2143 
2144  DriverName - Supplies a Unicode string descriptor variable in which the
2145  name of the driver is returned.
2146 
2147 Return Value:
2148 
2149  The function value is the final status of the operation.
2150 
2151 --*/
2152 
2153 {
2154  PKEY_VALUE_FULL_INFORMATION keyValueInformation;
2155  PKEY_BASIC_INFORMATION keyBasicInformation;
2156  ULONG keyBasicLength;
2157  NTSTATUS status;
2158 
2159  PAGED_CODE();
2160 
2161  //
2162  // Get the optional object name for this driver from the value for this
2163  // key. If one exists, then its name overrides the default name of the
2164  // driver.
2165  //
2166 
2167  status = IopGetRegistryValue( KeyHandle,
2168  L"ObjectName",
2169  &keyValueInformation );
2170 
2171  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
2172 
2173  PWSTR src, dst;
2174  ULONG i, nameLength;
2175 
2176  //
2177  // The driver entry specifies an object name. This overrides the
2178  // default name for the driver. Use this name to open the driver
2179  // object.
2180  //
2181 
2182  if ((keyValueInformation->DataLength == 0) || (keyValueInformation->DataLength == 1)) {
2183  ExFreePool( keyValueInformation );
2184  return STATUS_ILL_FORMED_SERVICE_ENTRY;
2185  }
2186 
2187  DriverName->Length = (USHORT) (keyValueInformation->DataLength - sizeof( WCHAR ));
2188  DriverName->MaximumLength = (USHORT) keyValueInformation->DataLength;
2189 
2190  src = (PWSTR) ((PUCHAR) keyValueInformation + keyValueInformation->DataOffset);
2191  dst = (PWSTR) keyValueInformation;
2192  nameLength = DriverName->Length / sizeof( WCHAR );
2193 
2194  for (i = nameLength; i; i--) {
2195  *dst++ = *src++;
2196  }
2197 
2198  DriverName->Buffer = (PWSTR) keyValueInformation;
2199 
2200  } else {
2201 
2202  PULONG driverType;
2203  PWSTR baseObjectName;
2204  UNICODE_STRING remainderName;
2205 
2206  //
2207  // The driver node does not specify an object name, so determine
2208  // what the default name for the driver object should be based on
2209  // the information in the key.
2210  //
2211 
2212  status = IopGetRegistryValue( KeyHandle,
2213  L"Type",
2214  &keyValueInformation );
2215  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status ) || !keyValueInformation->DataLength) {
2216 
2217  //
2218  // There must be some type of "Type" associated with this driver,
2219  // either DRIVER or FILE_SYSTEM. Otherwise, this node is ill-
2220  // formed.
2221  //
2222 
2223  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
2224  ExFreePool( keyValueInformation );
2225  }
2226 
2227  return STATUS_ILL_FORMED_SERVICE_ENTRY;
2228  }
2229 
2230  //
2231  // Now determine whether the type of this entry is a driver or a
2232  // file system. Begin by assuming that it is a device driver.
2233  //
2234 
2235  baseObjectName = L"\\Driver\\";
2236  DriverName->Length = 8*2;
2237 
2238  driverType = (PULONG) ((PUCHAR) keyValueInformation + keyValueInformation->DataOffset);
2239 
2240  if (*driverType == FileSystemType ||
2241  *driverType == RecognizerType) {
2242  baseObjectName = L"\\FileSystem\\";
2243  DriverName->Length = 12*2;
2244  }
2245 
2246  //
2247  // Get the name of the key that is being used to describe this
2248  // driver. This will return just the last component of the name
2249  // string, which can be used to formulate the name of the driver.
2250  //
2251 
2252  status = ZwQueryKey( KeyHandle,
2253  KeyBasicInformation,
2254  (PVOID) NULL,
2255  0,
2256  &keyBasicLength );
2257 
2258  keyBasicInformation = ExAllocatePool( NonPagedPool, keyBasicLength );
2259  if (!keyBasicInformation) {
2260  ExFreePool( keyValueInformation );
2261  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
2262  }
2263 
2264  status = ZwQueryKey( KeyHandle,
2265  KeyBasicInformation,
2266  keyBasicInformation,
2267  keyBasicLength,
2268  &keyBasicLength );
2269  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
2270  ExFreePool( keyBasicInformation );
2271  ExFreePool( keyValueInformation );
2272  return status;
2273  }
2274 
2275  //
2276  // Allocate a buffer from pool that is large enough to contain the
2277  // entire name string of the driver object.
2278  //
2279 
2280  DriverName->MaximumLength = (USHORT) (DriverName->Length + keyBasicInformation->NameLength);
2281  DriverName->Buffer = ExAllocatePool( NonPagedPool,
2282  DriverName->MaximumLength );
2283  if (!DriverName->Buffer) {
2284  ExFreePool( keyBasicInformation );
2285  ExFreePool( keyValueInformation );
2286  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
2287  }
2288 
2289  //
2290  // Now form the name of the object to be opened.
2291  //
2292 
2293  DriverName->Length = 0;
2294  RtlAppendUnicodeToString( DriverName, baseObjectName );
2295  remainderName.Length = (USHORT) keyBasicInformation->NameLength;
2296  remainderName.MaximumLength = remainderName.Length;
2297  remainderName.Buffer = &keyBasicInformation->Name[0];
2298  RtlAppendUnicodeStringToString( DriverName, &remainderName );
2299  ExFreePool( keyBasicInformation );
2300  ExFreePool( keyValueInformation );
2301  }
2302 
2303  //
2304  // Finally, simply return to the caller with the name filled in. Note
2305  // that the caller must free the buffer pointed to by the Buffer field
2306  // of the Unicode string descriptor.
2307  //
2308 
2309  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
2310 }
2311 
2312 
2313 
2314 NTSTATUS
2315 IopGetFileInformation(
2316  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
2317  IN ULONG Length,
2318  IN FILE_INFORMATION_CLASS FileInformationClass,
2319  OUT PVOID FileInformation,
2320  OUT PULONG ReturnedLength
2321  )
2322 
2323 /*++
2324 
2325 Routine Description:
2326 
2327  This routine is invoked to asynchronously obtain the name or other information
2328  of a file object when the file was opened for synchronous I/O, and the previous mode of the
2329  caller was kernel mode, and the query was done through the Object Manager.
2330  In this case, the situation is likely that the Lazy Writer has incurred a
2331  write error, and it is attempting to obtain the name of the file so that it
2332  can output a popup. In doing so, a deadlock can occur because another
2333  thread has locked the file object synchronous I/O lock. Hence, this routine
2334  obtains the name of the file w/o acquiring that lock.
2335 
2336 Arguments:
2337 
2338  FileObject - A pointer to the file object whose name is to be queried.
2339 
2340  Length - Supplies the length of the buffer to receive the name.
2341 
2342  FileInformation - A pointer to the buffer to receive the name.
2343 
2344  ReturnedLength - A variable to receive the length of the name returned.
2345 
2346 Return Value:
2347 
2348  The status returned is the final completion status of the operation.
2349 
2350 --*/
2351 
2352 {
2353 
2354  PIRP irp;
2355  NTSTATUS status;
2356  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
2357  KEVENT event;
2358  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
2359  IO_STATUS_BLOCK localIoStatus;
2360 
2361  PAGED_CODE();
2362 
2363  //
2364  // Reference the file object here so that no special checks need be made
2365  // in I/O completion to determine whether or not to dereference the file
2366  // object.
2367  //
2368 
2369  ObReferenceObject( FileObject );
2370 
2371  //
2372  // Initialize an event that will be used to synchronize the completion of
2373  // the query operation. Note that this is the only way to synchronize this
2374  // since the file object itself cannot be used since it was opened for
2375  // synchronous I/O and may be busy.
2376  //
2377 
2378  KeInitializeEvent( &event, SynchronizationEvent, FALSE );
2379 
2380  //
2381  // Get the address of the target device object.
2382  //
2383 
2384  deviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( FileObject );
2385 
2386  //
2387  // Allocate and initialize the I/O Request Packet (IRP) for this operation.
2388  //
2389 
2390  irp = IoAllocateIrp( deviceObject->StackSize, FALSE );
2391  if (!irp) {
2392 
2393  //
2394  // An IRP could not be allocated. Cleanup and return an appropriate
2395  // error status code.
2396  //
2397 
2398  ObDereferenceObject( FileObject );
2399  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
2400  }
2401 
2402  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = FileObject;
2403  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
2404  irp->RequestorMode = KernelMode;
2405 
2406  //
2407  // Fill in the service independent parameters in the IRP. Note that the
2408  // setting of the special query name flag in the packet guarantees that the
2409  // standard completion for a synchronous file object will not occur because
2410  // this flag communicates to the I/O completion that it should not do so.
2411  //
2412 
2413  irp->UserEvent = &event;
2414  irp->Flags = IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API | IRP_OB_QUERY_NAME;
2415  irp->UserIosb = &localIoStatus;
2416  irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine = (PIO_APC_ROUTINE) NULL;
2417 
2418  //
2419  // Get a pointer to the stack location for the first driver. This will be
2420  // used to pass the original function codes and parameters.
2421  //
2422 
2423  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
2424  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_QUERY_INFORMATION;
2425  irpSp->FileObject = FileObject;
2426 
2427  //
2428  // Set the system buffer address to the address of the caller's buffer and
2429  // set the flags so that the buffer is not deallocated.
2430  //
2431 
2432  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer = FileInformation;
2433  irp->Flags |= IRP_BUFFERED_IO;
2434 
2435  //
2436  // Copy the caller's parameters to the service-specific portion of the
2437  // IRP.
2438  //
2439 
2440  irpSp->Parameters.QueryFile.Length = Length;
2441  irpSp->Parameters.QueryFile.FileInformationClass = FileInformationClass;
2442 
2443  //
2444  // Insert the packet at the head of the IRP list for the thread.
2445  //
2446 
2447  IopQueueThreadIrp( irp );
2448 
2449  //
2450  // Now simply invoke the driver at its dispatch entry with the IRP.
2451  //
2452 
2453  status = IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp );
2454 
2455  //
2456  // Now get the final status of the operation once the request completes
2457  // and return the length of the buffer written.
2458  //
2459 
2460  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
2461  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
2462  Executive,
2463  KernelMode,
2464  FALSE,
2465  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
2466  status = localIoStatus.Status;
2467  }
2468 
2469  *ReturnedLength = (ULONG) localIoStatus.Information;
2470  return status;
2471 }
2472 
2473 BOOLEAN
2474 IopGetMountFlag(
2475  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
2476  )
2477 
2478 /*++
2479 
2480 Routine Description:
2481 
2482  This routine is invoked to determine whether or not the specified device
2483  is mounted.
2484 
2485 Arguments:
2486 
2487  DeviceObject - Supplies a pointer to the device object for which the mount
2488  flag is tested.
2489 
2490 Return Value:
2491 
2492  The function value is TRUE if the specified device is mounted, otherwise
2493  FALSE.
2494 
2495 
2496 --*/
2497 
2498 {
2499  KIRQL irql;
2500  BOOLEAN deviceMounted = FALSE;
2501 
2502  //
2503  // Check to see whether or not the device is mounted. Note that the caller
2504  // has probably already looked to see whether or not the device has a VPB
2505  // outside of owning the lock, so simply get the lock and check it again
2506  // to start with, rather than checking to see whether or not the device
2507  // still has a VPB without holding the lock.
2508  //
2509 
2510  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoVpbLock );
2511  if (DeviceObject->Vpb) {
2512  if (DeviceObject->Vpb->Flags & VPB_MOUNTED) {
2513  deviceMounted = TRUE;
2514  }
2515  }
2516  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoVpbLock, irql );
2517 
2518  return deviceMounted;
2519 }
2520 
2521 NTSTATUS
2522 IopGetRegistryKeyInformation(
2523  IN HANDLE KeyHandle,
2524  OUT PKEY_FULL_INFORMATION *Information
2525  )
2526 
2527 /*++
2528 
2529 Routine Description:
2530 
2531  This routine is invoked to retrieve the full key information for a
2532  registry key. This is done by querying the full key information
2533  of the key with a zero-length buffer to determine the size of the data,
2534  and then allocating a buffer and actually querying the data into the buffer.
2535 
2536  It is the responsibility of the caller to free the buffer.
2537 
2538 Arguments:
2539 
2540  KeyHandle - Supplies the key handle whose full key information is to
2541  be queried
2542 
2543  Information - Returns a pointer to the allocated data buffer.
2544 
2545 Return Value:
2546 
2547  The function value is the final status of the query operation.
2548 
2549 --*/
2550 
2551 {
2552  NTSTATUS status;
2553  PKEY_FULL_INFORMATION infoBuffer;
2554  ULONG keyInfoLength;
2555 
2556  PAGED_CODE();
2557 
2558  //
2559  // Figure out how big the data value is so that a buffer of the
2560  // appropriate size can be allocated.
2561  //
2562 
2563  status = ZwQueryKey( KeyHandle,
2564  KeyFullInformation,
2565  (PVOID) NULL,
2566  0,
2567  &keyInfoLength );
2568  if (status != STATUS_BUFFER_OVERFLOW &&
2569  status != STATUS_BUFFER_TOO_SMALL) {
2570  return status;
2571  }
2572 
2573  //
2574  // Allocate a buffer large enough to contain the entire key data.
2575  //
2576 
2577  infoBuffer = ExAllocatePool( NonPagedPool, keyInfoLength );
2578  if (!infoBuffer) {
2579  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
2580  }
2581 
2582  //
2583  // Query the full key data for the key.
2584  //
2585 
2586  status = ZwQueryKey( KeyHandle,
2587  KeyFullInformation,
2588  infoBuffer,
2589  keyInfoLength,
2590  &keyInfoLength );
2591  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
2592  ExFreePool( infoBuffer );
2593  return status;
2594  }
2595 
2596  //
2597  // Everything worked, so simply return the address of the allocated
2598  // buffer to the caller, who is now responsible for freeing it.
2599  //
2600 
2601  *Information = infoBuffer;
2602  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
2603 }
2604 
2605 NTSTATUS
2606 IopGetRegistryValue(
2607  IN HANDLE KeyHandle,
2608  IN PWSTR ValueName,
2609  OUT PKEY_VALUE_FULL_INFORMATION *Information
2610  )
2611 
2612 /*++
2613 
2614 Routine Description:
2615 
2616  This routine is invoked to retrieve the data for a registry key's value.
2617  This is done by querying the value of the key with a zero-length buffer
2618  to determine the size of the value, and then allocating a buffer and
2619  actually querying the value into the buffer.
2620 
2621  It is the responsibility of the caller to free the buffer.
2622 
2623 Arguments:
2624 
2625  KeyHandle - Supplies the key handle whose value is to be queried
2626 
2627  ValueName - Supplies the null-terminated Unicode name of the value.
2628 
2629  Information - Returns a pointer to the allocated data buffer.
2630 
2631 Return Value:
2632 
2633  The function value is the final status of the query operation.
2634 
2635 --*/
2636 
2637 {
2638  UNICODE_STRING unicodeString;
2639  NTSTATUS status;
2640  PKEY_VALUE_FULL_INFORMATION infoBuffer;
2641  ULONG keyValueLength, guessSize;
2642 
2643  PAGED_CODE();
2644 
2645  RtlInitUnicodeString( &unicodeString, ValueName );
2646 
2647  //
2648  // Set an initial size to try when loading a key. Note that
2649  // KeyValueFullInformation already comes with a single WCHAR of data.
2650  //
2651  guessSize = (ULONG)(sizeof(KEY_VALUE_FULL_INFORMATION) +
2652  wcslen(ValueName)*sizeof(WCHAR));
2653 
2654  //
2655  // Now round up to a natural alignment. This needs to be done because our
2656  // data member will naturally aligned as well.
2657  //
2658  guessSize = (ULONG) ALIGN_POINTER_OFFSET(guessSize);
2659 
2660  //
2661  // Set the data cache length to a ULONG's worth of data, because most data
2662  // we read via this function is type REG_DWORD.
2663  //
2664  guessSize += sizeof(ULONG);
2665 
2666  infoBuffer = ExAllocatePool(NonPagedPool, guessSize);
2667  if (!infoBuffer) {
2668  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
2669  }
2670 
2671  //
2672  // Figure out how big the data value is so that a buffer of the
2673  // appropriate size can be allocated.
2674  //
2675 
2676  status = ZwQueryValueKey( KeyHandle,
2677  &unicodeString,
2678  KeyValueFullInformation,
2679  (PVOID) infoBuffer,
2680  guessSize,
2681  &keyValueLength );
2682  if (NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
2683 
2684  //
2685  // First guess worked, bail!
2686  //
2687  *Information = infoBuffer;
2688  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
2689  }
2690 
2691  ExFreePool(infoBuffer);
2692  if (status != STATUS_BUFFER_OVERFLOW &&
2693  status != STATUS_BUFFER_TOO_SMALL) {
2694 
2695  ASSERT(!NT_SUCCESS(status));
2696  return status;
2697  }
2698 
2699  //
2700  // Allocate a buffer large enough to contain the entire key data value.
2701  //
2702 
2703  infoBuffer = ExAllocatePool( NonPagedPool, keyValueLength );
2704  if (!infoBuffer) {
2705  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
2706  }
2707 
2708  //
2709  // Query the data for the key value.
2710  //
2711 
2712  status = ZwQueryValueKey( KeyHandle,
2713  &unicodeString,
2714  KeyValueFullInformation,
2715  infoBuffer,
2716  keyValueLength,
2717  &keyValueLength );
2718  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
2719  ExFreePool( infoBuffer );
2720  return status;
2721  }
2722 
2723  //
2724  // Everything worked, so simply return the address of the allocated
2725  // buffer to the caller, who is now responsible for freeing it.
2726  //
2727 
2728  *Information = infoBuffer;
2729  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
2730 }
2731 
2732 NTSTATUS
2733 IopGetRegistryValues(
2734  IN HANDLE KeyHandle,
2735  IN PKEY_VALUE_FULL_INFORMATION *ValueList
2736  )
2737 
2738 /*++
2739 
2740 Routine Description:
2741 
2742  This routine is invoked to retrieve the *three* types of data for a
2743  registry key's. This is done by calling the IopGetRegistryValue function
2744  with the three valid key names.
2745 
2746  It is the responsibility of the caller to free the three buffers.
2747 
2748 Arguments:
2749 
2750  KeyHandle - Supplies the key handle whose value is to be queried
2751 
2752  ValueList - Pointer to a buffer in which the three pointers to the value
2753  entries will be stored.
2754 
2755 Return Value:
2756 
2757  The function value is the final status of the query operation.
2758 
2759 Note:
2760 
2761  The values are stored in the order represented by the I/O query device
2762  data format.
2763 
2764 --*/
2765 
2766 {
2767  NTSTATUS status;
2768 
2769  PAGED_CODE();
2770 
2771  //
2772  // Zero out all entries initially.
2773  //
2774 
2775  *ValueList = NULL;
2776  *(ValueList + 1) = NULL;
2777  *(ValueList + 2) = NULL;
2778 
2779  //
2780  // Get the information for each of the three types of entries available.
2781  // Each time, check if an internal error occurred; If the object name was
2782  // not found, it only means not data was present, and this does not
2783  // constitute an error.
2784  //
2785 
2786  status = IopGetRegistryValue( KeyHandle,
2787  L"Identifier",
2788  ValueList );
2789 
2790  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status ) && (status != STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_NOT_FOUND)) {
2791  return status;
2792  }
2793 
2794  status = IopGetRegistryValue( KeyHandle,
2795  L"Configuration Data",
2796  ++ValueList );
2797 
2798  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status ) && (status != STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_NOT_FOUND)) {
2799  return status;
2800  }
2801 
2802  status = IopGetRegistryValue( KeyHandle,
2803  L"Component Information",
2804  ++ValueList );
2805 
2806  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status ) && (status != STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_NOT_FOUND)) {
2807  return status;
2808  }
2809 
2810  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
2811 }

2813 NTSTATUS
2814 IopGetSetObjectId(
2815  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
2816  IN OUT PVOID Buffer,
2817  IN ULONG Length,
2818  IN ULONG Function
2819  )
2820 
2821 /*++
2822 
2823 Routine Description:
2824 
2825  This routine is invoked to obtain or set the object ID for a file. If
2826  one does not exist for the file, then one is created, provided that the
2827  underlying file system supports object IDs in the first place (query).
2828 
2829 Arguments:
2830 
2831  FileObject - Supplies a pointer to the referenced file object whose ID is
2832  to be returned or set.
2833 
2834  Buffer - A variable to receive the object ID of the file (query) or that
2835  contains the object ID that is to be set on the file.
2836 
2837  Length - The length of the Buffer.
2838 
2839  Function - The FSCTL to send.
2840  FSCTL_LMR_GET_LINK_TRACKING_INFORMATION;
2841  FSCTL_CREATE_OR_GET_OBJECT_ID;
2842  FSCTL_GET_OBJECT_ID;
2843  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID_EXTENDED;
2844  FSCTL_LMR_SET_LINK_TRACKING_INFORMATION;
2845  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID_EXTENDED;
2846  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID;
2847  FSCTL_DELETE_OBJECT_ID;
2848 
2849 Return Value:
2850 
2851  The status returned is the final completion status of the operation.
2852 
2853 --*/
2854 
2855 {
2856  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
2857  NTSTATUS status;
2858  PIRP irp;
2859  KEVENT event;
2860  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
2861  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
2862 
2863  PAGED_CODE();
2864 
2865  //
2866  // Initialize the event structure to synchronize completion of the I/O
2867  // request.
2868  //
2869 
2870  KeInitializeEvent( &event,
2871  NotificationEvent,
2872  FALSE );
2873 
2874  //
2875  // Build an I/O Request Packet to be sent to the file system driver to get
2876  // the object ID.
2877  //
2878 
2879  deviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( FileObject );
2880 
2881  irp = IoBuildDeviceIoControlRequest( Function,
2882  deviceObject,
2883  NULL,
2884  0,
2885  NULL,
2886  0,
2887  FALSE,
2888  &event,
2889  &ioStatus );
2890  if (!irp) {
2891  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
2892  }
2893 
2894  //
2895  // Fill in the remainder of the IRP to retrieve the object ID for the
2896  // file.
2897  //
2898 
2899  irp->Flags |= IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API;
2900  irp->UserBuffer = Buffer;
2901  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer = Buffer;
2902  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = FileObject;
2903 
2904  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
2905  irpSp->FileObject = FileObject;
2906  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL;
2907  irpSp->MinorFunction = IRP_MN_KERNEL_CALL;
2908 
2909  if (Function == FSCTL_LMR_GET_LINK_TRACKING_INFORMATION ||
2910  Function == FSCTL_CREATE_OR_GET_OBJECT_ID ||
2911  Function == FSCTL_GET_OBJECT_ID ) {
2912  irpSp->Parameters.FileSystemControl.OutputBufferLength = Length;
2913  } else {
2914  irpSp->Parameters.FileSystemControl.InputBufferLength = Length;
2915  }
2916 
2917  //
2918  // Take out another reference to the file object to guarantee that it does
2919  // not get deleted.
2920  //
2921 
2922  ObReferenceObject( FileObject );
2923 
2924  //
2925  // Call the driver to get the request.
2926  //
2927 
2928  status = IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp );
2929 
2930  //
2931  // Synchronize completion of the request.
2932  //
2933 
2934  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
2935  status = KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
2936  Executive,
2937  KernelMode,
2938  FALSE,
2939  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
2940  status = ioStatus.Status;
2941  }
2942 
2943  return status;
2944 }
