2946 NTSTATUS
2947 IopGetVolumeId(
2948  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
2949  IN OUT PFILE_VOLUMEID_WITH_TYPE ObjectId,
2950  IN ULONG Length
2951  )
2952 
2953 /*++
2954 
2955 Routine Description:
2956 
2957  This routine is invoked by the I/O System link tracking code to obtain the
2958  volume ID for a file that has been moved or is being moved between volumes
2959  and potentially between systems.
2960 
2961 Arguments:
2962 
2963  FileObject - Supplies the file object for the file.
2964 
2965  ObjectId - A buffer to receive the volume object ID.
2966 
2967  Length - Length of the buffer.
2968 
2969 Return Value:
2970 
2971  The final function value is the final completion status of the operation.
2972 
2973 --*/
2974 
2975 {
2976  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
2977  NTSTATUS status;
2978  PIRP irp;
2979  KEVENT event;
2980  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
2981  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
2982  FILE_FS_OBJECTID_INFORMATION volumeId;
2983 
2984  PAGED_CODE();
2985 
2986 #if !DBG
2987  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (Length);
2988 #endif
2989 
2990  ASSERT (Length >= sizeof(GUID));
2991 
2992  //
2993  // Initialize the event structure to synchronize completion of the I/O
2994  // request.
2995  //
2996 
2997  KeInitializeEvent( &event,
2998  NotificationEvent,
2999  FALSE );
3000 
3001  //
3002  // Build an I/O Request Packet to be sent to the file system driver to get
3003  // the volume ID.
3004  //
3005 
3006  deviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( FileObject );
3007 
3008  irp = IoBuildDeviceIoControlRequest( 0,
3009  deviceObject,
3010  NULL,
3011  0,
3012  NULL,
3013  0,
3014  FALSE,
3015  &event,
3016  &ioStatus );
3017  if (!irp) {
3018  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
3019  }
3020 
3021  //
3022  // Fill in the remainder of the IRP to retrieve the volume ID for the
3023  // file.
3024  //
3025 
3026  irp->Flags |= IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API;
3027  irp->UserBuffer = &volumeId;
3028  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer = &volumeId;
3029  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = FileObject;
3030 
3031  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
3032  irpSp->FileObject = FileObject;
3033  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_QUERY_VOLUME_INFORMATION;
3034  irpSp->Parameters.QueryVolume.Length = sizeof( volumeId );
3035  irpSp->Parameters.QueryVolume.FsInformationClass = FileFsObjectIdInformation;
3036 
3037  //
3038  // Take out another reference to the file object to guarantee that it does
3039  // not get deleted.
3040  //
3041 
3042  ObReferenceObject( FileObject );
3043 
3044  //
3045  // Call the driver to get the request.
3046  //
3047 
3048  status = IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp );
3049 
3050  //
3051  // Synchronize completion of the request.
3052  //
3053 
3054  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
3055  status = KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
3056  Executive,
3057  KernelMode,
3058  FALSE,
3059  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
3060  status = ioStatus.Status;
3061  }
3062 
3063  //
3064  // If the file system returned the volume ID, copy it to the caller's
3065  // buffer and set the file system tracking type.
3066  //
3067 
3068  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
3069  ObjectId->Type = NtfsLinkTrackingInformation;
3070  RtlCopyMemory( ObjectId->VolumeId,
3071  &volumeId.ObjectId,
3072  sizeof( GUID ) );
3073  }
3074 
3075  return status;
3076 }

3078 PIOP_HARD_ERROR_PACKET
3079 IopRemoveHardErrorPacket(
3080  VOID
3081  )
3082 {
3083  PIOP_HARD_ERROR_PACKET hardErrorPacket;
3084  KIRQL oldIrql;
3085  PVOID entry;
3086 
3087 #if !DBG && defined(NT_UP)
3088  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (oldIrql);
3089 #endif
3090 
3091  ExAcquireFastLock( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSpinLock, &oldIrql );
3092 
3093  //
3094  // The work queue structures are now exclusively owned, so remove the
3095  // first packet from the head of the list.
3096  //
3097 
3098  entry = RemoveHeadList( &IopHardError.WorkQueue );
3099 
3100  hardErrorPacket = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry,
3101  IOP_HARD_ERROR_PACKET,
3102  WorkQueueLinks );
3103 
3104  IopCurrentHardError = hardErrorPacket;
3105 
3106  ExReleaseFastLock( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSpinLock, oldIrql );
3107 
3108  return hardErrorPacket;
3109 }
3110 
3111 BOOLEAN
3112 IopCheckHardErrorEmpty(
3113  VOID
3114  )
3115 {
3116  BOOLEAN MoreEntries;
3117  KIRQL oldIrql;
3118 
3119 #if !DBG && defined(NT_UP)
3120  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (oldIrql);
3121 #endif
3122 
3123  MoreEntries = TRUE;
3124 
3125  ExAcquireFastLock( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSpinLock, &oldIrql );
3126 
3127  IopCurrentHardError = NULL;
3128 
3129  if ( IsListEmpty( &IopHardError.WorkQueue ) ) {
3130  IopHardError.ThreadStarted = FALSE;
3131  MoreEntries = FALSE;
3132  }
3133 
3134  ExReleaseFastLock( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSpinLock, oldIrql );
3135 
3136  return MoreEntries;
3137 }
3138 
3139 VOID
3140 IopHardErrorThread(
3141  IN PVOID StartContext
3142  )
3143 
3144 /*++
3145 
3146 Routine Description:
3147 
3148  This function waits for work on the IopHardErrorQueue, and all calls
3149  IopRaiseInformationalHardError to actually perform the pop-ups.
3150 
3151 Arguments:
3152 
3153  StartContext - Startup context; not used.
3154 
3155 Return Value:
3156 
3157  None.
3158 
3159 --*/
3160 
3161 {
3162  ULONG parameterPresent;
3163  ULONG_PTR errorParameter;
3164  ULONG errorResponse;
3165  BOOLEAN MoreEntries;
3166  PIOP_HARD_ERROR_PACKET hardErrorPacket;
3167 
3168  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( StartContext );
3169 
3170  PAGED_CODE();
3171  //
3172  // Loop, waiting forever for a hard error packet to be sent to this thread.
3173  // When one is placed onto the queue, wake up, process it, and continue
3174  // the loop.
3175  //
3176 
3177  MoreEntries = TRUE;
3178 
3179  do {
3180 
3181  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &IopHardError.WorkQueueSemaphore,
3182  Executive,
3183  KernelMode,
3184  FALSE,
3185  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
3186 
3187  hardErrorPacket = IopRemoveHardErrorPacket();
3188 
3189 
3190  //
3191  // Simply raise the hard error if the system is ready to accept one.
3192  //
3193 
3194  errorParameter = (ULONG_PTR) &hardErrorPacket->String;
3195  parameterPresent = (hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer != NULL);
3196 
3197  if (ExReadyForErrors) {
3198  (VOID) ExRaiseHardError( hardErrorPacket->ErrorStatus,
3199  parameterPresent,
3200  parameterPresent,
3201  parameterPresent ? &errorParameter : NULL,
3202  OptionOkNoWait,
3203  &errorResponse );
3204  }
3205 
3206  //
3207  // If this was the last entry, exit the thread and mark it as so.
3208  //
3209 
3210  MoreEntries = IopCheckHardErrorEmpty();
3211 
3212  //
3213  // Now free the packet and the buffer, if one was specified.
3214  //
3215 
3216  if (hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer) {
3217  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer );
3218  }
3219 
3220  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket );
3221 
3222  } while ( MoreEntries );
3223 }

3226 NTSTATUS
3227 IopInvalidDeviceRequest(
3228  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
3229  IN PIRP Irp
3230  )
3231 
3232 /*++
3233 
3234 Routine Description:
3235 
3236  This function is the default dispatch routine for all driver entries
3237  not implemented by drivers that have been loaded into the system. Its
3238  responsibility is simply to set the status in the packet to indicate
3239  that the operation requested is invalid for this device type, and then
3240  complete the packet.
3241 
3242 Arguments:
3243 
3244  DeviceObject - Specifies the device object for which this request is
3245  bound. Ignored by this routine.
3246 
3247  Irp - Specifies the address of the I/O Request Packet (IRP) for this
3248  request.
3249 
3250 Return Value:
3251 
3252  The final status is always STATUS_INVALID_DEVICE_REQUEST.
3253 
3254 
3255 --*/
3256 
3257 {
3258  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( DeviceObject );
3259 
3260  //
3261  // Simply store the appropriate status, complete the request, and return
3262  // the same status stored in the packet.
3263  //
3264 
3265  if ((IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation(Irp))->MajorFunction == IRP_MJ_POWER) {
3266  PoStartNextPowerIrp(Irp);
3267  }
3268  Irp->IoStatus.Status = STATUS_INVALID_DEVICE_REQUEST;
3269  IoCompleteRequest( Irp, IO_NO_INCREMENT );
3270  return STATUS_INVALID_DEVICE_REQUEST;

3272 
3273 LOGICAL
3274 IopIsSameMachine(
3275  IN PFILE_OBJECT SourceFile,
3276  IN HANDLE TargetFile
3277  )
3278 
3279 /*++
3280 
3281 Routine Description:
3282 
3283  This routine is invoked to determine whether two file objects that represent
3284  files on remote machines actually reside on the same physical system.
3285 
3286 Arguments:
3287 
3288  SourceFile - Supplies the file object for the first file.
3289 
3290  TargetFile - Supplies the file object for the second file.
3291 
3292 Return Value:
3293 
3294  The final function value is TRUE if the files reside on the same machine,
3295  otherwise FALSE is returned.
3296 
3297 --*/
3298 
3299 {
3300  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
3301  PFAST_IO_DISPATCH fastIoDispatch;
3302  NTSTATUS status = STATUS_NOT_SAME_DEVICE;
3303  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
3304  HANDLE target = TargetFile;
3305 
3306  PAGED_CODE();
3307 
3308  //
3309  // Simply invoke the device I/O control function to determine whether or
3310  // not the two files are on the same server. If the fast I/O path does
3311  // not exist, or the function fails for any reason, then the two files are
3312  // assumed to not be on the same machine. Note that this simply means
3313  // that there will be a performance penalty on open of the target, but
3314  // the above will only fail if the two files really aren't on the same
3315  // machine in the first place, or if there's a filter that doesn't under-
3316  // stand what is being done here.
3317  //
3318 
3319  deviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( SourceFile );
3320 
3321  fastIoDispatch = deviceObject->DriverObject->FastIoDispatch;
3322  if (fastIoDispatch && fastIoDispatch->FastIoDeviceControl) {
3323  if (fastIoDispatch->FastIoDeviceControl( SourceFile,
3324  TRUE,
3325  (PVOID) &target,
3326  sizeof( target ),
3327  (PVOID) NULL,
3328  0,
3329  IOCTL_LMR_ARE_FILE_OBJECTS_ON_SAME_SERVER,
3330  &ioStatus,
3331  deviceObject )) {
3332  status = ioStatus.Status;
3333  }
3334  }
3335 
3336  return status == STATUS_SUCCESS;
3337 }

3339 NTSTATUS
3340 IopBuildFullDriverPath(
3341  IN PUNICODE_STRING KeyName,
3342  IN HANDLE KeyHandle,
3343  OUT PUNICODE_STRING FullPath
3344  )
3345 /*++
3346 
3347 Routine Description:
3348 
3349  This routine builds up the full path for the driver. If ImagePath is
3350  specified, use it or else prepend the standard drivers path.
3351 
3352 Arguments:
3353 
3354  KeyHandle - Supplies a handle to the driver service node in the registry
3355  that describes the driver to be loaded.
3356 
3357  CheckForSafeBoot - If TRUE, the driver will be loaded only if it belongs
3358  to the list of safe mode OK binaries.
3359 
3360  FullPath - Full driver path is returned in this.
3361 
3362 Return Value:
3363 
3364  STATUS_SUCCESS or STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES.
3365 
3366 --*/
3367 {
3368  NTSTATUS status;
3369  PWCHAR path, name, ext;
3370  ULONG pathLength, nameLength, extLength;
3371  PKEY_VALUE_FULL_INFORMATION keyValueInformation;
3372 
3373  FullPath->Length = FullPath->MaximumLength = 0;
3374  FullPath->Buffer = NULL;
3375  extLength = nameLength = pathLength = 0;
3376  keyValueInformation = NULL;
3377  status = IopGetRegistryValue( KeyHandle,
3378  L"ImagePath",
3379  &keyValueInformation);
3380  if (NT_SUCCESS(status) && keyValueInformation->DataLength) {
3381 
3382  nameLength = keyValueInformation->DataLength - sizeof(WCHAR);
3383  name = (PWCHAR)KEY_VALUE_DATA(keyValueInformation);
3384  if (name[0] != L'\\') {
3385 
3386  path = L"\\SystemRoot\\";
3387  pathLength = sizeof(L"\\SystemRoot\\") - sizeof(UNICODE_NULL);
3388  }
3389  else {
3390  path = NULL;
3391  }
3392  ext = NULL;
3393  } else {
3394 
3395  nameLength = KeyName->Length;
3396  name = KeyName->Buffer;
3397  pathLength = sizeof(L"\\SystemRoot\\System32\\Drivers\\") - sizeof(UNICODE_NULL);
3398  path = L"\\SystemRoot\\System32\\Drivers\\";
3399  extLength = sizeof(L".SYS") - sizeof(UNICODE_NULL);
3400  ext = L".SYS";
3401  }
3402  //
3403  // Allocate storage for the full path.
3404  //
3405  FullPath->MaximumLength = (USHORT)(pathLength + nameLength + extLength + sizeof(UNICODE_NULL));
3406  FullPath->Buffer = ExAllocatePool(PagedPool, FullPath->MaximumLength);
3407  if (FullPath->Buffer) {
3408 
3409  FullPath->Length = FullPath->MaximumLength - sizeof(UNICODE_NULL);
3410  //
3411  // Create the full path by combining path, name and ext.
3412  //
3413  if (path) {
3414 
3415  RtlCopyMemory(FullPath->Buffer, path, pathLength);
3416  }
3417  if (nameLength) {
3418 
3419  RtlCopyMemory((PUCHAR)FullPath->Buffer + pathLength, name, nameLength);
3420  }
3421  if (extLength) {
3422 
3423  RtlCopyMemory((PUCHAR)FullPath->Buffer + pathLength + nameLength, ext, extLength);
3424  }
3425  //
3426  // NULL terminate the full path.
3427  //
3428  FullPath->Buffer[FullPath->Length / sizeof(WCHAR)] = UNICODE_NULL;
3429  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
3430 
3431  } else {
3432 
3433  FullPath->MaximumLength = 0;
3434  status = STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
3435  }
3436  //
3437  // Clean up on the way out.
3438  //
3439  if (keyValueInformation) {
3440 
3441  ExFreePool(keyValueInformation);
3442  }
3443 
3444  return status;
3445 }
3446 
3447 #if defined(_WIN64)
3448 
3449 #define SYSTEM32_DRIVERS_DIR (L"\\System32\\drivers\\")
3450 #define SYSTEM32_DRIVERS_DIR_LEN ((sizeof (SYSTEM32_DRIVERS_DIR) / sizeof (WCHAR)) - 1)

3452 BOOLEAN
3453 IopIsNotNativeDriverImage(
3454  IN PUNICODE_STRING ImageFileName
3455  )
3456 
3457 /*++
3458 
3459 Routine Description:
3460 
3461  This routine reads checks if the file is not a native driver image.
3462 
3463 Arguments:
3464 
3465  ImageFileName - Full qualified path name to the driver.
3466 
3467 Return Value:
3468 
3469  BOOLEAN. Returns TRUE if the image is not native.
3470 --*/
3471 {
3472  HANDLE ImageFileHandle;
3473  IO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatus;
3474  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES ObjectAttributes;
3475  HANDLE Section;
3476  PVOID ViewBase;
3477  SIZE_T ViewSize;
3478  KAPC_STATE ApcState;
3479  PIMAGE_NT_HEADERS NtHeaders;
3480  NTSTATUS Status;
3481  BOOLEAN RetValue;
3482 
3483 
3484  RetValue = FALSE;
3485 
3486  //
3487  // Attempt to open the driver image itself. If this fails, then the
3488  // driver image cannot be located, so nothing else matters.
3489  //
3490 
3491  InitializeObjectAttributes (&ObjectAttributes,
3492  ImageFileName,
3493  (OBJ_CASE_INSENSITIVE | OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE),
3494  NULL,
3495  NULL);
3496 
3497  Status = ZwOpenFile (&ImageFileHandle,
3498  FILE_EXECUTE,
3499  &ObjectAttributes,
3500  &IoStatus,
3501  FILE_SHARE_READ | FILE_SHARE_DELETE,
3502  0);
3503 
3504  if (!NT_SUCCESS (Status)) {
3505  return RetValue;
3506  }
3507 
3508  InitializeObjectAttributes (&ObjectAttributes,
3509  NULL,
3510  (OBJ_CASE_INSENSITIVE | OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE),
3511  NULL,
3512  NULL);
3513 
3514  Status = ZwCreateSection (&Section,
3515  SECTION_MAP_EXECUTE,
3516  &ObjectAttributes,
3517  NULL,
3518  PAGE_EXECUTE,
3519  SEC_COMMIT,
3520  ImageFileHandle);
3521 
3522  if (!NT_SUCCESS (Status)) {
3523  ZwClose (ImageFileHandle);
3524  return RetValue;
3525  }
3526 
3527  ViewBase = NULL;
3528  ViewSize = 0;
3529 
3530  //
3531  // Since callees are not always in the context of the system process,
3532  // attach here when necessary to guarantee the driver load occurs in a
3533  // known safe address space to prevent security holes.
3534  //
3535 
3536  KeStackAttachProcess (&PsInitialSystemProcess->Pcb, &ApcState);
3537 
3538  Status = ZwMapViewOfSection (Section,
3539  NtCurrentProcess (),
3540  (PVOID *)&ViewBase,
3541  0L,
3542  0L,
3543  NULL,
3544  &ViewSize,
3545  ViewShare,
3546  0L,
3547  PAGE_EXECUTE);
3548 
3549  if (!NT_SUCCESS(Status)) {
3550  KeUnstackDetachProcess (&ApcState);
3551  ZwClose (Section);
3552  ZwClose (ImageFileHandle);
3553  return RetValue;
3554  }
3555 
3556  try {
3557  NtHeaders = RtlImageNtHeader (ViewBase);
3558  if (NtHeaders != NULL) {
3559  if (NtHeaders->FileHeader.Machine != IMAGE_FILE_MACHINE_NATIVE) {
3560  RetValue = TRUE;
3561  }
3562  }
3563  } except (EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
3564  NOTHING;
3565  }
3566 
3567 
3568  ZwUnmapViewOfSection (NtCurrentProcess (), ViewBase);
3569 
3570  KeUnstackDetachProcess (&ApcState);
3571 
3572  ZwClose (Section);
3573 
3574  ZwClose (ImageFileHandle);
3575 
3576  return RetValue;
3577 }

3579 BOOLEAN
3580 IopCheckIfNotNativeDriver(
3581  IN NTSTATUS InitialDriverLoadStatus,
3582  IN PUNICODE_STRING ImageFileName
3583  )
3584 
3585 /*++
3586 
3587 Routine Description:
3588 
3589  This routine reads checks to see if the specified file is not a native driver image.
3590 
3591 Arguments:
3592 
3593  InitialDriverLoadStatus - NT Status code of the initial driver load failure.
3594 
3595  ImageFileName - Supplies the full path name (including the image name)
3596  of the image to load.
3597 
3598 Return Value:
3599 
3600  BOOLEAN. Returns TRUE if the driver is not native.
3601 --*/
3602 {
3603  PWCHAR System32DriversPath;
3604 
3605  //
3606  // Check to see if the driver may exist in the \SystemRoot\SysWow64 directory
3607  //
3608 
3609  System32DriversPath = ImageFileName->Buffer;
3610  if (InitialDriverLoadStatus == STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_NOT_FOUND) {
3611  while (System32DriversPath != NULL) {
3612  if (_wcsnicmp (System32DriversPath, SYSTEM32_DRIVERS_DIR, SYSTEM32_DRIVERS_DIR_LEN) == 0) {
3613  wcsncpy (System32DriversPath + 1,
3614  L"SysWow64",
3615  ((sizeof (L"SysWow64") - sizeof (UNICODE_NULL)) / sizeof (WCHAR)));
3616  break;
3617  }
3618  System32DriversPath = wcsstr ((System32DriversPath + 1), L"\\");
3619  }
3620 
3621  if (System32DriversPath == NULL) {
3622  return FALSE;
3623  }
3624  }
3625 
3626  return IopIsNotNativeDriverImage (ImageFileName);
3627 }

3688 NTSTATUS
3689 IopLoadDriver(
3690  IN HANDLE KeyHandle,
3691  IN BOOLEAN CheckForSafeBoot,
3692  IN BOOLEAN IsFilter,
3693  OUT NTSTATUS *DriverEntryStatus
3694  )
3695 /*++
3696 
3697 Routine Description:
3698 
3699  This routine is invoked to load a device or file system driver, either
3700  during system initialization, or dynamically while the system is running.
3701 
3702 Arguments:
3703 
3704  KeyHandle - Supplies a handle to the driver service node in the registry
3705  that describes the driver to be loaded.
3706 
3707  IsFilter - TRUE if the driver is a WDM filter, FALSE otherwise.
3708 
3709  CheckForSafeBoot - If TRUE, the driver will be loaded only if it belongs
3710  to the list of safe mode OK binaries.
3711 
3712  DriverEntryStatus - Receives status returned by DriverEntry(...)
3713 
3714 Return Value:
3715 
3716  The function value is the final status of the load operation. If
3717  STATUS_FAILED_DRIVER_ENTRY is returned, the driver's return value
3718  is stored in DriverEntryStatus.
3719 
3720 Notes:
3721 
3722  Note that this routine closes the KeyHandle before returning.
3723 
3724 
3725 --*/
3726 {
3727  NTSTATUS status;
3728  PLIST_ENTRY nextEntry;
3729  PKLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY driverEntry;
3730  PKEY_BASIC_INFORMATION keyBasicInformation = NULL;
3731  ULONG keyBasicLength;
3732  UNICODE_STRING baseName;
3733  UNICODE_STRING serviceName = {0, 0, NULL};
3734  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
3735  PVOID sectionPointer;
3736  UNICODE_STRING driverName;
3737  PDRIVER_OBJECT driverObject;
3738  PIMAGE_NT_HEADERS ntHeaders;
3739  PVOID imageBaseAddress;
3740  ULONG_PTR entryPoint;
3741  HANDLE driverHandle;
3742  ULONG i;
3743  POBJECT_NAME_INFORMATION registryPath;
3744 #if DBG
3745  LARGE_INTEGER stime, etime;
3746  ULONG dtime;
3747 #endif
3748 
3749  PAGED_CODE();
3750 
3751  driverName.Buffer = (PWSTR) NULL;
3752  *DriverEntryStatus = STATUS_SUCCESS;
3753  baseName.Buffer = NULL;
3754 
3755  //
3756  // Begin by formulating the name of the driver image file to be loaded.
3757  // Note that this is used to determine whether or not the driver has
3758  // already been loaded by the OS loader, not necessarily in actually
3759  // loading the driver image, since the node can override that name.
3760  //
3761 
3762  status = NtQueryKey( KeyHandle,
3763  KeyBasicInformation,
3764  (PVOID) NULL,
3765  0,
3766  &keyBasicLength );
3767  if (status != STATUS_BUFFER_OVERFLOW &&
3768  status != STATUS_BUFFER_TOO_SMALL) {
3769 
3770  status = STATUS_ILL_FORMED_SERVICE_ENTRY;
3771  goto IopLoadExit;
3772  }
3773 
3774  keyBasicInformation = ExAllocatePool( NonPagedPool,
3775  keyBasicLength + (4 * 2) );
3776  if (!keyBasicInformation) {
3777  status = STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
3778  goto IopLoadExit;
3779  }
3780 
3781  status = NtQueryKey( KeyHandle,
3782  KeyBasicInformation,
3783  keyBasicInformation,
3784  keyBasicLength,
3785  &keyBasicLength );
3786  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
3787  goto IopLoadExit;
3788  }
3789 
3790  //
3791  // Create a Unicode string descriptor which forms the name of the
3792  // driver.
3793  //
3794 
3795  baseName.Length = (USHORT) keyBasicInformation->NameLength;
3796  baseName.MaximumLength = (USHORT) (baseName.Length + (4 * 2));
3797  baseName.Buffer = &keyBasicInformation->Name[0];
3798 
3799  serviceName.Buffer = ExAllocatePool(PagedPool, baseName.Length + sizeof(UNICODE_NULL));
3800  if (serviceName.Buffer) {
3801  serviceName.Length = baseName.Length;
3802  serviceName.MaximumLength = serviceName.Length + sizeof(UNICODE_NULL);
3803  RtlCopyMemory(serviceName.Buffer, baseName.Buffer, baseName.Length);
3804  serviceName.Buffer[serviceName.Length / sizeof(WCHAR)] = UNICODE_NULL;
3805  } else {
3806  status = STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
3807  goto IopLoadExit;
3808  }
3809 
3810  RtlAppendUnicodeToString( &baseName, L".SYS" );
3811 
3812  //
3813  // Log the file name
3814  //
3815  HeadlessKernelAddLogEntry(HEADLESS_LOG_LOADING_FILENAME, &baseName);
3816 
3817  if (CheckForSafeBoot && InitSafeBootMode) {
3818 
3819  BOOLEAN GroupIsGood = FALSE;
3820  UNICODE_STRING string;
3821  PKEY_VALUE_PARTIAL_INFORMATION keyValue;
3822  UCHAR nameBuffer[FIELD_OFFSET(KEY_VALUE_PARTIAL_INFORMATION, Data) + 64];
3823  ULONG length;
3824 
3825  RtlInitUnicodeString( &string, L"Group" );
3826  keyValue = (PKEY_VALUE_PARTIAL_INFORMATION)nameBuffer;
3827  RtlZeroMemory(nameBuffer, sizeof(nameBuffer));
3828 
3829  status = NtQueryValueKey(
3830  KeyHandle,
3831  &string,
3832  KeyValuePartialInformation,
3833  keyValue,
3834  sizeof(nameBuffer),
3835  &length
3836  );
3837  if (NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
3838 
3839  string.Length = (USHORT)(keyValue->DataLength - sizeof(WCHAR));
3840  string.MaximumLength = string.Length;
3841  string.Buffer = (PWSTR)keyValue->Data;
3842 
3843  if (IopSafebootDriverLoad(&string)) {
3844  GroupIsGood = TRUE;
3845  }
3846  }
3847 
3848  if (!GroupIsGood && !IopSafebootDriverLoad(&baseName)) {
3849  //
3850  // don't load the driver
3851  //
3852 
3853  IopBootLog(&baseName, FALSE);
3854 
3855  DbgPrint("SAFEBOOT: skipping device = %wZ(%wZ)\n",&baseName,&string);
3856  HeadlessKernelAddLogEntry(HEADLESS_LOG_LOAD_SUCCESSFUL, NULL);
3857  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
3858  }
3859 
3860  }
3861 
3862  //
3863  // See if this driver has already been loaded by the boot loader.
3864  //
3865 
3866  //
3867  // No need to do KeEnterCriticalRegion as this is called
3868  // from system process only.
3869  //
3870  ExAcquireResourceSharedLite( &PsLoadedModuleResource, TRUE );
3871  nextEntry = PsLoadedModuleList.Flink;
3872  while (nextEntry != &PsLoadedModuleList) {
3873 
3874  //
3875  // Look at the next boot driver in the list.
3876  //
3877 
3878  driverEntry = CONTAINING_RECORD( nextEntry,
3879  KLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY,
3880  InLoadOrderLinks );
3881 
3882  //
3883  // If this is not the kernel image (ntoskrnl) and not the HAL (hal),
3884  // then this is a driver, so initialize it.
3885  //
3886 
3887  if (RtlEqualUnicodeString( &baseName,
3888  &driverEntry->FullDllName,
3889  TRUE )) {
3890 
3891  status = STATUS_IMAGE_ALREADY_LOADED;
3892  ExReleaseResourceLite( &PsLoadedModuleResource );
3893 
3894  IopBootLog(&baseName, TRUE);
3895  baseName.Buffer = NULL;
3896  goto IopLoadExit;
3897  }
3898 
3899  nextEntry = nextEntry->Flink;
3900  }
3901  ExReleaseResourceLite( &PsLoadedModuleResource );
3902 
3903  //
3904  // This driver has not already been loaded by the OS loader. Form the
3905  // full path name for this driver.
3906  //
3907 
3908  status = IopBuildFullDriverPath(&serviceName, KeyHandle, &baseName);
3909  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
3910 
3911  baseName.Buffer = NULL;
3912  goto IopLoadExit;
3913  }
3914 
3915  //
3916  // Now get the name of the driver object.
3917  //
3918 
3919  status = IopGetDriverNameFromKeyNode( KeyHandle,
3920  &driverName );
3921  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
3922  goto IopLoadExit;
3923  }
3924 
3925  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
3926  &driverName,
3927  OBJ_PERMANENT,
3928  (HANDLE) NULL,
3929  (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL );
3930 
3931  //
3932  // Load the driver image into memory. If this fails partway through
3933  // the operation, then it will automatically be unloaded.
3934  //
3935 
3936  //
3937  // No need to do KeEnterCriticalRegion here as this is only
3938  // called from system process
3939  //
3940  ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite( &IopDriverLoadResource, TRUE );
3941 
3942  status = MmLoadSystemImage( &baseName,
3943  NULL,
3944  NULL,
3945  0,
3946  &sectionPointer,
3947  (PVOID *) &imageBaseAddress );
3948 
3949  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
3950 
3951 
3952  //
3953  // If the image was not already loaded then exit.
3954  //
3955 
3956  if (status != STATUS_IMAGE_ALREADY_LOADED) {
3957 
3958 #if defined(_WIN64)
3959  //
3960  // If this is a driver meant for another architecture, then block this driver
3961  // and continue with loading the rest of the drivers stack.
3962  //
3963 
3964  if (IopCheckIfNotNativeDriver (status, &baseName) == TRUE) {
3965 
3966  if (IsFilter != FALSE) {
3967  status = STATUS_DRIVER_BLOCKED;
3968  } else {
3969  status = STATUS_DRIVER_BLOCKED_CRITICAL;
3970  }
3971 #if DBG
3972  DbgPrint ("IopLoadDriver - Blocking driver %ws (32-bit) - Status = %lx\n",
3973  baseName.Buffer, status);
3974 #endif
3975 
3976  //
3977  // Log an event to the eventlog
3978  //
3979 
3980  IopLogBlockedDriverEvent (&baseName, STATUS_INCOMPATIBLE_DRIVER_BLOCKED, status);
3981  }
3982 #endif
3983 
3984 
3985  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDriverLoadResource );
3986  IopBootLog(&baseName, FALSE);
3987 
3988  goto IopLoadExit;
3989  }
3990 
3991  //
3992  // Open the driver object.
3993  //
3994 
3995  status = ObOpenObjectByName( &objectAttributes,
3996  IoDriverObjectType,
3997  KernelMode,
3998  NULL,
3999  0,
4000  NULL,
4001  &driverHandle );
4002 
4003 
4004  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
4005 
4006  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDriverLoadResource );
4007  IopBootLog(&baseName, FALSE);
4008 
4009  if (status == STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_NOT_FOUND) {
4010 
4011  //
4012  // Adjust the exit code so that we can distinguish drivers that
4013  // aren't present from drivers that are present but have had
4014  // their driver objects made temporary.
4015  //
4016  status = STATUS_DRIVER_FAILED_PRIOR_UNLOAD;
4017  }
4018 
4019  goto IopLoadExit;
4020  }
4021 
4022  //
4023  // Reference the handle and obtain a pointer to the driver object so that
4024  // the handle can be deleted without the object going away.
4025  //
4026 
4027  status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle( driverHandle,
4028  0,
4029  IoDriverObjectType,
4030  KeGetPreviousMode(),
4031  (PVOID *) &driverObject,
4032  (POBJECT_HANDLE_INFORMATION) NULL );
4033  NtClose( driverHandle );
4034 
4035  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
4036  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDriverLoadResource );
4037  IopBootLog(&baseName, FALSE);
4038  goto IopLoadExit;
4039  }
4040 
4041 
4042  status = IopResurrectDriver( driverObject );
4043 
4044  //
4045  // Regardless of the status the driver object should be dereferenced.
4046  // if the unload has already run then driver is almost gone. If
4047  // the driver has been resurrected then the I/O system still has its
4048  // original reference.
4049  //
4050 
4051  ObDereferenceObject( driverObject );
4052  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDriverLoadResource );
4053  IopBootLog(&baseName, FALSE);
4054  goto IopLoadExit;
4055  } else {
4056 
4057  ntHeaders = RtlImageNtHeader( imageBaseAddress );
4058 
4059  //
4060  // Check should this driver be loaded. If yes, the enum subkey
4061  // of the service will be prepared.
4062  //
4063 
4064  status = IopPrepareDriverLoading (&serviceName, KeyHandle, imageBaseAddress, IsFilter);
4065  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
4066  MmUnloadSystemImage(sectionPointer);
4067  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDriverLoadResource );
4068  IopBootLog(&baseName, FALSE);
4069  goto IopLoadExit;
4070  }
4071 
4072  }
4073 
4074  //
4075  // The driver image has now been loaded into memory. Create the driver
4076  // object that represents this image.
4077  //
4078 
4079  status = ObCreateObject( KeGetPreviousMode(),
4080  IoDriverObjectType,
4081  &objectAttributes,
4082  KernelMode,
4083  (PVOID) NULL,
4084  (ULONG) (sizeof( DRIVER_OBJECT ) + sizeof ( DRIVER_EXTENSION )),
4085  0,
4086  0,
4087  (PVOID *) &driverObject );
4088 
4089  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
4090  MmUnloadSystemImage(sectionPointer);
4091  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDriverLoadResource );
4092  IopBootLog(&baseName, FALSE);
4093  goto IopLoadExit;
4094  }
4095 
4096  //
4097  // Initialize this driver object and insert it into the object table.
4098  //
4099 
4100  RtlZeroMemory( driverObject, sizeof( DRIVER_OBJECT ) + sizeof ( DRIVER_EXTENSION) );
4101  driverObject->DriverExtension = (PDRIVER_EXTENSION) (driverObject + 1);
4102  driverObject->DriverExtension->DriverObject = driverObject;
4103 
4104  for (i = 0; i <= IRP_MJ_MAXIMUM_FUNCTION; i++) {
4105  driverObject->MajorFunction[i] = IopInvalidDeviceRequest;
4106  }
4107 
4108  driverObject->Type = IO_TYPE_DRIVER;
4109  driverObject->Size = sizeof( DRIVER_OBJECT );
4110  ntHeaders = RtlImageNtHeader( imageBaseAddress );
4111  entryPoint = ntHeaders->OptionalHeader.AddressOfEntryPoint;
4112  entryPoint += (ULONG_PTR) imageBaseAddress;
4113  if (!(ntHeaders->OptionalHeader.DllCharacteristics & IMAGE_DLLCHARACTERISTICS_WDM_DRIVER)) {
4114  driverObject->Flags |= DRVO_LEGACY_DRIVER;
4115  }
4116  driverObject->DriverInit = (PDRIVER_INITIALIZE) entryPoint;
4117  driverObject->DriverSection = sectionPointer;
4118  driverObject->DriverStart = imageBaseAddress;
4119  driverObject->DriverSize = ntHeaders->OptionalHeader.SizeOfImage;
4120 
4121  status = ObInsertObject( driverObject,
4122  (PACCESS_STATE) NULL,
4123  FILE_READ_DATA,
4124  0,
4125  (PVOID *) NULL,
4126  &driverHandle );
4127 
4128  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDriverLoadResource );
4129 
4130  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
4131  IopBootLog(&baseName, FALSE);
4132  goto IopLoadExit;
4133  }
4134 
4135  //
4136  // Reference the handle and obtain a pointer to the driver object so that
4137  // the handle can be deleted without the object going away.
4138  //
4139 
4140  status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle( driverHandle,
4141  0,
4142  IoDriverObjectType,
4143  KeGetPreviousMode(),
4144  (PVOID *) &driverObject,
4145  (POBJECT_HANDLE_INFORMATION) NULL );
4146 
4147  ASSERT(status == STATUS_SUCCESS);
4148 
4149  NtClose( driverHandle );
4150 
4151  //
4152  // Load the Registry information in the appropriate fields of the device
4153  // object.
4154  //
4155 
4156  driverObject->HardwareDatabase =
4157  &CmRegistryMachineHardwareDescriptionSystemName;
4158 
4159  //
4160  // Store the name of the device driver in the driver object so that it
4161  // can be easily found by the error log thread.
4162  //
4163 
4164  driverObject->DriverName.Buffer = ExAllocatePool( PagedPool,
4165  driverName.MaximumLength );
4166  if (driverObject->DriverName.Buffer) {
4167  driverObject->DriverName.MaximumLength = driverName.MaximumLength;
4168  driverObject->DriverName.Length = driverName.Length;
4169 
4170  RtlCopyMemory( driverObject->DriverName.Buffer,
4171  driverName.Buffer,
4172  driverName.MaximumLength );
4173  }
4174 
4175  //
4176  // Query the name of the registry path for this driver so that it can
4177  // be passed to the driver.
4178  //
4179 
4180  registryPath = ExAllocatePool( NonPagedPool, PAGE_SIZE );
4181  if (!registryPath) {
4182  ObMakeTemporaryObject( driverObject );
4183  ObDereferenceObject( driverObject );
4184  status = STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
4185  goto IopLoadExit;
4186  }
4187 
4188  status = NtQueryObject( KeyHandle,
4189  ObjectNameInformation,
4190  registryPath,
4191  PAGE_SIZE,
4192  &i );
4193  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
4194  ObMakeTemporaryObject( driverObject );
4195  ObDereferenceObject( driverObject );
4196  ExFreePool( registryPath );
4197  goto IopLoadExit;
4198  }
4199 
4200 #if DBG
4201  KeQuerySystemTime (&stime);
4202 #endif
4203 
4204  //
4205  // Store the service key name of the device driver in the driver object
4206  //
4207 
4208  if (serviceName.Buffer) {
4209  driverObject->DriverExtension->ServiceKeyName.Buffer =
4210  ExAllocatePool( NonPagedPool, serviceName.MaximumLength );
4211  if (driverObject->DriverExtension->ServiceKeyName.Buffer) {
4212  driverObject->DriverExtension->ServiceKeyName.MaximumLength = serviceName.MaximumLength;
4213  driverObject->DriverExtension->ServiceKeyName.Length = serviceName.Length;
4214 
4215  RtlCopyMemory( driverObject->DriverExtension->ServiceKeyName.Buffer,
4216  serviceName.Buffer,
4217  serviceName.MaximumLength );
4218  }
4219  }
4220 
4221  //
4222  // Now invoke the driver's initialization routine to initialize itself.
4223  //
4224 
4225  status = driverObject->DriverInit( driverObject, &registryPath->Name );
4226 
4227  *DriverEntryStatus = status;
4228  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
4229 
4230  status = STATUS_FAILED_DRIVER_ENTRY;
4231  }
4232 
4233 #if DBG
4234 
4235  //
4236  // If DriverInit took longer than 5 seconds, print a message.
4237  //
4238 
4239  KeQuerySystemTime (&etime);
4240  dtime = (ULONG) ((etime.QuadPart - stime.QuadPart) / 1000000);
4241 
4242  if (dtime > 50) {
4243  DbgPrint( "IOLOAD: Driver %wZ took %d.%ds to %s\n",
4244  &driverName,
4245  dtime/10,
4246  dtime%10,
4247  NT_SUCCESS(status) ? "initialize" : "fail initialization"
4248  );
4249 
4250  }
4251 #endif
4252 
4253  //
4254  // Workaround for broken NT 4.0 3D labs driver
4255  // They zero out some function table entries by mistake.
4256 
4257  for (i = 0; i <= IRP_MJ_MAXIMUM_FUNCTION; i++) {
4258  if (driverObject->MajorFunction[i] == NULL) {
4259  ASSERT(driverObject->MajorFunction[i] != NULL);
4260  driverObject->MajorFunction[i] = IopInvalidDeviceRequest;
4261  }
4262  }
4263 
4264  //
4265  // If DriverInit doesn't work, then simply unload the image and mark the driver
4266  // object as temporary. This will cause everything to be deleted.
4267  //
4268 
4269  ExFreePool( registryPath );
4270 
4271  //
4272  // If we load the driver because we think it is a legacy driver and
4273  // it does not create any device object in its DriverEntry. We will
4274  // unload this driver.
4275  //
4276 
4277  if (NT_SUCCESS(status) && !IopIsLegacyDriver(driverObject)) {
4278 
4279  status = IopPnpDriverStarted(driverObject, KeyHandle, &serviceName);
4280 
4281  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
4282  if (driverObject->DriverUnload) {
4283  driverObject->Flags |= DRVO_UNLOAD_INVOKED;
4284  driverObject->DriverUnload(driverObject);
4285  IopBootLog(&baseName, FALSE);
4286  } else {
4287 #if DBG
4288  DbgPrint("IopLoadDriver: A PnP driver %wZ does not support DriverUnload routine.\n", &driverName);
4289 #endif
4290  }
4291  }
4292  }
4293 
4294  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
4295  ObMakeTemporaryObject( driverObject );
4296  ObDereferenceObject( driverObject );
4297  } else {
4298 
4299  //
4300  // Free the memory occupied by the driver's initialization routines.
4301  //
4302 
4303  IopBootLog(&baseName, TRUE);
4304  MmFreeDriverInitialization( driverObject->DriverSection );
4305  IopReadyDeviceObjects( driverObject );
4306  }
4307 
4308 IopLoadExit:
4309 
4310  if (NT_SUCCESS(status) || (status == STATUS_IMAGE_ALREADY_LOADED)) {
4311  HeadlessKernelAddLogEntry(HEADLESS_LOG_LOAD_SUCCESSFUL, NULL);
4312  } else {
4313  HeadlessKernelAddLogEntry(HEADLESS_LOG_LOAD_FAILED, NULL);
4314  }
4315 
4316  //
4317  // Free any pool that was allocated by this routine that has not yet
4318  // been freed.
4319  //
4320 
4321  if (driverName.Buffer != NULL) {
4322  ExFreePool( driverName.Buffer );
4323  }
4324 
4325  if (keyBasicInformation != NULL) {
4326  ExFreePool( keyBasicInformation );
4327  }
4328 
4329  if (serviceName.Buffer != NULL) {
4330  ExFreePool(serviceName.Buffer);
4331  }
4332 
4333  if (baseName.Buffer != NULL) {
4334  ExFreePool(baseName.Buffer);
4335  }
4336 
4337  //
4338  // If this routine is about to return a failure, then let the Configuration
4339  // Manager know about it. But, if STATUS_PLUGPLAY_NO_DEVICE, the device was
4340  // disabled by hardware profile. In this case we don't need to report it.
4341  //
4342 
4343  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status ) && (status != STATUS_PLUGPLAY_NO_DEVICE)) {
4344 
4345  NTSTATUS lStatus;
4346  PULONG errorControl;
4347  PKEY_VALUE_FULL_INFORMATION keyValueInformation;
4348 
4349  if (status != STATUS_IMAGE_ALREADY_LOADED) {
4350 
4351  //
4352  // If driver was loaded, do not call IopDriverLoadingFailed to change
4353  // the driver loading status. Because, obviously, the driver is
4354  // running.
4355  //
4356 
4357  IopDriverLoadingFailed(KeyHandle, NULL);
4358  lStatus = IopGetRegistryValue( KeyHandle,
4359  L"ErrorControl",
4360  &keyValueInformation );
4361  if (!NT_SUCCESS( lStatus ) || !keyValueInformation->DataLength) {
4362  if (NT_SUCCESS( lStatus )) {
4363  ExFreePool( keyValueInformation );
4364  }
4365  } else {
4366  errorControl = (PULONG) ((PUCHAR) keyValueInformation + keyValueInformation->DataOffset);
4367  CmBootLastKnownGood( *errorControl );
4368  ExFreePool( keyValueInformation );
4369  }
4370  }
4371  }
4372 
4373  //
4374  // Close the caller's handle and return the final status from the load
4375  // operation.
4376  //
4377 
4378  ObCloseHandle( KeyHandle , KernelMode);
4379  return status;
4380 }

4382 
4383 PDEVICE_OBJECT
4384 IopGetDeviceAttachmentBase(
4385  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
4386  )
4387 
4388 /*++
4389 
4390 Routine Description:
4391 
4392  This routine returns the lowest level device object associated with
4393  the specified device.
4394 
4395 Arguments:
4396 
4397  DeviceObject - Supplies a pointer to the device for which the bottom of
4398  attachment chain is to be found.
4399 
4400 Return Value:
4401 
4402  The function value is a reference to the lowest level device attached
4403  to the specified device. If the supplied device object is that device
4404  object, then a pointer to it is returned.
4405 
4406  N.B. Caller must own the IopDatabaseLock.
4407 
4408 --*/
4409 
4410 {
4411  PDEVICE_OBJECT baseDeviceObject;
4412  PDEVOBJ_EXTENSION deviceExtension;
4413 
4414  //
4415  // Descend down the attachment chain until we find a device object
4416  // that isn't attached to anything else.
4417  //
4418 
4419  baseDeviceObject = DeviceObject;
4420  deviceExtension = baseDeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension;
4421  while (deviceExtension->AttachedTo != NULL) {
4422 
4423  baseDeviceObject = deviceExtension->AttachedTo;
4424  deviceExtension = baseDeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension;
4425  }
4426 
4427  return baseDeviceObject;
4428 }
