4431 
4432 VOID
4433 IopDecrementDeviceObjectRef(
4434  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
4435  IN BOOLEAN AlwaysUnload,
4436  IN BOOLEAN OnCleanStack
4437  )
4438 
4439 /*++
4440 
4441 Routine Description:
4442 
4443  The routine decrements the reference count on a device object. If the
4444  reference count goes to zero and the device object is a candidate for deletion
4445  then IopCompleteUnloadOrDelete is called. A device object is subject for
4446  deletion if the AlwaysUnload flag is true, or the device object is pending
4447  deletion or the driver is pending unload.
4448 
4449 Arguments:
4450 
4451  DeviceObject - Supplies the device object whose reference count is to be
4452  decremented.
4453 
4454  AlwaysUnload - Indicates if the driver should be unloaded regardless of the
4455  state of the unload flag.
4456 
4457  OnCleanStack - Indicates whether the current thread is in the middle a
4458  driver operation.
4459 
4460 Return Value:
4461 
4462  None.
4463 
4464 --*/
4465 {
4466  KIRQL irql;
4467 
4468  //
4469  // Decrement the reference count on the device object. If this is the last
4470  // last reason that this mini-file system recognizer needs to stay around,
4471  // then unload it.
4472  //
4473 
4474  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
4475 
4476  ASSERT( DeviceObject->ReferenceCount > 0 );
4477 
4478  DeviceObject->ReferenceCount--;
4479 
4480  if (!DeviceObject->ReferenceCount && (AlwaysUnload ||
4481  DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags &
4482  (DOE_DELETE_PENDING | DOE_UNLOAD_PENDING | DOE_REMOVE_PENDING))) {
4483 
4484  IopCompleteUnloadOrDelete( DeviceObject, OnCleanStack, irql );
4485  } else {
4486  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
4487  }
4488 
4489 }
4490 
4491 VOID
4492 IopLoadFileSystemDriver(
4493  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
4494  )
4495 
4496 /*++
4497 
4498 Routine Description:
4499 
4500  This routine is invoked when a mini-file system recognizer driver recognizes
4501  a volume as being a particular file system, but the driver for that file
4502  system has not yet been loaded. This function allows the mini-driver to
4503  load the real file system, and remove itself from the system, so that the
4504  real file system can mount the device in question.
4505 
4506 Arguments:
4507 
4508  DeviceObject - Registered file system device object for the mini-driver.
4509 
4510 Return Value:
4511 
4512  None.
4513 
4514 --*/
4515 
4516 {
4517  KEVENT event;
4518  NTSTATUS status;
4519  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
4520  PIRP irp;
4521  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
4522  PDEVICE_OBJECT attachedDevice;
4523 
4524  PAGED_CODE();
4525 
4526  attachedDevice = DeviceObject;
4527  while (attachedDevice->AttachedDevice) {
4528  attachedDevice = attachedDevice->AttachedDevice;
4529  }
4530 
4531  //
4532  // Begin by building an I/O Request Packet to have the mini-file system
4533  // driver load the real file system.
4534  //
4535 
4536  KeInitializeEvent( &event, NotificationEvent, FALSE );
4537 
4538  irp = IoBuildDeviceIoControlRequest( IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL,
4539  attachedDevice,
4540  (PVOID) NULL,
4541  0,
4542  (PVOID) NULL,
4543  0,
4544  FALSE,
4545  &event,
4546  &ioStatus );
4547  if (irp) {
4548 
4549  //
4550  // Change the actual major and minor function codes to be a file system
4551  // control with a minor function code of load FS driver.
4552  //
4553 
4554  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
4555  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL;
4556  irpSp->MinorFunction = IRP_MN_LOAD_FILE_SYSTEM;
4557 
4558  //
4559  // Now issue the request.
4560  //
4561 
4562  status = IoCallDriver( attachedDevice, irp );
4563  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
4564  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
4565  Executive,
4566  KernelMode,
4567  FALSE,
4568  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
4569  }
4570  }
4571 
4572  //
4573  // Decrement the reference count on the device object. If this is the last
4574  // last reason that this mini-file system recognizer needs to stay around,
4575  // then unload it.
4576  //
4577 
4578  IopDecrementDeviceObjectRef(DeviceObject, TRUE, TRUE);
4579 
4580  return;
4581 }
4582 
4583 VOID
4584 IopLoadUnloadDriver(
4585  IN PVOID Parameter
4586  )
4587 
4588 /*++
4589 
4590 Routine Description:
4591 
4592  This routine is executed as an EX worker thread routine when a driver is
4593  to be loaded or unloaded dynamically. It is used because some drivers
4594  need to create system threads in the context of the system process, which
4595  cannot be done in the context of the caller of the system service that
4596  was invoked to load or unload the specified driver.
4597 
4598 Arguments:
4599 
4600  Parameter - Pointer to the load packet describing what work is to be
4601  done.
4602 
4603 Return Value:
4604 
4605  None.
4606 
4607 --*/
4608 
4609 {
4610  PLOAD_PACKET loadPacket;
4611  NTSTATUS status, driverEntryStatus;
4612  HANDLE keyHandle;
4613 
4614  PAGED_CODE();
4615 
4616  //
4617  // Begin by getting a pointer to the load packet.
4618  //
4619 
4620  loadPacket = (PLOAD_PACKET) Parameter;
4621 
4622  //
4623  // If the driver object field of the packet is non-NULL, then this is
4624  // a request to complete the unload of a driver. Simply invoke the
4625  // driver's unload routine. Note that the final status of the unload
4626  // is ignored, so it is not set here.
4627  //
4628 
4629  if (loadPacket->DriverObject) {
4630 
4631  loadPacket->DriverObject->DriverUnload( loadPacket->DriverObject );
4632  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
4633 
4634  } else {
4635 
4636  //
4637  // The driver specified by the DriverServiceName is to be loaded.
4638  // Begin by opening the registry node for this driver. Note
4639  // that if this is successful, then the load driver routine is
4640  // responsible for closing the handle.
4641  //
4642 
4643  status = IopOpenRegistryKey( &keyHandle,
4644  (HANDLE) NULL,
4645  loadPacket->DriverServiceName,
4646  KEY_READ,
4647  FALSE );
4648  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
4649 
4650  //
4651  // Invoke the internal common routine to perform the work.
4652  // This is the same routine that is used by the I/O system
4653  // initialization code to load drivers.
4654  //
4655 
4656  status = IopLoadDriver( keyHandle, TRUE, FALSE, &driverEntryStatus );
4657 
4658  if (status == STATUS_FAILED_DRIVER_ENTRY) {
4659 
4660  status = driverEntryStatus;
4661 
4662  } else if (status == STATUS_DRIVER_FAILED_PRIOR_UNLOAD) {
4663 
4664  //
4665  // Keep legacy behavior (don't change status code)
4666  //
4667  status = STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_NOT_FOUND;
4668  }
4669 
4670  IopCallDriverReinitializationRoutines();
4671  }
4672  }
4673 
4674  //
4675  // Set the final status of the load or unload operation, and indicate to
4676  // the caller that the operation is now complete.
4677  //
4678 
4679  loadPacket->FinalStatus = status;
4680  (VOID) KeSetEvent( &loadPacket->Event, 0, FALSE );
4681 }
4682 
4683 NTSTATUS
4684 IopMountVolume(
4685  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
4686  IN BOOLEAN AllowRawMount,
4687  IN BOOLEAN DeviceLockAlreadyHeld,
4688  IN BOOLEAN Alertable,
4689  OUT PVPB *Vpb
4690  )
4691 
4692 /*++
4693 
4694 Routine Description:
4695 
4696  This routine is used to mount a volume on the specified device. The Volume
4697  Parameter Block (VPB) for the specified device is a "clean" VPB. That is,
4698  it indicates that the volume has never been mounted. It is up to the file
4699  system that eventually mounts the volume to determine whether the volume is,
4700  or has been, mounted elsewhere.
4701 
4702 Arguments:
4703 
4704  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object on which the volume is to be
4705  mounted.
4706 
4707  AllowRawMount - This parameter tells us if we should continue our
4708  filesystem search to include the Raw file system. This flag will
4709  only be passed in as TRUE as a result of a DASD open.
4710 
4711  DeviceLockAlreadyHeld - If TRUE, then the caller has already acquired
4712  the device lock and we should not attempt to acquire it. This is
4713  currently passed in as TRUE when called from IoVerifyVolume.
4714 
4715 Return Value:
4716 
4717  The function value is a successful status code if a volume was successfully
4718  mounted on the device. Otherwise, an error code is returned.
4719 
4720 
4721 --*/
4722 
4723 {
4724  NTSTATUS status;
4725  KEVENT event;
4726  PIRP irp;
4727  PDEVICE_OBJECT fsDeviceObject;
4728  PDEVICE_OBJECT attachedDevice;
4729  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
4730  PLIST_ENTRY queueHeader;
4731  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
4732  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
4733  ULONG extraStack;
4734  LIST_ENTRY dummy;
4735  ULONG rawMountOnly;
4736  ULONG numRegOps;
4737  PETHREAD CurrentThread;
4738 
4739  PAGED_CODE();
4740 
4741  CurrentThread = PsGetCurrentThread ();
4742 
4743  //
4744  // Obtain the lock for the device to be mounted. This guarantees that
4745  // only one thread is attempting to mount (or verify) this particular
4746  // device at a time.
4747  //
4748 
4749  if (!DeviceLockAlreadyHeld) {
4750 
4751  status = KeWaitForSingleObject( &DeviceObject->DeviceLock,
4752  Executive,
4753  KeGetPreviousModeByThread(&CurrentThread->Tcb),
4754  Alertable,
4755  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
4756 
4757  //
4758  // If the wait ended because of an alert or an APC, return now
4759  // without mounting the device. Note that as the wait for the
4760  // event was unsuccessful, we do not set it on exit.
4761  //
4762 
4763  if (status == STATUS_ALERTED || status == STATUS_USER_APC) {
4764 
4765  return status;
4766  }
4767  }
4768 
4769  //
4770  // Now acquire the resource database lock for the I/O system to perform this
4771  // operation. This resource protects access to the file system queue.
4772  //
4773 
4774  KeEnterCriticalRegionThread(&CurrentThread->Tcb);
4775  (VOID) ExAcquireResourceSharedLite( &IopDatabaseResource, TRUE );
4776 
4777  //
4778  // Check the 'mounted' flag of the VPB to ensure that it is still clear.
4779  // If it is, then no one has gotten in before this to mount the volume.
4780  // Attempt to mount the volume in this case.
4781  //
4782 
4783  if ((DeviceObject->Vpb->Flags & (VPB_MOUNTED | VPB_REMOVE_PENDING)) == 0) {
4784 
4785  //
4786  // This volume has never been mounted. Initialize the event and set the
4787  // status to unsuccessful to set up for the loop. Also if the device
4788  // has the verify bit set, clear it.
4789  //
4790 
4791  KeInitializeEvent( &event, NotificationEvent, FALSE );
4792  status = STATUS_UNSUCCESSFUL;
4793  DeviceObject->Flags &= ~DO_VERIFY_VOLUME;
4794 
4795  //
4796  // Get the actual device that this volume is to be mounted on. This
4797  // device is the final device in the list of devices which are attached
4798  // to the specified real device.
4799  //
4800 
4801  attachedDevice = DeviceObject;
4802  while (attachedDevice->AttachedDevice) {
4803  attachedDevice = attachedDevice->AttachedDevice;
4804  }
4805 
4806  //
4807  // Reference the device object so it cannot go away.
4808  //
4809 
4810  ObReferenceObject( attachedDevice );
4811 
4812  //
4813  // Determine which type of file system should be invoked based on
4814  // the device type of the device being mounted.
4815  //
4816 
4817  if (DeviceObject->DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_DISK ||
4818  DeviceObject->DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_VIRTUAL_DISK) {
4819  queueHeader = &IopDiskFileSystemQueueHead;
4820  } else if (DeviceObject->DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_CD_ROM) {
4821  queueHeader = &IopCdRomFileSystemQueueHead;
4822  } else {
4823  queueHeader = &IopTapeFileSystemQueueHead;
4824  }
4825 
4826  rawMountOnly = (DeviceObject->Vpb->Flags & VPB_RAW_MOUNT);
4827 
4828  //
4829  // Now loop through each of the file systems which have been loaded in
4830  // the system to see whether anyone understands the media in the device.
4831  //
4832 
4833  for (entry = queueHeader->Flink;
4834  entry != queueHeader && !NT_SUCCESS( status );
4835  entry = entry->Flink) {
4836 
4837  PDEVICE_OBJECT savedFsDeviceObject;
4838 
4839  //
4840  // If this is the final entry (Raw file system), and it is also
4841  // not the first entry, and a raw mount is not permitted, then
4842  // break out of the loop at this point, as this volume cannot
4843  // be mounted for the caller's purposes.
4844  //
4845 
4846  if (!AllowRawMount && entry->Flink == queueHeader && entry != queueHeader->Flink) {
4847  break;
4848  }
4849 
4850  //
4851  // If raw mount is the only one requested and this is not the last entry on the list
4852  // then skip.
4853  //
4854  if (rawMountOnly && (entry->Flink != queueHeader)) {
4855  continue;
4856  }
4857 
4858  fsDeviceObject = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, DEVICE_OBJECT, Queue.ListEntry );
4859  savedFsDeviceObject = fsDeviceObject;
4860 
4861  //
4862  // It is possible that the file system has been attached to, so
4863  // walk the attached list for the file system. The number of stack
4864  // locations that must be allocated in the IRP must include one for
4865  // the file system itself, and then one for each driver that is
4866  // attached to it. Account for all of the stack locations required
4867  // to get through the mount process.
4868  //
4869 
4870  extraStack = 1;
4871 
4872  while (fsDeviceObject->AttachedDevice) {
4873  fsDeviceObject = fsDeviceObject->AttachedDevice;
4874  extraStack++;
4875  }
4876 
4877  //
4878  // Another file system has been found and the volume has still not
4879  // been mounted. Attempt to mount the volume using this file
4880  // system.
4881  //
4882  // Begin by resetting the event being used for synchronization with
4883  // the I/O operation.
4884  //
4885 
4886  KeClearEvent( &event );
4887 
4888  //
4889  // Allocate and initialize an IRP for this mount operation. Notice
4890  // that the flags for this operation appear the same as a page read
4891  // operation. This is because the completion code for both of the
4892  // operations is exactly the same logic.
4893  //
4894 
4895  irp = IoAllocateIrp ((CCHAR) (attachedDevice->StackSize + extraStack), FALSE);
4896 
4897  if ( !irp ) {
4898 
4899  status = STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
4900  break;
4901  }
4902 
4903  irp->Flags = IRP_MOUNT_COMPLETION | IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_PAGING_IO;
4904  irp->RequestorMode = KernelMode;
4905  irp->UserEvent = &event;
4906  irp->UserIosb = &ioStatus;
4907  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = CurrentThread;
4908  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
4909  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL;
4910  irpSp->MinorFunction = IRP_MN_MOUNT_VOLUME;
4911  irpSp->Flags = AllowRawMount;
4912  irpSp->Parameters.MountVolume.Vpb = DeviceObject->Vpb;
4913  irpSp->Parameters.MountVolume.DeviceObject = attachedDevice;
4914 
4915  numRegOps = IopFsRegistrationOps;
4916 
4917  //
4918  // Increment the number of reasons that this driver cannot
4919  // be unloaded. Note that this must be done while still
4920  // holding the database resource.
4921  //
4922 
4923  IopInterlockedIncrementUlong( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock,
4924  &savedFsDeviceObject->ReferenceCount );
4925 
4926  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDatabaseResource );
4927 
4928  status = IoCallDriver( fsDeviceObject, irp );
4929 
4930  //
4931  // Wait for the I/O operation to complete.
4932  //
4933 
4934  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
4935  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
4936  Executive,
4937  KernelMode,
4938  FALSE,
4939  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
4940  } else {
4941 
4942  //
4943  // Ensure that the proper status value gets picked up.
4944  //
4945 
4946  ioStatus.Status = status;
4947  ioStatus.Information = 0;
4948  }
4949 
4950  (VOID) ExAcquireResourceSharedLite( &IopDatabaseResource, TRUE );
4951 
4952 
4953  //
4954  // Decrement the number of reasons that this driver cannot be unloaded.
4955  // If the device object is for FSREC it could not have gotten de-registered
4956  // here. It should get de-registered only at the time of loading the driver
4957  // which should happen later.
4958  //
4959 
4960  IopInterlockedDecrementUlong( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock,
4961  &savedFsDeviceObject->ReferenceCount );
4962 
4963  //
4964  // If the operation was successful then set the VPB as mounted.
4965  //
4966 
4967  if (NT_SUCCESS( ioStatus.Status )) {
4968 
4969  status = ioStatus.Status;
4970 
4971  *Vpb = IopMountInitializeVpb(DeviceObject, attachedDevice, rawMountOnly);
4972 
4973  } else {
4974 
4975  //
4976  // The mount operation failed. Make a special check here to
4977  // determine whether or not a popup was enabled, and if so,
4978  // check to see whether or not the operation was to be aborted.
4979  // If so, bail out now and return the error to the caller.
4980  //
4981 
4982  status = ioStatus.Status;
4983  if (IoIsErrorUserInduced(status) &&
4984  ioStatus.Information == IOP_ABORT) {
4985  break;
4986  }
4987 
4988  //
4989  // If there were any registrations or unregistrations during the period
4990  // we unlocked the database resource bail out and start all over again.
4991  //
4992 
4993  if (numRegOps != IopFsRegistrationOps) {
4994 
4995  //
4996  // Reset the list back to the beginning and start over
4997  // again.
4998  //
4999 
5000  dummy.Flink = queueHeader->Flink;
5001  entry = &dummy;
5002  status = STATUS_UNRECOGNIZED_VOLUME;
5003  }
5004 
5005  //
5006  // Also check to see whether or not this is a volume that has
5007  // been recognized, but the file system for it needs to be
5008  // loaded. If so, drop the locks held at this point, tell the
5009  // mini-file system recognizer to load the driver, and then
5010  // reacquire the locks.
5011  //
5012 
5013  if (status == STATUS_FS_DRIVER_REQUIRED) {
5014 
5015  //
5016  // Increment the number of reasons that this driver cannot
5017  // be unloaded. Note that this must be done while still
5018  // holding the database resource.
5019  //
5020 
5021  IopInterlockedIncrementUlong( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock,
5022  &savedFsDeviceObject->ReferenceCount );
5023 
5024  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDatabaseResource );
5025 
5026  if (!DeviceLockAlreadyHeld) {
5027  KeSetEvent( &DeviceObject->DeviceLock, 0, FALSE );
5028  }
5029 
5030  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread(&CurrentThread->Tcb);
5031  IopLoadFileSystemDriver( savedFsDeviceObject );
5032 
5033  //
5034  // Now reacquire the locks, in the correct order, and check
5035  // to see if the volume has been mounted before we could
5036  // get back. If so, exit; otherwise, restart the file
5037  // file system queue scan from the beginning.
5038  //
5039 
5040  if (!DeviceLockAlreadyHeld) {
5041  status = KeWaitForSingleObject( &DeviceObject->DeviceLock,
5042  Executive,
5043  KeGetPreviousModeByThread(&CurrentThread->Tcb),
5044  Alertable,
5045  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
5046  if (status == STATUS_ALERTED || status == STATUS_USER_APC) {
5047 
5048  //
5049  // The device was not mounted by us so
5050  // drop the reference before returning.
5051  //
5052 
5053  ObDereferenceObject( attachedDevice );
5054 
5055  return status;
5056  }
5057  }
5058 
5059  KeEnterCriticalRegionThread(&CurrentThread->Tcb);
5060  (VOID) ExAcquireResourceSharedLite( &IopDatabaseResource, TRUE );
5061 
5062  if (DeviceObject->Vpb->Flags & VPB_MOUNTED) {
5063 
5064  //
5065  // This volume was mounted before we got back.
5066  // Hence deref the attachedDevice as the other thread
5067  // that got the reference is the one that's going to be
5068  // used by the filesystem.
5069  //
5070 
5071  ObDereferenceObject( attachedDevice );
5072  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
5073  break;
5074  }
5075 
5076  //
5077  // Reset the list back to the beginning and start over
5078  // again.
5079  //
5080 
5081  dummy.Flink = queueHeader->Flink;
5082  entry = &dummy;
5083  status = STATUS_UNRECOGNIZED_VOLUME;
5084  }
5085 
5086  //
5087  // If the error wasn't STATUS_UNRECOGNIZED_VOLUME, and this
5088  // request is not going to the Raw file system, then there
5089  // is no reason to continue looping.
5090  //
5091 
5092  if (!AllowRawMount && (status != STATUS_UNRECOGNIZED_VOLUME) &&
5093  FsRtlIsTotalDeviceFailure(status)) {
5094  break;
5095  }
5096 
5097  }
5098  }
5099 
5100  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
5101 
5102  //
5103  // The device was not mounted by us so
5104  // drop the reference.
5105  // On success this reference is used by the filesystem
5106  // Its usually Vcb->TargetDeviceObject.
5107  // On a dismount the filesystem deref (Vcb->TargetDeviceObject)
5108  //
5109 
5110  ObDereferenceObject( attachedDevice );
5111 
5112  }
5113 
5114  } else if((DeviceObject->Vpb->Flags & VPB_REMOVE_PENDING) != 0) {
5115 
5116  //
5117  // Pnp is attempting to remove this volume. Don't allow the mount.
5118  //
5119 
5120  status = STATUS_DEVICE_DOES_NOT_EXIST;
5121 
5122  } else {
5123 
5124  //
5125  // The volume for this device has already been mounted. Return a
5126  // success code.
5127  //
5128 
5129  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
5130  }
5131 
5132  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDatabaseResource );
5133 
5134  //
5135  // Release the I/O database resource lock and the synchronization event for
5136  // the device.
5137  //
5138 
5139  if (!DeviceLockAlreadyHeld) {
5140  KeSetEvent( &DeviceObject->DeviceLock, 0, FALSE );
5141  }
5142 
5143  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread(&CurrentThread->Tcb);
5144 
5145  //
5146  // Finally, if the mount operation failed, and the target device is the
5147  // boot partition, then bugcheck the system. It is not possible for the
5148  // system to run properly if the system's boot partition cannot be mounted.
5149  //
5150  // Note: Don't bugcheck if the system is already booted.
5151  //
5152 
5153  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status ) &&
5154  DeviceObject->Flags & DO_SYSTEM_BOOT_PARTITION &&
5155  InitializationPhase < 2) {
5156  KeBugCheckEx( UNMOUNTABLE_BOOT_VOLUME, (ULONG_PTR) DeviceObject, status, 0, 0 );
5157  }
5158 
5159  return status;
5160 }
5161 
5162 
5163 NTSTATUS
5164 IopInvalidateVolumesForDevice(
5165  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject
5166  )
5167 
5168 /*++
5169 
5170 Routine Description:
5171 
5172  This routine is used to force filesystems to, as completely as possible, throw
5173  out volumes which remain referenced for a given device.
5174 
5175 Arguments:
5176 
5177  DeviceObject - Pointer to device object for which volumes are to be
5178  invalidated.
5179 
5180 Return Value:
5181 
5182  The function value is a successful status code if all filesystems accepted the
5183  operation. Otherwise, an error code is returned.
5184 
5185 --*/
5186 
5187 {
5188  NTSTATUS status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
5189  NTSTATUS finalStatus;
5190  KEVENT event;
5191  PIRP irp;
5192  PDEVICE_OBJECT fsDeviceObject;
5193  PDEVICE_OBJECT attachedDevice;
5194  PFILE_OBJECT storageFileObject;
5195  HANDLE storageHandle;
5196  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
5197  PLIST_ENTRY queueHeader;
5198  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
5199  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
5200  PKTHREAD CurrentThread;
5201 
5202  PAGED_CODE();
5203 
5204 
5205  //
5206  // Get the actual device that could be mounted on.
5207  // Note that there could be multiple device objects on the stack that has a
5208  // VPB and could be potentially mounted on by FS. So we call the FS with every
5209  // device object that has a VPB. This is really a simple brute force approach but
5210  // this is not a high performance path and is backwards compatible.
5211  //
5212 
5213  for (attachedDevice = DeviceObject ;attachedDevice; attachedDevice = attachedDevice->AttachedDevice) {
5214 
5215  //
5216  // If the device object has no VPB skip.
5217  //
5218 
5219  if (!attachedDevice->Vpb) {
5220  continue;
5221  }
5222 
5223  //
5224  // Synchronize against mounts.
5225  //
5226 
5227  KeWaitForSingleObject(&(attachedDevice->DeviceLock),
5228  Executive,
5229  KernelMode,
5230  FALSE,
5231  NULL);
5232  //
5233  // Get a handle to this device for use in the fsctl. The way we have to do
5234  // this is kind of loopy: note we wind up with two references to clean up.
5235  //
5236  // The only use of this fileobject/handle is to communicate the device to
5237  // invalidate volumes on. It isn't used for anything else, and must not be.
5238  //
5239 
5240  storageHandle = NULL;
5241  storageFileObject = NULL;
5242 
5243  try {
5244 
5245  storageFileObject = IoCreateStreamFileObjectLite( NULL, attachedDevice );
5246  storageFileObject->Vpb = attachedDevice->Vpb;
5247 
5248  status = ObOpenObjectByPointer( storageFileObject,
5249  OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
5250  NULL,
5251  0,
5252  IoFileObjectType,
5253  KernelMode,
5254  &storageHandle );
5255 
5256  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
5257 
5258  status = GetExceptionCode();
5259  }
5260 
5261  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
5262 
5263  //
5264  // Now acquire the resource database lock for the I/O system to perform this
5265  // operation. This resource protects access to the file system queue.
5266  //
5267 
5268  CurrentThread = KeGetCurrentThread ();
5269  KeEnterCriticalRegionThread(CurrentThread);
5270  (VOID) ExAcquireResourceSharedLite( &IopDatabaseResource, TRUE );
5271 
5272  //
5273  // Determine which type of file system should be invoked based on
5274  // the device type of the device being invalidated.
5275  //
5276 
5277  if (DeviceObject->DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_DISK ||
5278  DeviceObject->DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_VIRTUAL_DISK) {
5279  queueHeader = &IopDiskFileSystemQueueHead;
5280  } else if (DeviceObject->DeviceType == FILE_DEVICE_CD_ROM) {
5281  queueHeader = &IopCdRomFileSystemQueueHead;
5282  } else {
5283  queueHeader = &IopTapeFileSystemQueueHead;
5284  }
5285 
5286  //
5287  // Initialize the event and set the status to set up
5288  // for the loop.
5289  //
5290 
5291  KeInitializeEvent( &event, NotificationEvent, FALSE );
5292  finalStatus = STATUS_SUCCESS;
5293 
5294  //
5295  // Now loop through each of the file systems which have been loaded in
5296  // the system and ask them to invalidate volumes they have had mounted
5297  // on it.
5298  //
5299 
5300  for (entry = queueHeader->Flink;
5301  entry != queueHeader;
5302  entry = entry->Flink) {
5303 
5304  //
5305  // If this is the final entry (Raw file system), then break out of the
5306  // loop at this point, as volumes cannot be invalidated for the caller's
5307  // purposes in Raw.
5308  //
5309 
5310  if (entry->Flink == queueHeader) {
5311  break;
5312  }
5313 
5314  fsDeviceObject = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, DEVICE_OBJECT, Queue.ListEntry );
5315 
5316  //
5317  // It is possible that the file system has been attached to, so
5318  // walk the attached list for the file system.
5319  //
5320 
5321  while (fsDeviceObject->AttachedDevice) {
5322  fsDeviceObject = fsDeviceObject->AttachedDevice;
5323  }
5324 
5325  //
5326  // Another file system has been found. Attempt to invalidate volumes
5327  // using this file system.
5328  //
5329  // Begin by resetting the event being used for synchronization with
5330  // the I/O operation.
5331  //
5332 
5333  KeClearEvent( &event );
5334 
5335  //
5336  // Build an IRP for this operation.
5337  //
5338 
5339  irp = IoBuildDeviceIoControlRequest( FSCTL_INVALIDATE_VOLUMES,
5340  fsDeviceObject,
5341  &storageHandle,
5342  sizeof(HANDLE),
5343  NULL,
5344  0,
5345  FALSE,
5346  &event,
5347  &ioStatus );
5348 
5349  if (irp == NULL) {
5350 
5351  finalStatus = STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
5352  break;
5353  }
5354 
5355  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
5356  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL;
5357 
5358  status = IoCallDriver( fsDeviceObject, irp );
5359 
5360  //
5361  // Wait for the I/O operation to complete.
5362  //
5363 
5364  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
5365  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
5366  Executive,
5367  KernelMode,
5368  FALSE,
5369  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
5370 
5371  status = ioStatus.Status;
5372 
5373  } else {
5374 
5375  //
5376  // Ensure that the proper status value gets picked up.
5377  //
5378 
5379  ioStatus.Status = status;
5380  ioStatus.Information = 0;
5381  }
5382 
5383  //
5384  // Commute status' indicating the operation is not implemented
5385  // to success. If a filesystem does not implement, it must not
5386  // hold volumes that are not mounted.
5387  //
5388 
5389  if (status == STATUS_INVALID_DEVICE_REQUEST ||
5390  status == STATUS_NOT_IMPLEMENTED) {
5391 
5392  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
5393  }
5394 
5395  //
5396  // Hand back the first failure we get, but plow on anyway.
5397  //
5398 
5399  if (NT_SUCCESS( finalStatus ) && !NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
5400  finalStatus = status;
5401  }
5402  }
5403 
5404  ExReleaseResourceLite( &IopDatabaseResource );
5405  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread(CurrentThread);
5406 
5407  if (storageFileObject) {
5408  ObDereferenceObject( storageFileObject );
5409  if (storageHandle) {
5410  ZwClose( storageHandle ); // Note that this is a close for which the FS has not
5411  // gotten the corresponding open.
5412  }
5413  }
5414 
5415  status = finalStatus;
5416  }
5417 
5418  //
5419  // Unlock the device lock to let mounts go
5420  //
5421 
5422  KeSetEvent(&(attachedDevice->DeviceLock), IO_NO_INCREMENT, FALSE);
5423  }
5424 
5425 
5426  return status;
5427 }
5428 
5429 NTSTATUS
5430 IopOpenLinkOrRenameTarget(
5431  OUT PHANDLE TargetHandle,
5432  IN PIRP Irp,
5433  IN PVOID RenameBuffer,
5434  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject
5435  )
5436 
5437 /*++
5438 
5439 Routine Description:
5440 
5441  This routine is invoked by the rename, set link and set copy-on-write code
5442  in the I/O system's NtSetInformationFile system service when the caller has
5443  specified a fully qualified file name as the target of a rename, set link,
5444  or set copy-on-write operation. This routine attempts to open the parent
5445  of the specified file and checks the following:
5446 
5447  o If the file itself exists, then the caller must have specified that
5448  the target is to be replaced, otherwise an error is returned.
5449 
5450  o Ensures that the target file specification refers to the same volume
5451  upon which the source file exists.
5452 
5453 Arguments:
5454 
5455  TargetHandle - Supplies the address of a variable to return the handle to
5456  the opened target file if no errors have occurred.
5457 
5458  Irp - Supplies a pointer to the IRP that represents the current rename
5459  request.
5460 
5461  RenameBuffer - Supplies a pointer to the system intermediate buffer that
5462  contains the caller's rename parameters.
5463 
5464  FileObject - Supplies a pointer to the file object representing the file
5465  being renamed.
5466 
5467 Return Value:
5468 
5469  The function value is the final status of the operation.
5470 
5471 Note:
5472 
5473  This function assumes that the layout of a rename, set link and set
5474  copy-on-write information structure are exactly the same.
5475 
5476 --*/
5477 
5478 {
5479  NTSTATUS status;
5480  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
5481  HANDLE handle;
5482  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
5483  UNICODE_STRING newFileName;
5484  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
5485  PFILE_OBJECT targetFileObject;
5486  OBJECT_HANDLE_INFORMATION handleInformation;
5487  PFILE_RENAME_INFORMATION renameBuffer = RenameBuffer;
5488  FILE_BASIC_INFORMATION basicInformation;
5489  ACCESS_MASK accessMask;
5490 
5491  PAGED_CODE();
5492 
5493  ASSERT( sizeof( FILE_RENAME_INFORMATION ) ==
5494  sizeof( FILE_LINK_INFORMATION ) );
5495  ASSERT( FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_RENAME_INFORMATION, ReplaceIfExists ) ==
5496  FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_LINK_INFORMATION, ReplaceIfExists ) );
5497  ASSERT( FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_RENAME_INFORMATION, RootDirectory ) ==
5498  FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_LINK_INFORMATION, RootDirectory ) );
5499  ASSERT( FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_RENAME_INFORMATION, FileNameLength ) ==
5500  FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_LINK_INFORMATION, FileNameLength ) );
5501  ASSERT( FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_RENAME_INFORMATION, FileName ) ==
5502  FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_LINK_INFORMATION, FileName ) );
5503 
5504  ASSERT( sizeof( FILE_RENAME_INFORMATION ) ==
5505  sizeof( FILE_MOVE_CLUSTER_INFORMATION ) );
5506  ASSERT( FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_RENAME_INFORMATION, ReplaceIfExists ) ==
5507  FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_MOVE_CLUSTER_INFORMATION, ClusterCount ) );
5508  ASSERT( FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_RENAME_INFORMATION, RootDirectory ) ==
5509  FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_MOVE_CLUSTER_INFORMATION, RootDirectory ) );
5510  ASSERT( FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_RENAME_INFORMATION, FileNameLength ) ==
5511  FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_MOVE_CLUSTER_INFORMATION, FileNameLength ) );
5512  ASSERT( FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_RENAME_INFORMATION, FileName ) ==
5513  FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_MOVE_CLUSTER_INFORMATION, FileName ) );
5514 
5515  //
5516  // Check if the fileobject is a directory or a regular file.
5517  // The access mask is different based on that behavior.
5518  //
5519 
5520  accessMask = FILE_WRITE_DATA;
5521 
5522  if (!(FileObject->Flags & FO_DIRECT_DEVICE_OPEN)) {
5523  status = IopGetBasicInformationFile(FileObject, &basicInformation);
5524 
5525  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
5526  return status;
5527  }
5528 
5529  if (basicInformation.FileAttributes & FILE_ATTRIBUTE_DIRECTORY) {
5530  accessMask = FILE_ADD_SUBDIRECTORY;
5531  }
5532  }
5533 
5534  //
5535  // A fully qualified file name was specified. Begin by attempting to open
5536  // the parent directory of the specified target file.
5537  //
5538 
5539  newFileName.Length = (USHORT) renameBuffer->FileNameLength;
5540  newFileName.MaximumLength = (USHORT) renameBuffer->FileNameLength;
5541  newFileName.Buffer = renameBuffer->FileName;
5542 
5543  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
5544  &newFileName,
5545  (FileObject->Flags & FO_OPENED_CASE_SENSITIVE ? 0 : OBJ_CASE_INSENSITIVE)|OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
5546  renameBuffer->RootDirectory,
5547  (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL );
5548 
5549  //
5550  // Check if the fileobject is not to the top of the stack.
5551  //
5552 
5553  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_FILE_OBJECT_HAS_EXTENSION) {
5554 
5555  PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION fileObjectExtension =
5556  (PIOP_FILE_OBJECT_EXTENSION)(FileObject + 1);
5557 
5558  ASSERT(!(FileObject->Flags & FO_DIRECT_DEVICE_OPEN));
5559 
5560  status = IoCreateFileSpecifyDeviceObjectHint( &handle,
5561  accessMask | SYNCHRONIZE,
5562  &objectAttributes,
5563  &ioStatus,
5564  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL,
5565  0,
5566  FILE_SHARE_READ | FILE_SHARE_WRITE,
5567  FILE_OPEN,
5568  FILE_OPEN_FOR_BACKUP_INTENT,
5569  (PVOID) NULL,
5570  0L,
5571  CreateFileTypeNone,
5572  (PVOID) NULL,
5573  IO_NO_PARAMETER_CHECKING |
5574  IO_OPEN_TARGET_DIRECTORY |
5575  IO_FORCE_ACCESS_CHECK |
5576  IOP_CREATE_USE_TOP_DEVICE_OBJECT_HINT,
5577  fileObjectExtension->TopDeviceObjectHint );
5578 
5579  } else {
5580 
5581  status = IoCreateFile( &handle,
5582  accessMask | SYNCHRONIZE,
5583  &objectAttributes,
5584  &ioStatus,
5585  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL,
5586  0,
5587  FILE_SHARE_READ | FILE_SHARE_WRITE,
5588  FILE_OPEN,
5589  FILE_OPEN_FOR_BACKUP_INTENT,
5590  (PVOID) NULL,
5591  0L,
5592  CreateFileTypeNone,
5593  (PVOID) NULL,
5594  IO_NO_PARAMETER_CHECKING |
5595  IO_OPEN_TARGET_DIRECTORY |
5596  IO_FORCE_ACCESS_CHECK );
5597  }
5598 
5599  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
5600  //
5601  // The open operation for the target file's parent directory was
5602  // successful. Check to see whether or not the file exists.
5603  //
5604 
5605  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( Irp );
5606  if (irpSp->Parameters.SetFile.FileInformationClass == FileLinkInformation &&
5607  !renameBuffer->ReplaceIfExists &&
5608  ioStatus.Information == FILE_EXISTS) {
5609 
5610  //
5611  // The target file exists, and the caller does not want to replace
5612  // it. This is a name collision error so cleanup and return.
5613  //
5614 
5615  ObCloseHandle( handle , KernelMode);
5616  status = STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_COLLISION;
5617 
5618  } else {
5619 
5620  //
5621  // Everything up to this point is fine, so dereference the handle
5622  // to a pointer to the file object and ensure that the two file
5623  // specifications refer to the same device.
5624  //
5625 
5626  status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle( handle,
5627  accessMask,
5628  IoFileObjectType,
5629  KernelMode,
5630  (PVOID *) &targetFileObject,
5631  &handleInformation );
5632  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
5633 
5634  ObDereferenceObject( targetFileObject );
5635 
5636  if (IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( targetFileObject) !=
5637  IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( FileObject )) {
5638 
5639  //
5640  // The two files refer to different devices. Clean everything
5641  // up and return an appropriate error.
5642  //
5643 
5644  ObCloseHandle( handle, KernelMode );
5645  status = STATUS_NOT_SAME_DEVICE;
5646 
5647  } else {
5648 
5649  //
5650  // Otherwise, everything worked, so allow the rename operation
5651  // to continue.
5652  //
5653 
5654  irpSp->Parameters.SetFile.FileObject = targetFileObject;
5655  *TargetHandle = handle;
5656  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
5657 
5658  }
5659 
5660  } else {
5661 
5662  //
5663  // There was an error referencing the handle to what should
5664  // have been the target directory. This generally means that
5665  // there was a resource problem or the handle was invalid, etc.
5666  // Simply attempt to close the handle and return the error.
5667  //
5668 
5669  ObCloseHandle( handle , KernelMode);
5670 
5671  }
5672 
5673  }
5674  }
5675 
5676  //
5677  // Return the final status of the operation.
5678  //
5679 
5680  return status;
5681 }
5682 
5683 NTSTATUS
5684 IopOpenRegistryKey(
5685  OUT PHANDLE Handle,
5686  IN HANDLE BaseHandle OPTIONAL,
5687  IN PUNICODE_STRING KeyName,
5688  IN ACCESS_MASK DesiredAccess,
5689  IN BOOLEAN Create
5690  )
5691 
5692 /*++
5693 
5694 Routine Description:
5695 
5696  Opens or creates a VOLATILE registry key using the name passed in based
5697  at the BaseHandle node.
5698 
5699 Arguments:
5700 
5701  Handle - Pointer to the handle which will contain the registry key that
5702  was opened.
5703 
5704  BaseHandle - Handle to the base path from which the key must be opened.
5705 
5706  KeyName - Name of the Key that must be opened/created.
5707 
5708  DesiredAccess - Specifies the desired access that the caller needs to
5709  the key.
5710 
5711  Create - Determines if the key is to be created if it does not exist.
5712 
5713 Return Value:
5714 
5715  The function value is the final status of the operation.
5716 
5717 --*/
5718 
5719 {
5720  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
5721  ULONG disposition;
5722 
5723  PAGED_CODE();
5724 
5725  //
5726  // Initialize the object for the key.
5727  //
5728 
5729  InitializeObjectAttributes( &objectAttributes,
5730  KeyName,
5731  OBJ_CASE_INSENSITIVE|OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
5732  BaseHandle,
5733  (PSECURITY_DESCRIPTOR) NULL );
5734 
5735  //
5736  // Create the key or open it, as appropriate based on the caller's
5737  // wishes.
5738  //
5739 
5740  if (Create) {
5741  return ZwCreateKey( Handle,
5742  DesiredAccess,
5743  &objectAttributes,
5744  0,
5745  (PUNICODE_STRING) NULL,
5746  REG_OPTION_VOLATILE,
5747  &disposition );
5748  } else {
5749  return ZwOpenKey( Handle,
5750  DesiredAccess,
5751  &objectAttributes );
5752  }
5753 }
5754 
5755 NTSTATUS
5756 IopQueryXxxInformation(
5757  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
5758  IN ULONG InformationClass,
5759  IN ULONG Length,
5760  IN KPROCESSOR_MODE Mode,
5761  OUT PVOID Information,
5762  OUT PULONG ReturnedLength,
5763  IN BOOLEAN FileInformation
5764  )
5765 
5766 /*++
5767 
5768 Routine Description:
5769 
5770  This routine returns the requested information about a specified file
5771  or volume. The information returned is determined by the class that
5772  is specified, and it is placed into the caller's output buffer.
5773 
5774 Arguments:
5775 
5776  FileObject - Supplies a pointer to the file object about which the requested
5777  information is returned.
5778 
5779  FsInformationClass - Specifies the type of information which should be
5780  returned about the file/volume.
5781 
5782  Length - Supplies the length of the buffer in bytes.
5783 
5784  FsInformation - Supplies a buffer to receive the requested information
5785  returned about the file. This buffer must not be pageable and must
5786  reside in system space.
5787 
5788  ReturnedLength - Supplies a variable that is to receive the length of the
5789  information written to the buffer.
5790 
5791  FileInformation - Boolean that indicates whether the information requested
5792  is for a file or a volume.
5793 
5794  Mode - Previous mode of the caller to this API.
5795 
5796 Return Value:
5797 
5798  The status returned is the final completion status of the operation.
5799 
5800 --*/
5801 
5802 {
5803  PIRP irp;
5804  NTSTATUS status;
5805  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
5806  KEVENT event;
5807  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
5808  IO_STATUS_BLOCK localIoStatus;
5809  BOOLEAN synchronousIo;
5810 
5811  PAGED_CODE();
5812 
5813  //
5814  // Reference the file object here so that no special checks need be made
5815  // in I/O completion to determine whether or not to dereference the file
5816  // object.
5817  //
5818 
5819  ObReferenceObject( FileObject );
5820 
5821  //
5822  // Make a special check here to determine whether this is a synchronous
5823  // I/O operation. If it is, then wait here until the file is owned by
5824  // the current thread. If this is not a (serialized) synchronous I/O
5825  // operation, then initialize the local event.
5826  //
5827 
5828  if (FileObject->Flags & FO_SYNCHRONOUS_IO) {
5829 
5830  BOOLEAN interrupted;
5831 
5832  if (!IopAcquireFastLock( FileObject )) {
5833  status = IopAcquireFileObjectLock( FileObject,
5834  Mode,
5835  (BOOLEAN) ((FileObject->Flags & FO_ALERTABLE_IO) != 0),
5836  &interrupted );
5837  if (interrupted) {
5838  ObDereferenceObject( FileObject );
5839  return status;
5840  }
5841  }
5842  KeClearEvent( &FileObject->Event );
5843  synchronousIo = TRUE;
5844  } else {
5845  KeInitializeEvent( &event, SynchronizationEvent, FALSE );
5846  synchronousIo = FALSE;
5847  }
5848 
5849  //
5850  // Get the address of the target device object.
5851  //
5852 
5853  deviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( FileObject );
5854 
5855  //
5856  // Allocate and initialize the I/O Request Packet (IRP) for this operation.
5857  // The allocation is performed with an exception handler in case the
5858  // caller does not have enough quota to allocate the packet.
5859  //
5860 
5861  irp = IoAllocateIrp( deviceObject->StackSize, !synchronousIo );
5862  if (!irp) {
5863 
5864  //
5865  // An IRP could not be allocated. Cleanup and return an appropriate
5866  // error status code.
5867  //
5868 
5869  IopAllocateIrpCleanup( FileObject, (PKEVENT) NULL );
5870 
5871  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
5872  }
5873  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = FileObject;
5874  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = PsGetCurrentThread();
5875  irp->RequestorMode = Mode;
5876 
5877  //
5878  // Fill in the service independent parameters in the IRP.
5879  //
5880 
5881  if (synchronousIo) {
5882  irp->UserEvent = (PKEVENT) NULL;
5883  } else {
5884  irp->UserEvent = &event;
5885  irp->Flags = IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API;
5886  }
5887  irp->UserIosb = &localIoStatus;
5888  irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine = (PIO_APC_ROUTINE) NULL;
5889 
5890  //
5891  // Get a pointer to the stack location for the first driver. This will be
5892  // used to pass the original function codes and parameters.
5893  //
5894 
5895  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
5896  irpSp->MajorFunction = FileInformation ?
5897  IRP_MJ_QUERY_INFORMATION :
5898  IRP_MJ_QUERY_VOLUME_INFORMATION;
5899  irpSp->FileObject = FileObject;
5900 
5901  //
5902  // Set the system buffer address to the address of the caller's buffer and
5903  // set the flags so that the buffer is not deallocated.
5904  //
5905 
5906  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer = Information;
5907  irp->Flags |= IRP_BUFFERED_IO;
5908 
5909  //
5910  // Copy the caller's parameters to the service-specific portion of the
5911  // IRP.
5912  //
5913 
5914  if (FileInformation) {
5915  irpSp->Parameters.QueryFile.Length = Length;
5916  irpSp->Parameters.QueryFile.FileInformationClass = InformationClass;
5917  } else {
5918  irpSp->Parameters.QueryVolume.Length = Length;
5919  irpSp->Parameters.QueryVolume.FsInformationClass = InformationClass;
5920  }
5921 
5922  //
5923  // Insert the packet at the head of the IRP list for the thread.
5924  //
5925 
5926  IopQueueThreadIrp( irp );
5927 
5928  //
5929  // Now simply invoke the driver at its dispatch entry with the IRP.
5930  //
5931 
5932  status = IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp );
5933 
5934  //
5935  // If this operation was a synchronous I/O operation, check the return
5936  // status to determine whether or not to wait on the file object. If
5937  // the file object is to be waited on, wait for the operation to complete
5938  // and obtain the final status from the file object itself.
5939  //
5940 
5941  if (synchronousIo) {
5942  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
5943  status = KeWaitForSingleObject( &FileObject->Event,
5944  Executive,
5945  Mode,
5946  (BOOLEAN) ((FileObject->Flags & FO_ALERTABLE_IO) != 0),
5947  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
5948  if (status == STATUS_ALERTED) {
5949  IopCancelAlertedRequest( &FileObject->Event, irp );
5950  }
5951  status = FileObject->FinalStatus;
5952  }
5953  IopReleaseFileObjectLock( FileObject );
5954 
5955  } else {
5956 
5957  //
5958  // This is a normal synchronous I/O operation, as opposed to a
5959  // serialized synchronous I/O operation. For this case, wait
5960  // for the local event and copy the final status information
5961  // back to the caller.
5962  //
5963 
5964  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
5965  (VOID) KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
5966  Executive,
5967  KernelMode,
5968  FALSE,
5969  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
5970  status = localIoStatus.Status;
5971  }
5972  }
5973 
5974  *ReturnedLength = (ULONG) localIoStatus.Information;
5975  return status;
5976 }
5977 
5978 VOID
5979 IopRaiseHardError(
5980  IN PVOID NormalContext,
5981  IN PVOID SystemArgument1,
5982  IN PVOID SystemArgument2
5983  )
5984 
5985 /*++
5986 
5987 Routine Description:
5988 
5989  This routine raises a hard error popup in the context of the current
5990  thread. The APC was used to get into the context of this thread so that
5991  the popup would be sent to the appropriate port.
5992 
5993 Arguments:
5994 
5995  NormalContext - Supplies a pointer to the I/O Request Packet (IRP) that
5996  was initially used to request the operation that has failed.
5997 
5998  SystemArgument1 - Supplies a pointer to the media's volume parameter block.
5999  See IoRaiseHardError documentation for more information.
6000 
6001  SystemArgument2 - Supplies a pointer to the real device object. See
6002  IoRaiseHardError documentation for more information.
6003 
6004 Return Value:
6005 
6006  None.
6007 
6008 --*/
6009 
6010 {
6011  ULONG_PTR parameters[3];
6012  ULONG numberOfParameters;
6013  ULONG parameterMask;
6014  ULONG response;
6015  NTSTATUS status;
6016  PIRP irp = (PIRP) NormalContext;
6017  PVPB vpb = (PVPB) SystemArgument1;
6018  PDEVICE_OBJECT realDeviceObject = (PDEVICE_OBJECT) SystemArgument2;
6019 
6020  ULONG length = 0;
6021  POBJECT_NAME_INFORMATION objectName;
6022 
6023  UNICODE_STRING labelName;
6024 
6025  //
6026  // Determine the name of the device and the volume label of the offending
6027  // media. Start by determining the size of the DeviceName, and allocate
6028  // enough storage for both the ObjectName structure and the string
6029  //
6030 
6031  ObQueryNameString( realDeviceObject, NULL, 0, &length );
6032 
6033  if ((objectName = ExAllocatePool(PagedPool, length)) == NULL) {
6034 
6035  status = STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
6036 
6037  } else {
6038 
6039  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
6040  }
6041 
6042  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status ) ||
6043  !NT_SUCCESS( status = ObQueryNameString( realDeviceObject,
6044  objectName,
6045  length,
6046  &response ) )) {
6047 
6048  //
6049  // Allocation of the pool to put up this popup did not work or
6050  // something else failed, so there isn't really much that can be
6051  // done here. Simply return an error back to the user.
6052  //
6053 
6054  if (objectName) {
6055  ExFreePool( objectName );
6056  }
6057 
6058  irp->IoStatus.Status = status;
6059  irp->IoStatus.Information = 0;
6060 
6061  IoCompleteRequest( irp, IO_DISK_INCREMENT );
6062 
6063  return;
6064  }
6065 
6066  //
6067  // The volume label has a max size of 32 characters (Unicode). Convert
6068  // it to a Unicode string for output in the popup message.
6069  //
6070 
6071  if (vpb != NULL && vpb->Flags & VPB_MOUNTED) {
6072 
6073  labelName.Buffer = &vpb->VolumeLabel[0];
6074  labelName.Length = vpb->VolumeLabelLength;
6075  labelName.MaximumLength = MAXIMUM_VOLUME_LABEL_LENGTH;
6076 
6077  } else {
6078 
6079  RtlInitUnicodeString( &labelName, NULL );
6080  }
6081 
6082  //
6083  // Different pop-ups have different printf formats. Depending on the
6084  // specific error value, adjust the parameters.
6085  //
6086 
6087  switch( irp->IoStatus.Status ) {
6088 
6089  case STATUS_MEDIA_WRITE_PROTECTED:
6090  case STATUS_WRONG_VOLUME:
6091 
6092  numberOfParameters = 3;
6093  parameterMask = 3;
6094 
6095  parameters[0] = (ULONG_PTR) &labelName;
6096  parameters[1] = (ULONG_PTR) &objectName->Name;
6097  parameters[2] = (ULONG_PTR) &PsGetCurrentProcess()->UniqueProcessId;
6098 
6099  break;
6100 
6101  case STATUS_DEVICE_NOT_READY:
6102  case STATUS_IO_TIMEOUT:
6103  case STATUS_NO_MEDIA_IN_DEVICE:
6104  case STATUS_UNRECOGNIZED_MEDIA:
6105 
6106  numberOfParameters = 2;
6107  parameterMask = 1;
6108 
6109  parameters[0] = (ULONG_PTR) &objectName->Name;
6110  parameters[1] = (ULONG_PTR) &PsGetCurrentProcess()->UniqueProcessId;
6111  parameters[2] = 0;
6112 
6113  break;
6114 
6115  default:
6116 
6117  numberOfParameters = 0;
6118  parameterMask = 0;
6119 
6120  }
6121 
6122  //
6123  // Simply raise the hard error.
6124  //
6125 
6126  if (ExReadyForErrors) {
6127  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp = IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation( irp );
6128  BOOLEAN attached = FALSE;
6129 
6130  if ((irpSp->MajorFunction == IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL) &&
6131  (irpSp->MinorFunction == IRP_MN_MOUNT_VOLUME)) {
6132 
6133  KeAttachProcess( &(THREAD_TO_PROCESS( irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread ))->Pcb );
6134 
6135  attached = TRUE;
6136  }
6137 
6138  status = ExRaiseHardError( irp->IoStatus.Status,
6139  numberOfParameters,
6140  parameterMask,
6141  parameters,
6142  OptionCancelTryContinue,
6143  &response );
6144 
6145  if (attached) {
6146 
6147  KeDetachProcess();
6148  }
6149 
6150  } else {
6151 
6152  status = STATUS_UNSUCCESSFUL;
6153  response = ResponseReturnToCaller;
6154  }
6155 
6156  //
6157  // Free any pool or other resources that were allocated to output the
6158  // popup.
6159  //
6160 
6161  ExFreePool( objectName );
6162 
6163  //
6164  // If there was a problem, or the user didn't want to retry, just
6165  // complete the request. Otherwise simply call the driver entry
6166  // point and retry the IRP as if it had never been tried before.
6167  //
6168 
6169  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status ) || response != ResponseTryAgain) {
6170 
6171  //
6172  // Before completing the request, make one last check. If this was
6173  // a mount request, and the reason for the failure was t/o, no media,
6174  // or unrecognized media, then set the Information field of the status
6175  // block to indicate whether or not an abort was performed.
6176  //
6177 
6178  if (response == ResponseCancel) {
6179  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp = IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation( irp );
6180  if (irpSp->MajorFunction == IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL &&
6181  irpSp->MinorFunction == IRP_MN_MOUNT_VOLUME) {
6182  irp->IoStatus.Information = IOP_ABORT;
6183  } else {
6184  irp->IoStatus.Status = STATUS_REQUEST_ABORTED;
6185  }
6186  }
6187 
6188  //
6189  // An error was incurred, so zero out the information field before
6190  // completing the request if this was an input operation. Otherwise,
6191  // IopCompleteRequest will try to copy to the user's buffer.
6192  //
6193 
6194  if (irp->Flags & IRP_INPUT_OPERATION) {
6195  irp->IoStatus.Information = 0;
6196  }
6197 
6198  IoCompleteRequest( irp, IO_DISK_INCREMENT );
6199 
6200  } else {
6201 
6202  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp = IoGetCurrentIrpStackLocation( irp );
6203  PDEVICE_OBJECT fsDeviceObject = irpSp->DeviceObject;
6204  PDRIVER_OBJECT driverObject = fsDeviceObject->DriverObject;
6205 
6206  //
6207  // Retry the request from the top.
6208  //
6209 
6210  driverObject->MajorFunction[irpSp->MajorFunction]( fsDeviceObject,
6211  irp );
6212 
6213  }
6214 }
6215 
6216 VOID
6217 IopRaiseInformationalHardError(
6218  IN PVOID NormalContext,
6219  IN PVOID SystemArgument1,
6220  IN PVOID SystemArgument2
6221  )
6222 
6223 /*++
6224 
6225 Routine Description:
6226 
6227  This routine performs the actual pop-up. It will called from either the
6228  hard-error thread, or a APC routine in a user thread after exiting the
6229  file system.
6230 
6231 Arguments:
6232 
6233  NormalContext - Contains the information for the pop-up
6234 
6235  SystemArgument1 - not used.
6236 
6237  SystemArgument1 - not used.
6238 
6239 Return Value:
6240 
6241  None.
6242 
6243 --*/
6244 
6245 {
6246  ULONG parameterPresent;
6247  ULONG_PTR errorParameter;
6248  ULONG errorResponse;
6249  PIOP_HARD_ERROR_PACKET hardErrorPacket;
6250 
6251  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( SystemArgument1 );
6252  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( SystemArgument2 );
6253 
6254  hardErrorPacket = (PIOP_HARD_ERROR_PACKET) NormalContext;
6255 
6256  //
6257  // Simply raise the hard error if the system is ready to accept one.
6258  //
6259 
6260  errorParameter = (ULONG_PTR) &hardErrorPacket->String;
6261 
6262  parameterPresent = (hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer != NULL);
6263 
6264  if (ExReadyForErrors) {
6265  (VOID) ExRaiseHardError( hardErrorPacket->ErrorStatus,
6266  parameterPresent,
6267  parameterPresent,
6268  parameterPresent ? &errorParameter : NULL,
6269  OptionOkNoWait,
6270  &errorResponse );
6271  }
6272 
6273  //
6274  // Now free the packet and the buffer, if one was specified.
6275  //
6276 
6277  if (hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer) {
6278  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket->String.Buffer );
6279  }
6280 
6281  ExFreePool( hardErrorPacket );
6282  InterlockedDecrement(&IopHardError.NumPendingApcPopups);
6283 }

6285 VOID
6286 IopReadyDeviceObjects(
6287  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject
6288  )
6289 
6290 /*++
6291 
6292 Routine Description:
6293 
6294  This routine is invoked to mark all of the device objects owned by the
6295  specified driver as having been fully initialized and therefore ready
6296  for access by other drivers/clients.
6297 
6298 Arguments:
6299 
6300  DriverObject - Supplies a pointer to the driver object for the driver
6301  whose devices are to be marked as being "ready".
6302 
6303 Return Value:
6304 
6305  None.
6306 
6307 --*/
6308 
6309 {
6310  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject = DriverObject->DeviceObject;
6311 
6312  PAGED_CODE();
6313 
6314  //
6315  // Loop through all of the driver's device objects, clearing the
6316  // DO_DEVICE_INITIALIZING flag.
6317  //
6318 
6319  DriverObject->Flags |= DRVO_INITIALIZED;
6320  while (deviceObject) {
6321  deviceObject->Flags &= ~DO_DEVICE_INITIALIZING;
6322  deviceObject = deviceObject->NextDevice;
6323  }
6324 }
6325 
6326 NTSTATUS
6327 IopResurrectDriver(
6328  PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject
6329  )
6330 
6331 /*++
6332 
6333 Routine Description:
6334 
6335  This routine is invoked to clear unload pending flag on all of the device
6336  objects owned by the specified driver, if the unload routine has not run.
6337  This allows the driver to come back to life after a pending unload.
6338 
6339 
6340 Arguments:
6341 
6342  DriverObject - Supplies a pointer to the driver object for the driver
6343  whose devices are to be cleared.
6344 
6345 Return Value:
6346 
6347  Status - Returns success if the driver's unload routine has not run;
6348  otherwise STATUS_IMAGE_ALREADY_LOADED is returned.
6349 
6350 --*/
6351 
6352 {
6353  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject = DriverObject->DeviceObject;
6354  KIRQL irql;
6355 
6356  //
6357  // Acquire the I/O spinlock that protects the device list and
6358  // driver flags.
6359  //
6360 
6361  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
6362 
6363  if (DriverObject->Flags & DRVO_UNLOAD_INVOKED || !deviceObject ||
6364  !(deviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags & DOE_UNLOAD_PENDING)) {
6365 
6366  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
6367  return STATUS_IMAGE_ALREADY_LOADED;
6368  }
6369 
6370  //
6371  // Loop through all of the driver's device objects, clearing the
6372  // DOE_UNLOAD_PENDING flag.
6373  //
6374 
6375  while (deviceObject) {
6376  deviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->ExtensionFlags &= ~DOE_UNLOAD_PENDING;
6377  deviceObject = deviceObject->NextDevice;
6378  }
6379 
6380  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
6381  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
6382 
6383 }
6384 
6385 VOID
6386 IopMarshalIds(
6387  OUT PTRACKING_BUFFER TrackingBuffer,
6388  IN PFILE_VOLUMEID_WITH_TYPE TargetVolumeId,
6389  IN PFILE_OBJECTID_BUFFER TargetObjectId,
6390  IN PFILE_TRACKING_INFORMATION TrackingInfo
6391  )
6392 
6393 /*++
6394 
6395 Routine Description:
6396 
6397  This routine marshals the TargetVolumeId and TargetObjectId
6398  into the supplied TrackingBuffer in a standard remotable format.
6399 
6400  It also clears the DestinationFile handle to NULL, and sets the
6401  ObjectInformationLength to the size of the marshalled data.
6402 
6403 Arguments:
6404 
6405  TrackingBuffer - The buffer to receive the marshalled parameters.
6406 
6407  TargetVolumeId - The volume id to marshal.
6408 
6409  TargetObjectId - The object id to marshal.
6410 
6411  TrackingInfo - The additional tracking information to marshal.
6412 
6413 --*/
6414 
6415 {
6416  ULONG ObjectInformationLength = 0;
6417 
6418  TrackingBuffer->TrackingInformation.DestinationFile = (HANDLE) NULL;
6419 
6420  RtlZeroMemory( &TrackingBuffer->TrackingInformation.ObjectInformation[ ObjectInformationLength ],
6421  sizeof(TargetVolumeId->Type) );
6422 
6423  RtlCopyMemory( &TrackingBuffer->TrackingInformation.ObjectInformation[ ObjectInformationLength ],
6424  &TargetVolumeId->Type,
6425  sizeof(TargetVolumeId->Type) );
6426  ObjectInformationLength += sizeof(TargetVolumeId->Type);
6427 
6428  RtlCopyMemory( &TrackingBuffer->TrackingInformation.ObjectInformation[ ObjectInformationLength ],
6429  &TargetVolumeId->VolumeId[0],
6430  sizeof(TargetVolumeId->VolumeId) );
6431  ObjectInformationLength += sizeof(TargetVolumeId->VolumeId);
6432 
6433  RtlCopyMemory( &TrackingBuffer->TrackingInformation.ObjectInformation[ ObjectInformationLength ],
6434  &TargetObjectId->ObjectId[0],
6435  sizeof(TargetObjectId->ObjectId) );
6436  ObjectInformationLength += sizeof(TargetObjectId->ObjectId);
6437 
6438  RtlCopyMemory( &TrackingBuffer->TrackingInformation.ObjectInformation[ ObjectInformationLength ],
6439  &TrackingInfo->ObjectInformation[0],
6440  TrackingInfo->ObjectInformationLength );
6441  ObjectInformationLength += TrackingInfo->ObjectInformationLength;
6442 
6443  TrackingBuffer->TrackingInformation.ObjectInformationLength = ObjectInformationLength;
6444 
6445 }
6446 
6447 VOID
6448 IopUnMarshalIds(
6449  IN FILE_TRACKING_INFORMATION * TrackingInformation,
6450  OUT FILE_VOLUMEID_WITH_TYPE * TargetVolumeId,
6451  OUT GUID * TargetObjectId,
6452  OUT GUID * TargetMachineId
6453  )
6454 
6455 /*++
6456 
6457 Routine Description:
6458 
6459  This routine unmarshals the TargetVolumeId and TargetObjectId
6460  from the supplied TrackingInformation from a standard remotable format.
6461 
6462 Arguments:
6463 
6464  TrackingInformation - The buffer containing the marshalled parameters.
6465 
6466  TargetVolumeId - Buffer to receive the volume id.
6467 
6468  TargetObjectId - Buffer to receive the object id.
6469 
6470  TargetMachineId - Buffer to receive the machine id.
6471 
6472 --*/
6473 
6474 {
6475  ULONG ObjectInformationLength = 0;
6476 
6477  RtlCopyMemory( &TargetVolumeId->Type,
6478  &TrackingInformation->ObjectInformation[ ObjectInformationLength ],
6479  sizeof(TargetVolumeId->Type) );
6480  ObjectInformationLength += sizeof(TargetVolumeId->Type);
6481 
6482 
6483  RtlCopyMemory( &TargetVolumeId->VolumeId[0],
6484  &TrackingInformation->ObjectInformation[ ObjectInformationLength ],
6485  sizeof(TargetVolumeId->VolumeId) );
6486  ObjectInformationLength += sizeof(TargetVolumeId->VolumeId);
6487 
6488  RtlCopyMemory( TargetObjectId,
6489  &TrackingInformation->ObjectInformation[ ObjectInformationLength ],
6490  sizeof(*TargetObjectId) );
6491  ObjectInformationLength += sizeof(*TargetObjectId);
6492 
6493  if( TrackingInformation->ObjectInformationLength > ObjectInformationLength ) {
6494  RtlCopyMemory( TargetMachineId,
6495  &TrackingInformation->ObjectInformation[ ObjectInformationLength ],
6496  min( sizeof(*TargetMachineId), TrackingInformation->ObjectInformationLength - ObjectInformationLength) );
6497  // ObjectInformationLength += sizeof(GUID);
6498  }
6499 }

6501 
6502 NTSTATUS
6503 IopSendMessageToTrackService(
6504  IN PFILE_VOLUMEID_WITH_TYPE SourceVolumeId,
6505  IN PFILE_OBJECTID_BUFFER SourceObjectId,
6506  IN PFILE_TRACKING_INFORMATION TargetObjectInformation
6507  )
6508 
6509 /*++
6510 
6511 Routine Description:
6512 
6513  This routine is invoked to send a message to the user-mode link tracking
6514  service to inform it that a file has been moved so that it can track it
6515  by its object ID.
6516 
6517 Arguments:
6518 
6519  SourceVolumeId - Volume ID of the source file.
6520 
6521  SourceObjectId - Object ID of the source file.
6522 
6523  TargetObjectInformation - Volume ID, object ID of the target file.
6524 
6525 Return Value:
6526 
6527  The final function value is the final completion status of the operation.
6528 
6529 
6530 --*/
6531 
6532 {
6533  typedef struct _LINK_TRACKING_MESSAGE {
6534  NTSTATUS Status;
6535  ULONG Request;
6536  FILE_VOLUMEID_WITH_TYPE SourceVolumeId; // src vol type & id
6537  FILE_OBJECTID_BUFFER SourceObjectId; // src obj id & birth info
6538  FILE_VOLUMEID_WITH_TYPE TargetVolumeId; // tgt vol type & id
6539  GUID TargetObjectId; // tgt obj id
6540  GUID TargetMachineId;
6541  } LINK_TRACKING_MESSAGE, *PLINK_TRACKING_MESSAGE;
6542 
6543  typedef struct _LINK_TRACKING_RESPONSE {
6544  NTSTATUS Status;
6545  } LINK_TRACKING_RESPONSE, *PLINK_TRACKING_RESPONSE;
6546 
6547  PPORT_MESSAGE portMessage;
6548  PPORT_MESSAGE portReplyMessage;
6549  CHAR portReply[ 256 ];
6550  PLINK_TRACKING_MESSAGE requestMessage;
6551  PLINK_TRACKING_RESPONSE replyMessage;
6552  NTSTATUS status;
6553  ULONG loopCount = 0;
6554  KPROCESSOR_MODE PreviousMode;
6555 
6556  PAGED_CODE();
6557 
6558  PreviousMode = KeGetPreviousMode();
6559  //
6560  // Begin by determining whether or not the LPC port to the link tracking
6561  // service has been opened. If not, then attempt to open it now.
6562  //
6563 
6564 retry:
6565 
6566  if (!IopLinkTrackingServiceObject) {
6567 
6568  //
6569  // The port has not yet been opened. Check to see whether or not
6570  // the service has been started. If not, then get out now as there
6571  // will be no port if the service is not running.
6572  //
6573 
6574  if (!KeReadStateEvent( IopLinkTrackingServiceEvent )) {
6575  return STATUS_NO_TRACKING_SERVICE;
6576  }
6577 
6578  for (;; ) {
6579  status = KeWaitForSingleObject(&IopLinkTrackingPortObject,
6580  Executive,
6581  PreviousMode,
6582  FALSE,
6583  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
6584 
6585  if ((status == STATUS_USER_APC) || (status == STATUS_ALERTED)) {
6586  return status;
6587  }
6588 
6589  //
6590  // There is no referenced object pointer to the
6591  // link tracking port so open it.
6592  //
6593  if (!IopLinkTrackingServiceObject) {
6594  ExInitializeWorkItem(
6595  &IopLinkTrackingPacket.WorkQueueItem,
6596  IopConnectLinkTrackingPort,
6597  &IopLinkTrackingPacket);
6598  (VOID)KeResetEvent(&IopLinkTrackingPacket.Event);
6599  ExQueueWorkItem( &IopLinkTrackingPacket.WorkQueueItem,
6600  DelayedWorkQueue );
6601  status = KeWaitForSingleObject(
6602  &IopLinkTrackingPacket.Event,
6603  Executive,
6604  PreviousMode,
6605  FALSE,
6606  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
6607 
6608  if ((status == STATUS_USER_APC) || (status == STATUS_ALERTED)) {
6609  NOTHING;
6610  } else if (!NT_SUCCESS( IopLinkTrackingPacket.FinalStatus )) {
6611  status = IopLinkTrackingPacket.FinalStatus;
6612  }
6613 
6614  KeSetEvent(&IopLinkTrackingPortObject,
6615  0,
6616  FALSE);
6617  if (status == STATUS_SUCCESS) {
6618  break;
6619  } else {
6620  return status;
6621  }
6622 
6623  } else {
6624  //
6625  // The connection is established.
6626  //
6627 
6628  KeSetEvent(&IopLinkTrackingPortObject,
6629  0,
6630  FALSE);
6631  break;
6632  }
6633  }
6634  }
6635 
6636  //
6637  // Form a message from the input parameters and send it to the caller.
6638  //
6639 
6640  portMessage = ExAllocatePool( PagedPool,
6641  sizeof( LINK_TRACKING_MESSAGE ) +
6642  sizeof( PORT_MESSAGE ) );
6643  if (!portMessage) {
6644  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
6645  }
6646 
6647  requestMessage = (PLINK_TRACKING_MESSAGE) (portMessage + 1);
6648  RtlZeroMemory( requestMessage, sizeof(*requestMessage) );
6649 
6650  requestMessage->Status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
6651  requestMessage->Request = 0;
6652 
6653  RtlCopyMemory( &requestMessage->SourceVolumeId,
6654  SourceVolumeId,
6655  sizeof( FILE_VOLUMEID_WITH_TYPE ) );
6656 
6657  RtlCopyMemory( &requestMessage->SourceObjectId,
6658  SourceObjectId,
6659  sizeof( FILE_OBJECTID_BUFFER ) );
6660 
6661  IopUnMarshalIds( TargetObjectInformation,
6662  &requestMessage->TargetVolumeId,
6663  &requestMessage->TargetObjectId,
6664  &requestMessage->TargetMachineId);
6665 
6666  portMessage->u1.s1.TotalLength = (USHORT) (sizeof( PORT_MESSAGE ) +
6667  sizeof( LINK_TRACKING_MESSAGE ));
6668  portMessage->u1.s1.DataLength = (USHORT) sizeof( LINK_TRACKING_MESSAGE );
6669  portMessage->u2.ZeroInit = 0;
6670 
6671  status = LpcRequestWaitReplyPort( IopLinkTrackingServiceObject,
6672  portMessage,
6673  (PPORT_MESSAGE) &portReply[0] );
6674  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
6675  if (status == STATUS_PORT_DISCONNECTED) {
6676  status = KeWaitForSingleObject(&IopLinkTrackingPortObject,
6677  Executive,
6678  PreviousMode,
6679  FALSE,
6680  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
6681  ObDereferenceObject( IopLinkTrackingServiceObject );
6682  IopLinkTrackingServiceObject = NULL;
6683  KeSetEvent(&IopLinkTrackingPortObject,
6684  0,
6685  FALSE);
6686  if (!loopCount) {
6687  loopCount += 1;
6688  goto retry;
6689  }
6690  }
6691  }
6692 
6693  if (NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
6694  portReplyMessage = (PPORT_MESSAGE) &portReply[0];
6695  replyMessage = (PLINK_TRACKING_RESPONSE) (portReplyMessage + 1);
6696  status = replyMessage->Status;
6697  }
6698 
6699  return status;
6700 }
6701 
6702 NTSTATUS
6703 IopSetEaOrQuotaInformationFile(
6704  IN HANDLE FileHandle,
6705  OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock,
6706  IN PVOID Buffer,
6707  IN ULONG Length,
6708  IN BOOLEAN SetEa
6709  )
6710 
6711 /*++
6712 
6713 Routine Description:
6714 
6715  This routine is invoked by the NtSetEa[Quota]InformationFile system services
6716  to either modify the EAs on a file or the quota entries on a volume. All of
6717  the specified entries in the buffer are made to the file or volume.
6718 
6719 Arguments:
6720 
6721  FileHandle - Supplies a handle to the file/volume for which the entries are
6722  to be applied.
6723 
6724  IoStatusBlock - Address of the caller's I/O status block.
6725 
6726  Buffer - Supplies a buffer containing the entries to be added/modified.
6727 
6728  Length - Supplies the length, in bytes, of the buffer.
6729 
6730  SetEa - A BOOLEAN that indicates whether to change the EAs on a file or
6731  the quota entries on the volume.
6732 
6733 Return Value:
6734 
6735  The status returned is the final completion status of the operation.
6736 
6737 --*/
6738 
6739 {
6740  PIRP irp;
6741  NTSTATUS status;
6742  PFILE_OBJECT fileObject;
6743  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
6744  PKEVENT event = (PKEVENT) NULL;
6745  KPROCESSOR_MODE requestorMode;
6746  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
6747  IO_STATUS_BLOCK localIoStatus;
6748  BOOLEAN synchronousIo;
6749  PETHREAD CurrentThread;
6750 
6751  PAGED_CODE();
6752 
6753  //
6754  // Get the previous mode; i.e., the mode of the caller.
6755  //
6756 
6757  CurrentThread = PsGetCurrentThread ();
6758  requestorMode = KeGetPreviousModeByThread(&CurrentThread->Tcb);
6759 
6760  if (requestorMode != KernelMode) {
6761 
6762  //
6763  // The caller's access mode is user, so probe each of the arguments
6764  // and capture them as necessary. If any failures occur, the condition
6765  // handler will be invoked to handle them. It will simply cleanup and
6766  // return an access violation status code back to the system service
6767  // dispatcher.
6768  //
6769 
6770  try {
6771 
6772  //
6773  // The IoStatusBlock parameter must be writeable by the caller.
6774  //
6775 
6776  ProbeForWriteIoStatus( IoStatusBlock);
6777 
6778  //
6779  // The Buffer parameter must be readable by the caller.
6780  //
6781 
6782  ProbeForRead( Buffer, Length, sizeof( ULONG ) );
6783 
6784  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
6785 
6786  //
6787  // An exception was incurred while probing the caller's parameters.
6788  // Cleanup and return an appropriate error status code.
6789  //
6790 
6791  return GetExceptionCode();
6792  }
6793  }
6794 
6795  //
6796  // There were no blatant errors so far, so reference the file object so
6797  // the target device object can be found. Note that if the handle does
6798  // not refer to a file object, or if the caller does not have the required
6799  // access to the file, then it will fail.
6800  //
6801 
6802  status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle( FileHandle,
6803  SetEa ? FILE_WRITE_EA : FILE_WRITE_DATA,
6804  IoFileObjectType,
6805  requestorMode,
6806  (PVOID *) &fileObject,
6807  NULL );
6808  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
6809  return status;
6810  }
6811 
6812  //
6813  // Make a special check here to determine whether this is a synchronous
6814  // I/O operation. If it is, then wait here until the file is owned by
6815  // the current thread. If this is not a (serialized) synchronous I/O
6816  // operation, then allocate and initialize the local event.
6817  //
6818 
6819  if (fileObject->Flags & FO_SYNCHRONOUS_IO) {
6820 
6821  BOOLEAN interrupted;
6822 
6823  if (!IopAcquireFastLock( fileObject )) {
6824  status = IopAcquireFileObjectLock( fileObject,
6825  requestorMode,
6826  (BOOLEAN) ((fileObject->Flags & FO_ALERTABLE_IO) != 0),
6827  &interrupted );
6828  if (interrupted) {
6829  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
6830  return status;
6831  }
6832  }
6833  synchronousIo = TRUE;
6834  } else {
6835 
6836  //
6837  // This is a synchronous API being invoked for a file that is opened
6838  // for asynchronous I/O. This means that this system service is
6839  // to synchronize the completion of the operation before returning
6840  // to the caller. A local event is used to do this.
6841  //
6842 
6843  event = ExAllocatePool( NonPagedPool, sizeof( KEVENT ) );
6844  if (!event) {
6845  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
6846  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
6847  }
6848  KeInitializeEvent( event, SynchronizationEvent, FALSE );
6849  synchronousIo = FALSE;
6850  }
6851 
6852  //
6853  // Set the file object to the Not-Signaled state.
6854  //
6855 
6856  KeClearEvent( &fileObject->Event );
6857 
6858  //
6859  // Get the address of the target device object.
6860  //
6861 
6862  deviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( fileObject );
6863 
6864  //
6865  // Allocate and initialize the I/O Request Packet (IRP) for this operation.
6866  // The allocation is performed with an exception handler in case the
6867  // caller does not have enough quota to allocate the packet.
6868 
6869  irp = IoAllocateIrp( deviceObject->StackSize, FALSE );
6870  if (!irp) {
6871 
6872  //
6873  // An IRP could not be allocated. Cleanup and return an appropriate
6874  // error status code.
6875  //
6876 
6877  if (!(fileObject->Flags & FO_SYNCHRONOUS_IO)) {
6878  ExFreePool( event );
6879  }
6880 
6881  IopAllocateIrpCleanup( fileObject, (PKEVENT) NULL );
6882 
6883  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
6884  }
6885  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = fileObject;
6886  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = CurrentThread;
6887  irp->RequestorMode = requestorMode;
6888 
6889  //
6890  // Fill in the service independent parameters in the IRP.
6891  //
6892 
6893  if (synchronousIo) {
6894  irp->UserEvent = (PKEVENT) NULL;
6895  irp->UserIosb = IoStatusBlock;
6896  } else {
6897  irp->UserEvent = event;
6898  irp->UserIosb = &localIoStatus;
6899  irp->Flags = IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API;
6900  }
6901  irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine = (PIO_APC_ROUTINE) NULL;
6902 
6903  //
6904  // Get a pointer to the stack location for the first driver. This will be
6905  // used to pass the original function codes and parameters.
6906  //
6907 
6908  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
6909  irpSp->MajorFunction = SetEa ? IRP_MJ_SET_EA : IRP_MJ_SET_QUOTA;
6910  irpSp->FileObject = fileObject;
6911 
6912  //
6913  // Now determine whether this driver expects to have data buffered to it
6914  // or whether it performs direct I/O. This is based on the DO_BUFFERED_IO
6915  // flag in the device object. if the flag is set, then a system buffer is
6916  // allocated and driver's data is copied to it. If the DO_DIRECT_IO flag
6917  // is set in the device object, then a Memory Descriptor List (MDL) is
6918  // allocated and the caller's buffer is locked down using it. Finally, if
6919  // the driver specifies neither of the flags, then simply pass the address
6920  // and length of the buffer and allow the driver to perform all of the
6921  // checking and buffering if any is required.
6922  //
6923 
6924  if (deviceObject->Flags & DO_BUFFERED_IO) {
6925 
6926  PVOID systemBuffer;
6927  ULONG errorOffset;
6928 
6929  if (Length) {
6930  //
6931  // The driver wishes the caller's buffer to be copied into an
6932  // intermediary buffer. Allocate the system buffer and specify
6933  // that it should be deallocated on completion. Also check to
6934  // ensure that the caller's EA list or quota list is valid. All
6935  // of this is performed within an exception handler that will perform
6936  // cleanup if the operation fails.
6937  //
6938 
6939  try {
6940 
6941  //
6942  // Allocate the intermediary system buffer and charge the caller
6943  // quota for its allocation. Copy the caller's buffer into the
6944  // system buffer and check to ensure that it is valid.
6945  //
6946 
6947  systemBuffer = ExAllocatePoolWithQuota( NonPagedPool, Length );
6948 
6949  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer = systemBuffer;
6950 
6951  RtlCopyMemory( systemBuffer, Buffer, Length );
6952 
6953  if (SetEa) {
6954  status = IoCheckEaBufferValidity( systemBuffer,
6955  Length,
6956  &errorOffset );
6957  } else {
6958  status = IoCheckQuotaBufferValidity( systemBuffer,
6959  Length,
6960  &errorOffset );
6961  }
6962 
6963  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
6964  IoStatusBlock->Status = status;
6965  IoStatusBlock->Information = errorOffset;
6966  ExRaiseStatus( status );
6967  }
6968 
6969  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
6970 
6971  //
6972  // An exception was incurred while allocating the buffer, copying
6973  // the caller's data into it, or walking the buffer. Determine
6974  // what happened, cleanup, and return an appropriate error status
6975  // code.
6976  //
6977 
6978  IopExceptionCleanup( fileObject,
6979  irp,
6980  (PKEVENT) NULL,
6981  event );
6982 
6983  return GetExceptionCode();
6984 
6985  }
6986 
6987  //
6988  // Set the flags so that the completion code knows to deallocate the
6989  // buffer.
6990  //
6991 
6992  irp->Flags |= IRP_BUFFERED_IO | IRP_DEALLOCATE_BUFFER;
6993 
6994  } else {
6995  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer = NULL;
6996  irp->UserBuffer = Buffer;
6997  }
6998 
6999 
7000  } else if (deviceObject->Flags & DO_DIRECT_IO) {
7001 
7002  PMDL mdl;
7003 
7004  if (Length) {
7005  //
7006  // This is a direct I/O operation. Allocate an MDL and invoke the
7007  // memory management routine to lock the buffer into memory. This is
7008  // done using an exception handler that will perform cleanup if the
7009  // operation fails.
7010  //
7011 
7012  mdl = (PMDL) NULL;
7013 
7014  try {
7015 
7016  //
7017  // Allocate an MDL, charging quota for it, and hang it off of the
7018  // IRP. Probe and lock the pages associated with the caller's
7019  // buffer for read access and fill in the MDL with the PFNs of those
7020  // pages.
7021  //
7022 
7023  mdl = IoAllocateMdl( Buffer, Length, FALSE, TRUE, irp );
7024  if (!mdl) {
7025  ExRaiseStatus( STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES );
7026  }
7027  IopProbeAndLockPages( mdl, requestorMode, IoReadAccess, deviceObject, irpSp->MajorFunction);
7028 
7029  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
7030 
7031  //
7032  // An exception was incurred while either probing the caller's
7033  // buffer or allocating the MDL. Determine what actually happened,
7034  // clean everything up, and return an appropriate error status code.
7035  //
7036 
7037  IopExceptionCleanup( fileObject,
7038  irp,
7039  (PKEVENT) NULL,
7040  event );
7041 
7042  return GetExceptionCode();
7043 
7044  }
7045  }
7046 
7047  } else {
7048 
7049  //
7050  // Pass the address of the user's buffer so the driver has access to
7051  // it. It is now the driver's responsibility to do everything.
7052  //
7053 
7054  irp->UserBuffer = Buffer;
7055 
7056  }
7057 
7058  //
7059  // Copy the caller's parameters to the service-specific portion of the
7060  // IRP.
7061  //
7062 
7063  if (SetEa) {
7064  irpSp->Parameters.SetEa.Length = Length;
7065  } else {
7066  irpSp->Parameters.SetQuota.Length = Length;
7067  }
7068 
7069  //
7070  // Queue the packet, call the driver, and synchronize appropriately with
7071  // I/O completion.
7072  //
7073 
7074  status = IopSynchronousServiceTail( deviceObject,
7075  irp,
7076  fileObject,
7077  FALSE,
7078  requestorMode,
7079  synchronousIo,
7080  OtherTransfer );
7081 
7082  //
7083  // If the file for this operation was not opened for synchronous I/O, then
7084  // synchronization of completion of the I/O operation has not yet occurred
7085  // since the allocated event must be used for synchronous APIs on files
7086  // opened for asynchronous I/O. Synchronize the completion of the I/O
7087  // operation now.
7088  //
7089 
7090  if (!synchronousIo) {
7091 
7092  status = IopSynchronousApiServiceTail( status,
7093  event,
7094  irp,
7095  requestorMode,
7096  &localIoStatus,
7097  IoStatusBlock );
7098  }
7099 
7100  return status;
7101 }
7102 
7103 NTSTATUS
7104 IopSetRemoteLink(
7105  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
7106  IN PFILE_OBJECT DestinationFileObject OPTIONAL,
7107  IN PFILE_TRACKING_INFORMATION FileInformation OPTIONAL
7108  )
7109 
7110 /*++
7111 
7112 Routine Description:
7113 
7114  This routine is invoked to remote an NtSetInformationFile API call via an
7115  FSCTL to the Redirector. The call will cause the remote system to perform
7116  the service call to track the link for a file which was just moved.
7117 
7118 Arguments:
7119 
7120  FileObject - Supplies the file object for the file that was moved.
7121 
7122  DestinationFileObject - Optionally supplies the file object for the new
7123  destination location for the file.
7124 
7125  FileInformation - Optionally supplies the volume and file object IDs of
7126  the target file.
7127 
7128 Return Value:
7129 
7130  The final function value is the final completion status of the operation.
7131 
7132 --*/
7133 
7134 {
7135  REMOTE_LINK_BUFFER remoteBuffer;
7136  IO_STATUS_BLOCK ioStatus;
7137  NTSTATUS status;
7138  PIRP irp;
7139  KEVENT event;
7140  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
7141  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
7142  ULONG length = 0;
7143 
7144  PAGED_CODE();
7145
