7146  //
7147  // Initialize the event structure to synchronize completion of the I/O
7148  // request.
7149  //
7150 
7151  KeInitializeEvent( &event,
7152  NotificationEvent,
7153  FALSE );
7154 
7155  //
7156  // Build an I/O Request Packet to be sent to the file system driver to get
7157  // the volume ID.
7158  //
7159 
7160  deviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( FileObject );
7161 
7162  irp = IoBuildDeviceIoControlRequest( FSCTL_LMR_SET_LINK_TRACKING_INFORMATION,
7163  deviceObject,
7164  NULL,
7165  0,
7166  NULL,
7167  0,
7168  FALSE,
7169  &event,
7170  &ioStatus );
7171  if (!irp) {
7172  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
7173  }
7174 
7175  //
7176  // Initialize the remote link buffer according to the input information.
7177  //
7178 
7179  if (DestinationFileObject) {
7180 
7181  // The FileObject and DestinationFileObject are on the same machine
7182  remoteBuffer.TrackingInformation.TargetFileObject = DestinationFileObject;
7183 
7184  if (FileInformation) {
7185  // Copy the ObjectInformation from the FileInformation buffer into
7186  // the TargetLinkTrackingInformationBuffer. Set 'length' to include
7187  // this buffer.
7188 
7189  remoteBuffer.TrackingInformation.TargetLinkTrackingInformationLength
7190  = length = FileInformation->ObjectInformationLength;
7191  RtlCopyMemory( &remoteBuffer.TrackingInformation.TargetLinkTrackingInformationBuffer,
7192  FileInformation->ObjectInformation,
7193  length );
7194  } else {
7195  // We don't have any extra FileInformation.
7196  remoteBuffer.TrackingInformation.TargetLinkTrackingInformationLength = 0;
7197  }
7198 
7199  // Increment the length to include the size of the non-optional fields in
7200  // REMOTE_LINK_TRACKING_INFORMATION.
7201  length += sizeof( PFILE_OBJECT ) + sizeof( ULONG );
7202 
7203  } else {
7204  // There's no DestinationFileObject, so all the necessary information is in the
7205  // FileInformation structure.
7206  length = FileInformation->ObjectInformationLength + sizeof( HANDLE ) + sizeof( ULONG );
7207  RtlCopyMemory( &remoteBuffer.TrackingInformation,
7208  FileInformation,
7209  length );
7210  remoteBuffer.TrackingInformation.TargetFileObject = NULL;
7211  }
7212 
7213  //
7214  // Fill in the remainder of the IRP to retrieve the object ID for the
7215  // file.
7216  //
7217 
7218  irp->Flags |= IRP_SYNCHRONOUS_API;
7219  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer = &remoteBuffer;
7220  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = FileObject;
7221 
7222  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
7223  irpSp->FileObject = FileObject;
7224  irpSp->MajorFunction = IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL;
7225  irpSp->MinorFunction = IRP_MN_KERNEL_CALL;
7226  irpSp->Parameters.FileSystemControl.InputBufferLength = length;
7227 
7228  //
7229  // Take out another reference to the file object to guarantee that it does
7230  // not get deleted.
7231  //
7232 
7233  ObReferenceObject( FileObject );
7234 
7235  //
7236  // Call the driver to get the request.
7237  //
7238 
7239  status = IoCallDriver( deviceObject, irp );
7240 
7241  //
7242  // Synchronize completion of the request.
7243  //
7244 
7245  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
7246  status = KeWaitForSingleObject( &event,
7247  Executive,
7248  KernelMode,
7249  FALSE,
7250  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
7251  status = ioStatus.Status;
7252  }
7253 
7254  return status;
7255 }
7256 
7257 VOID
7258 IopStartApcHardError(
7259  IN PVOID StartContext
7260  )
7261 
7262 /*++
7263 
7264 Routine Description:
7265 
7266  This function is invoked in an ExWorker thread when we need to do a
7267  hard error pop-up, but the Irp's originating thread is at APC level,
7268  ie. IoPageRead. It starts a thread to hold the pop-up.
7269 
7270 Arguments:
7271 
7272  StartContext - Startup context, contains a IOP_APC_HARD_ERROR_PACKET.
7273 
7274 Return Value:
7275 
7276  None.
7277 
7278 --*/
7279 
7280 {
7281  HANDLE thread;
7282  NTSTATUS status;
7283 
7284  //
7285  // Create the hard error pop-up thread. If for whatever reason we
7286  // can't do this then just complete the Irp with the error.
7287  //
7288 
7289  status = PsCreateSystemThread( &thread,
7290  0,
7291  (POBJECT_ATTRIBUTES)NULL,
7292  (HANDLE)0,
7293  (PCLIENT_ID)NULL,
7294  IopApcHardError,
7295  StartContext );
7296 
7297  if ( !NT_SUCCESS( status ) ) {
7298 
7299 
7300  IoCompleteRequest( ((PIOP_APC_HARD_ERROR_PACKET)StartContext)->Irp,
7301  IO_DISK_INCREMENT );
7302  ExFreePool( StartContext );
7303  return;
7304  }
7305 
7306  //
7307  // Close thread handle
7308  //
7309 
7310  ZwClose(thread);
7311 }
7312 
7313 NTSTATUS
7314 IopSynchronousApiServiceTail(
7315  IN NTSTATUS ReturnedStatus,
7316  IN PKEVENT Event,
7317  IN PIRP Irp,
7318  IN KPROCESSOR_MODE RequestorMode,
7319  IN PIO_STATUS_BLOCK LocalIoStatus,
7320  OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock
7321  )
7322 
7323 /*++
7324 
7325 Routine Description:
7326 
7327  This routine is invoked when a synchronous API is invoked for a file
7328  that has been opened for asynchronous I/O. This function synchronizes
7329  the completion of the I/O operation on the file.
7330 
7331 Arguments:
7332 
7333  ReturnedStatus - Supplies the status that was returned from the call to
7334  IoCallDriver.
7335 
7336  Event - Address of the allocated kernel event to be used for synchronization
7337  of the I/O operation.
7338 
7339  Irp - Address of the I/O Request Packet submitted to the driver.
7340 
7341  RequestorMode - Processor mode of the caller when the operation was
7342  requested.
7343 
7344  LocalIoStatus - Address of the I/O status block used to capture the final
7345  status by the service itself.
7346 
7347  IoStatusBlock - Address of the I/O status block supplied by the caller of
7348  the system service.
7349 
7350 Return Value:
7351 
7352  The function value is the final status of the operation.
7353 
7354 
7355 --*/
7356 
7357 {
7358  NTSTATUS status;
7359 
7360  PAGED_CODE();
7361 
7362  //
7363  // This is a normal synchronous I/O operation, as opposed to a
7364  // serialized synchronous I/O operation. For this case, wait for
7365  // the local event and copy the final status information back to
7366  // the caller.
7367  //
7368 
7369  status = ReturnedStatus;
7370 
7371  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
7372 
7373  status = KeWaitForSingleObject( Event,
7374  Executive,
7375  RequestorMode,
7376  FALSE,
7377  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
7378 
7379  if (status == STATUS_USER_APC) {
7380 
7381  //
7382  // The wait request has ended either because the thread was
7383  // alerted or an APC was queued to this thread, because of
7384  // thread rundown or CTRL/C processing. In either case, try
7385  // to bail out of this I/O request carefully so that the IRP
7386  // completes before this routine exists or the event will not
7387  // be around to set to the Signaled state.
7388  //
7389 
7390  IopCancelAlertedRequest( Event, Irp );
7391 
7392  }
7393 
7394  status = LocalIoStatus->Status;
7395  }
7396 
7397  try {
7398 
7399  *IoStatusBlock = *LocalIoStatus;
7400 
7401  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
7402 
7403  //
7404  // An exception occurred attempting to write the caller's I/O
7405  // status block. Simply change the final status of the operation
7406  // to the exception code.
7407  //
7408 
7409  status = GetExceptionCode();
7410  }
7411 
7412  ExFreePool( Event );
7413 
7414  return status;
7415 }
7416 
7417 NTSTATUS
7418 IopSynchronousServiceTail(
7419  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
7420  IN PIRP Irp,
7421  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
7422  IN BOOLEAN DeferredIoCompletion,
7423  IN KPROCESSOR_MODE RequestorMode,
7424  IN BOOLEAN SynchronousIo,
7425  IN TRANSFER_TYPE TransferType
7426  )
7427 
7428 /*++
7429 
7430 Routine Description:
7431 
7432  This routine is invoked to complete the operation of a system service.
7433  It queues the IRP to the thread's queue, updates the transfer count,
7434  calls the driver, and finally synchronizes completion of the I/O.
7435 
7436 Arguments:
7437 
7438  DeviceObject - Device on which the I/O is to occur.
7439 
7440  Irp - I/O Request Packet representing the I/O operation.
7441 
7442  FileObject - File object for this open instantiation.
7443 
7444  DeferredIoCompletion - Indicates whether deferred completion is possible.
7445 
7446  RequestorMode - Mode in which request was made.
7447 
7448  SynchronousIo - Indicates whether the operation is to be synchronous.
7449 
7450  TransferType - Type of transfer being performed: read, write, or other.
7451 
7452 Return Value:
7453 
7454  The function value is the final status of the operation.
7455 
7456 --*/
7457 
7458 {
7459  NTSTATUS status;
7460 
7461  PAGED_CODE();
7462 
7463  //
7464  // Insert the packet at the head of the IRP list for the thread.
7465  //
7466 
7467  if (!SynchronousIo) {
7468  IopQueueThreadIrp( Irp );
7469  }
7470 
7471  //
7472  // Update the operation count statistic for the current process.
7473  //
7474 
7475  switch( TransferType ) {
7476 
7477  case ReadTransfer:
7478  IopUpdateReadOperationCount();
7479  break;
7480 
7481  case WriteTransfer:
7482  IopUpdateWriteOperationCount();
7483  break;
7484 
7485  case OtherTransfer:
7486  IopUpdateOtherOperationCount();
7487  break;
7488  }
7489 
7490  //
7491  // Now simply invoke the driver at its dispatch entry with the IRP.
7492  //
7493 
7494  status = IoCallDriver( DeviceObject, Irp );
7495 
7496  //
7497  // If deferred I/O completion is possible, check for pending returned
7498  // from the driver. If the driver did not return pending, then the
7499  // packet has not actually been completed yet, so complete it here.
7500  //
7501 
7502  if (DeferredIoCompletion) {
7503 
7504  if (status != STATUS_PENDING) {
7505 
7506  //
7507  // The I/O operation was completed without returning a status of
7508  // pending. This means that at this point, the IRP has not been
7509  // fully completed. Complete it now.
7510  //
7511 
7512  PKNORMAL_ROUTINE normalRoutine;
7513  PVOID normalContext;
7514  KIRQL irql = PASSIVE_LEVEL; // Just to shut up the compiler
7515 
7516  ASSERT( !Irp->PendingReturned );
7517 
7518  if (!SynchronousIo) {
7519  KeRaiseIrql( APC_LEVEL, &irql );
7520  }
7521  IopCompleteRequest( &Irp->Tail.Apc,
7522  &normalRoutine,
7523  &normalContext,
7524  (PVOID *) &FileObject,
7525  &normalContext );
7526 
7527  if (!SynchronousIo) {
7528  KeLowerIrql( irql );
7529  }
7530  }
7531  }
7532 
7533  //
7534  // If this operation was a synchronous I/O operation, check the return
7535  // status to determine whether or not to wait on the file object. If
7536  // the file object is to be waited on, wait for the operation to complete
7537  // and obtain the final status from the file object itself.
7538  //
7539 
7540  if (SynchronousIo) {
7541 
7542  if (status == STATUS_PENDING) {
7543 
7544  status = KeWaitForSingleObject( &FileObject->Event,
7545  Executive,
7546  RequestorMode,
7547  (BOOLEAN) ((FileObject->Flags & FO_ALERTABLE_IO) != 0),
7548  (PLARGE_INTEGER) NULL );
7549 
7550  if (status == STATUS_ALERTED || status == STATUS_USER_APC) {
7551 
7552  //
7553  // The wait request has ended either because the thread was alerted
7554  // or an APC was queued to this thread, because of thread rundown or
7555  // CTRL/C processing. In either case, try to bail out of this I/O
7556  // request carefully so that the IRP completes before this routine
7557  // exists so that synchronization with the file object will remain
7558  // intact.
7559  //
7560 
7561  IopCancelAlertedRequest( &FileObject->Event, Irp );
7562 
7563  }
7564 
7565  status = FileObject->FinalStatus;
7566 
7567  }
7568 
7569  IopReleaseFileObjectLock( FileObject );
7570 
7571  }
7572 
7573  return status;
7574 }
7575 
7576 VOID
7577 IopTimerDispatch(
7578  IN PKDPC Dpc,
7579  IN PVOID DeferredContext,
7580  IN PVOID SystemArgument1,
7581  IN PVOID SystemArgument2
7582  )
7583 
7584 /*++
7585 
7586 Routine Description:
7587 
7588  This routine scans the I/O system timer database and invokes each driver
7589  that has enabled a timer in the list, once every second.
7590 
7591 Arguments:
7592 
7593  Dpc - Supplies a pointer to a control object of type DPC.
7594 
7595  DeferredContext - Optional deferred context; not used.
7596 
7597  SystemArgument1 - Optional argument 1; not used.
7598 
7599  SystemArgument2 - Optional argument 2; not used.
7600 
7601 Return Value:
7602 
7603  None.
7604 
7605 --*/
7606 
7607 {
7608  PLIST_ENTRY timerEntry;
7609  PIO_TIMER timer;
7610  KIRQL irql;
7611  ULONG i;
7612 
7613  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( Dpc );
7614  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( DeferredContext );
7615  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( SystemArgument1 );
7616  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( SystemArgument2 );
7617 
7618  //
7619  // Check to see whether or not there are any timers in the queue that
7620  // have been enabled. If so, then walk the list and invoke all of the
7621  // drivers' routines. Note that if the counter changes, which it can
7622  // because the spin lock is not owned, then a timer routine may be
7623  // missed. However, this is acceptable, since the driver inserting the
7624  // entry could be context switched away from, etc. Therefore, this is
7625  // not a critical resource for the most part.
7626  //
7627 
7628  if (IopTimerCount) {
7629 
7630  //
7631  // There is at least one timer entry in the queue that is enabled.
7632  // Walk the queue and invoke each specified timer routine.
7633  //
7634 
7635  ExAcquireSpinLock( &IopTimerLock, &irql );
7636  i = IopTimerCount;
7637  timerEntry = IopTimerQueueHead.Flink;
7638 
7639  //
7640  // For each entry found that is enabled, invoke the driver's routine
7641  // with its specified context parameter. The local count is used
7642  // to abort the queue traversal when there are more entries in the
7643  // queue, but they are not enabled.
7644  //
7645 
7646  for (timerEntry = IopTimerQueueHead.Flink;
7647  (timerEntry != &IopTimerQueueHead) && i;
7648  timerEntry = timerEntry->Flink ) {
7649 
7650  timer = CONTAINING_RECORD( timerEntry, IO_TIMER, TimerList );
7651 
7652  if (timer->TimerFlag) {
7653  timer->TimerRoutine( timer->DeviceObject, timer->Context );
7654  i--;
7655  }
7656  }
7657  ExReleaseSpinLock( &IopTimerLock, irql );
7658  }
7659 }
7660 
7661 
7662 
7663 
7664 
7665 NTSTATUS
7666 IopTrackLink(
7667  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
7668  IN OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock,
7669  IN PFILE_TRACKING_INFORMATION FileInformation,
7670  IN ULONG Length,
7671  IN PKEVENT Event,
7672  IN KPROCESSOR_MODE RequestorMode
7673  )
7674 
7675 /*++
7676 
7677 Routine Description:
7678 
7679  This routine is invoked to track a link. It tracks the source file's Object
7680  ID to the target file so that links to the source will follow to the new
7681  location of the target.
7682 
7683 Arguments:
7684 
7685  FileObject - Supplies a pointer to the referenced source file object.
7686 
7687  IoStatusBlock - Pointer to the caller's I/O status block.
7688 
7689  FileInformation - A buffer containing the parameters for the move that was
7690  performed.
7691 
7692  Length - Specifies the length of the FileInformation buffer.
7693 
7694  Event - An event to be set to the Signaled state once the operation has been
7695  performed, provided it was successful.
7696 
7697  RequestorMode - Requestor mode of the caller.
7698 
7699 N.B. - Note that the presence of an event indicates that the source file was
7700  opened for asynchronous I/O, otherwise it was opened for synchronous I/O.
7701 
7702 Return Value:
7703 
7704  The status returned is the final completion status of the operation.
7705 
7706 
7707 --*/
7708 
7709 {
7710  PFILE_TRACKING_INFORMATION trackingInfo = NULL;
7711  PFILE_OBJECT dstFileObject = NULL;
7712  FILE_VOLUMEID_WITH_TYPE SourceVolumeId;
7713  FILE_OBJECTID_BUFFER SourceObjectId;
7714  FILE_OBJECTID_BUFFER NormalizedObjectId;
7715  FILE_OBJECTID_BUFFER CrossVolumeObjectId;
7716  FILE_VOLUMEID_WITH_TYPE TargetVolumeId;
7717  FILE_OBJECTID_BUFFER TargetObjectId;
7718  TRACKING_BUFFER trackingBuffer;
7719  NTSTATUS status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
7720 
7721  PAGED_CODE();
7722 
7723  //
7724  // Begin by capturing the caller's buffer, if required.
7725  //
7726 
7727  if (RequestorMode != KernelMode) {
7728 
7729  try {
7730  trackingInfo = ExAllocatePoolWithQuota( PagedPool,
7731  Length );
7732  RtlCopyMemory( trackingInfo, FileInformation, Length );
7733 
7734  if (!trackingInfo->DestinationFile ||
7735  ((Length - FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_TRACKING_INFORMATION, ObjectInformation ))
7736  < trackingInfo->ObjectInformationLength)) {
7737  ExFreePool( trackingInfo );
7738  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
7739  }
7740 
7741  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
7742 
7743  //
7744  // An exception was incurred while allocating the intermediary
7745  // system buffer or while copying the caller's data into the
7746  // buffer. Cleanup and return an appropriate error status code.
7747  //
7748 
7749  if (trackingInfo) {
7750  ExFreePool( trackingInfo );
7751  }
7752 
7753  return GetExceptionCode();
7754  }
7755  } else {
7756  trackingInfo = FileInformation;
7757  }
7758 
7759  //
7760  // If a destination file handle was specified, convert it to a pointer to
7761  // a file object.
7762  //
7763 
7764  if (trackingInfo->DestinationFile) {
7765  status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle( trackingInfo->DestinationFile,
7766  FILE_WRITE_DATA,
7767  IoFileObjectType,
7768  RequestorMode,
7769  (PVOID *) &dstFileObject,
7770  NULL );
7771  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
7772  if (RequestorMode != KernelMode) {
7773  ExFreePool( trackingInfo );
7774  }
7775  return status;
7776  }
7777  }
7778 
7779  try {
7780 
7781  //
7782  // Determine whether this is a local or a remote link tracking
7783  // operation.
7784  //
7785 
7786  if (IsFileLocal( FileObject )) {
7787 
7788  //
7789  // The source file, i.e., the one being moved, is a file local to
7790  // this system. Determine the form of the target file and track
7791  // it accordingly.
7792  //
7793 
7794  if (trackingInfo->DestinationFile) {
7795 
7796  if (IsFileLocal( dstFileObject )) {
7797 
7798  BOOLEAN IdSetOnTarget = FALSE;
7799 
7800  //
7801  // The target file is specified as a handle and it is local.
7802  // Simply perform the query and set locally. Note that if
7803  // the source file does not have an object ID, then no
7804  // tracking will be performed, but it will appear as if the
7805  // operation worked.
7806  //
7807 
7808  status = IopGetSetObjectId( FileObject,
7809  &SourceObjectId,
7810  sizeof( SourceObjectId ),
7811  FSCTL_GET_OBJECT_ID );
7812 
7813  if (status == STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_NOT_FOUND) {
7814  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
7815  leave;
7816  }
7817 
7818  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
7819  leave;
7820  }
7821 
7822  //
7823  // If the extended info field is zero then this file
7824  // has no interesting tracking information.
7825  //
7826  if (RtlCompareMemoryUlong(SourceObjectId.BirthObjectId,
7827  sizeof(SourceObjectId.BirthObjectId),
7828  0) == sizeof(SourceObjectId.BirthObjectId)) {
7829  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
7830  leave;
7831  }
7832 
7833  //
7834  // Get the volume ID of the source and destination
7835  //
7836 
7837  status = IopGetVolumeId( dstFileObject,
7838  &TargetVolumeId,
7839  sizeof( TargetVolumeId ) );
7840  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
7841  leave;
7842  }
7843 
7844  status = IopGetVolumeId( FileObject,
7845  &SourceVolumeId,
7846  sizeof( SourceVolumeId ) );
7847  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
7848  leave;
7849  }
7850 
7851  //
7852  // Delete the ID from the source now, since the
7853  // target may be on the same volume. If there's a
7854  // subsequent error, we'll try to restore it.
7855  //
7856 
7857  status = IopGetSetObjectId( FileObject,
7858  NULL,
7859  0,
7860  FSCTL_DELETE_OBJECT_ID );
7861  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
7862  leave;
7863  }
7864 
7865  //
7866  // Set the ID on the target. If it's a cross-volume
7867  // move, set the bit that indicates same.
7868  //
7869 
7870  CrossVolumeObjectId = TargetObjectId = SourceObjectId;
7871  if( !RtlEqualMemory( &TargetVolumeId.VolumeId[0],
7872  &SourceVolumeId.VolumeId[0],
7873  sizeof(SourceVolumeId.VolumeId) )) {
7874  CrossVolumeObjectId.BirthVolumeId[0] |= 1;
7875  }
7876 
7877  status = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
7878  &CrossVolumeObjectId,
7879  sizeof( CrossVolumeObjectId ),
7880  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID );
7881 
7882  if( status == STATUS_DUPLICATE_NAME ||
7883  status == STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_COLLISION ) {
7884 
7885  // This object ID is already in use on the target volume,
7886  // or the dest file already has an object ID.
7887  // Get the file's ID (or have NTFS generate a new one).
7888 
7889  status = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
7890  &TargetObjectId,
7891  sizeof(TargetObjectId),
7892  FSCTL_CREATE_OR_GET_OBJECT_ID );
7893  if( NT_SUCCESS(status) ) {
7894 
7895  // Write the birth ID
7896 
7897  status = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
7898  &CrossVolumeObjectId.ExtendedInfo[0],
7899  sizeof( CrossVolumeObjectId.ExtendedInfo ),
7900  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID_EXTENDED );
7901  }
7902  }
7903 
7904  if( NT_SUCCESS(status) ) {
7905 
7906  IdSetOnTarget = TRUE;
7907 
7908  // If this was a cross-volume move, notify the tracking service.
7909 
7910  if( !RtlEqualMemory( &TargetVolumeId.VolumeId[0],
7911  &SourceVolumeId.VolumeId[0],
7912  sizeof(SourceVolumeId.VolumeId) )) {
7913 
7914  IopMarshalIds( &trackingBuffer, &TargetVolumeId, &TargetObjectId, trackingInfo );
7915 
7916  // Bit 0 must be reset before notifying tracking service
7917  NormalizedObjectId = SourceObjectId;
7918  NormalizedObjectId.BirthVolumeId[0] &= 0xfe;
7919 
7920  status = IopSendMessageToTrackService( &SourceVolumeId,
7921  &NormalizedObjectId,
7922  &trackingBuffer.TrackingInformation );
7923  }
7924  }
7925 
7926  //
7927  // If there was an error after the ObjectID was deleted
7928  // from the source. Try to restore it before returning.
7929  //
7930 
7931  if( !NT_SUCCESS(status) ) {
7932  NTSTATUS statusT = STATUS_SUCCESS;
7933 
7934  if( IdSetOnTarget ) {
7935 
7936  if( RtlEqualMemory( &TargetObjectId.ObjectId,
7937  &SourceObjectId.ObjectId,
7938  sizeof(TargetObjectId.ObjectId) )) {
7939 
7940  // This ID was set with FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID
7941  statusT = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
7942  NULL,
7943  0,
7944  FSCTL_DELETE_OBJECT_ID );
7945 
7946  } else {
7947 
7948  // Restore the target's extended data.
7949 
7950  statusT = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
7951  &TargetObjectId.ExtendedInfo[0],
7952  sizeof(TargetObjectId.ExtendedInfo),
7953  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID_EXTENDED );
7954  }
7955  }
7956 
7957  if( NT_SUCCESS( statusT )) {
7958 
7959  IopGetSetObjectId( FileObject,
7960  &SourceObjectId,
7961  sizeof(SourceObjectId),
7962  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID );
7963  }
7964 
7965  leave;
7966  }
7967 
7968 
7969  } else { // if (IsFileLocal( dstFileObject ))
7970 
7971  //
7972  // The source file is local, but the destination file object
7973  // is remote. For this case query the target file's object
7974  // ID and notify the link tracking system that the file has
7975  // been moved across systems.
7976  //
7977 
7978  //
7979  // Begin by ensuring that the source file has an object ID
7980  // already. If not, then just make it appear as if the
7981  // operation worked.
7982  //
7983 
7984  status = IopGetSetObjectId( FileObject,
7985  &SourceObjectId,
7986  sizeof( SourceObjectId ),
7987  FSCTL_GET_OBJECT_ID );
7988  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
7989  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
7990  leave;
7991  }
7992 
7993 
7994  //
7995  // If the extended info field is zero then this file
7996  // has no interesting tracking information.
7997  //
7998  if (RtlCompareMemoryUlong(&SourceObjectId.BirthObjectId,
7999  sizeof(SourceObjectId.BirthObjectId),
8000  0) == sizeof(SourceObjectId.BirthObjectId)) {
8001  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
8002  leave;
8003  }
8004 
8005  //
8006  // Query the volume ID of the target.
8007  //
8008 
8009  status = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
8010  &TargetVolumeId,
8011  sizeof( FILE_VOLUMEID_WITH_TYPE ),
8012  FSCTL_LMR_GET_LINK_TRACKING_INFORMATION );
8013  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8014  leave;
8015  }
8016 
8017  //
8018  // Query the object ID of the target.
8019  //
8020 
8021  status = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
8022  &TargetObjectId,
8023  sizeof( TargetObjectId ),
8024  FSCTL_CREATE_OR_GET_OBJECT_ID );
8025  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8026  leave;
8027  }
8028 
8029  //
8030  // Notify the tracking system of the move.
8031  //
8032 
8033  IopMarshalIds( &trackingBuffer, &TargetVolumeId, &TargetObjectId, trackingInfo );
8034  status = IopTrackLink( FileObject,
8035  IoStatusBlock,
8036  &trackingBuffer.TrackingInformation,
8037  FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_TRACKING_INFORMATION,
8038  ObjectInformation ) +
8039  trackingBuffer.TrackingInformation.ObjectInformationLength,
8040  Event,
8041  KernelMode );
8042  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8043  leave;
8044  }
8045 
8046  //
8047  // Delete the ID from the source
8048  //
8049 
8050  status = IopGetSetObjectId( FileObject,
8051  NULL,
8052  0,
8053  FSCTL_DELETE_OBJECT_ID );
8054  if( !NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8055  leave;
8056  }
8057 
8058  //
8059  // Set the Birth ID on the target, turning on the bit
8060  // that indicates that this file has been involved in a cross-
8061  // volume move.
8062  //
8063 
8064  CrossVolumeObjectId = SourceObjectId;
8065  CrossVolumeObjectId.BirthVolumeId[0] |= 1;
8066 
8067  status = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
8068  &CrossVolumeObjectId.ExtendedInfo[0],
8069  sizeof( CrossVolumeObjectId.ExtendedInfo ),
8070  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID_EXTENDED );
8071  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8072 
8073  // Try to restore the source
8074  IopGetSetObjectId( FileObject,
8075  &SourceObjectId,
8076  sizeof(SourceObjectId),
8077  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID );
8078  leave;
8079  }
8080 
8081 
8082  } // if (IsFileLocal( dstFileObject ))
8083 
8084  } else { // if (trackingInfo->DestinationFile)
8085 
8086  //
8087  // A destination file handle was not specified. Simply query
8088  // the source file's object ID and call the link tracking code.
8089  // Note that the function input buffer contains the volume ID
8090  // and file object ID of the target. Note also that it is
8091  // assumed that the source file has an object ID.
8092  //
8093 
8094  status = IopGetVolumeId( FileObject,
8095  &SourceVolumeId,
8096  sizeof( SourceVolumeId ) );
8097  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8098  leave;
8099  }
8100 
8101  status = IopGetSetObjectId( FileObject,
8102  &SourceObjectId,
8103  sizeof( SourceObjectId ),
8104  FSCTL_GET_OBJECT_ID );
8105  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8106  leave;
8107  }
8108 
8109  //
8110  // If the extended info field is zero then this file
8111  // has no interesting tracking information.
8112  //
8113  if (RtlCompareMemoryUlong(SourceObjectId.BirthObjectId,
8114  sizeof(SourceObjectId.BirthObjectId),
8115  0) == sizeof(SourceObjectId.BirthObjectId)) {
8116  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
8117  leave;
8118  }
8119  //
8120  // Inform the user-mode link tracking service that the file
8121  // has been moved.
8122  //
8123 
8124  NormalizedObjectId = SourceObjectId;
8125  NormalizedObjectId.BirthVolumeId[0] &= 0xfe;
8126 
8127  status = IopSendMessageToTrackService( &SourceVolumeId,
8128  &NormalizedObjectId,
8129  FileInformation );
8130  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8131  leave;
8132  }
8133 
8134  } // if (trackingInfo->DestinationFile) ... else
8135 
8136  } else { // if (IsFileLocal( FileObject ))
8137 
8138  //
8139  // The source file is remote. For this case, remote the operation
8140  // to the system on which the source file is located. Begin by
8141  // ensuring that the source file actually has an object ID. If
8142  // not, then get out now since there is nothing to be done.
8143  //
8144 
8145  status = IopGetSetObjectId( FileObject,
8146  &SourceObjectId,
8147  sizeof( SourceObjectId ),
8148  FSCTL_GET_OBJECT_ID );
8149 
8150  if (status == STATUS_OBJECT_NAME_NOT_FOUND)
8151  {
8152  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
8153  leave;
8154  }
8155 
8156  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8157  leave;
8158  }
8159 
8160  //
8161  // If the extended info field is zero then this file
8162  // has no interesting tracking information.
8163  //
8164  if (RtlCompareMemoryUlong(SourceObjectId.BirthObjectId,
8165  sizeof(SourceObjectId.BirthObjectId),
8166  0) == sizeof(SourceObjectId.BirthObjectId)) {
8167  status = STATUS_SUCCESS;
8168  leave;
8169  }
8170  if (trackingInfo->DestinationFile) {
8171 
8172  //
8173  // A handle was specified for the destination file. Determine
8174  // whether it is local or remote. If remote and both handles
8175  // refer to the same machine, then ship the entire API to that
8176  // machine and have it perform the operation.
8177  //
8178  // Otherwise, query the target file's object ID, and then redo
8179  // the operation. This will cause the API to be remoted to the
8180  // machine where the source file resides.
8181  //
8182 
8183  if (IsFileLocal( dstFileObject )) {
8184 
8185  //
8186  // The source is remote and the destination is local, so
8187  // query the object ID of the target and recursively track
8188  // the link from the source file's remote node.
8189  //
8190 
8191  status = IopGetVolumeId( dstFileObject,
8192  &TargetVolumeId,
8193  sizeof( TargetVolumeId ) );
8194  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8195  leave;
8196  }
8197 
8198  status = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
8199  &TargetObjectId,
8200  sizeof( TargetObjectId ),
8201  FSCTL_CREATE_OR_GET_OBJECT_ID );
8202  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8203  leave;
8204  }
8205 
8206 
8207  //
8208  // Notify the tracking system of the move.
8209  //
8210 
8211  IopMarshalIds( &trackingBuffer, &TargetVolumeId, &TargetObjectId, trackingInfo );
8212 
8213  status = IopTrackLink( FileObject,
8214  IoStatusBlock,
8215  &trackingBuffer.TrackingInformation,
8216  FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_TRACKING_INFORMATION,
8217  ObjectInformation ) +
8218  trackingBuffer.TrackingInformation.ObjectInformationLength,
8219  Event,
8220  KernelMode );
8221  if( !NT_SUCCESS(status) ) {
8222  leave;
8223  }
8224 
8225  //
8226  // Delete the ID from the source
8227  //
8228 
8229  status = IopGetSetObjectId( FileObject,
8230  NULL,
8231  0,
8232  FSCTL_DELETE_OBJECT_ID );
8233  if( !NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8234  leave;
8235  }
8236 
8237  //
8238  // Set the birth ID on the target, also turning on the bit
8239  // that indicates that this file has moved across volumes.
8240  //
8241 
8242  CrossVolumeObjectId = SourceObjectId;
8243  CrossVolumeObjectId.BirthVolumeId[0] |= 1;
8244 
8245  status = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
8246  &CrossVolumeObjectId.ExtendedInfo[0],
8247  sizeof( CrossVolumeObjectId.ExtendedInfo ),
8248  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID_EXTENDED );
8249 
8250  if( !NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8251 
8252  IopGetSetObjectId( FileObject,
8253  &SourceObjectId,
8254  sizeof(SourceObjectId),
8255  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID );
8256  leave;
8257  }
8258 
8259  } // if (IsFileLocal( dstFileObject ))
8260 
8261  else if (!IopIsSameMachine( FileObject, trackingInfo->DestinationFile)) {
8262 
8263  //
8264  // The source and the target are remote from each other and from
8265  // this machine. Query the object ID of the target and recursively
8266  // track the link from the source file's remote node.
8267  //
8268 
8269  //
8270  // Query the volume ID of the target.
8271  //
8272 
8273  status = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
8274  &TargetVolumeId,
8275  sizeof( FILE_VOLUMEID_WITH_TYPE ),
8276  FSCTL_LMR_GET_LINK_TRACKING_INFORMATION );
8277 
8278  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8279  leave;
8280  }
8281 
8282  //
8283  // Query the object ID of the target.
8284  //
8285 
8286  status = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
8287  &TargetObjectId,
8288  sizeof( TargetObjectId ),
8289  FSCTL_CREATE_OR_GET_OBJECT_ID );
8290  if( !NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8291  leave;
8292  }
8293 
8294  //
8295  // Notify the tracking system of the move.
8296  //
8297 
8298  IopMarshalIds( &trackingBuffer, &TargetVolumeId, &TargetObjectId, trackingInfo );
8299 
8300  status = IopTrackLink( FileObject,
8301  IoStatusBlock,
8302  &trackingBuffer.TrackingInformation,
8303  FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_TRACKING_INFORMATION,
8304  ObjectInformation ) +
8305  trackingBuffer.TrackingInformation.ObjectInformationLength,
8306  Event,
8307  KernelMode );
8308  if( !NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8309  leave;
8310  }
8311 
8312  //
8313  // Set the birth ID on the target, turning on the bit that indicates
8314  // that this file has moved across volumes.
8315  //
8316 
8317  CrossVolumeObjectId = SourceObjectId;
8318  CrossVolumeObjectId.BirthVolumeId[0] |= 1;
8319 
8320  status = IopGetSetObjectId( dstFileObject,
8321  &CrossVolumeObjectId.ExtendedInfo[0],
8322  sizeof( CrossVolumeObjectId.ExtendedInfo ),
8323  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID_EXTENDED );
8324 
8325  if( !NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8326  IopGetSetObjectId( FileObject,
8327  &SourceObjectId,
8328  sizeof(SourceObjectId),
8329  FSCTL_SET_OBJECT_ID );
8330  leave;
8331  }
8332 
8333  } else { // else if (!IopIsSameMachine( FileObject, trackingInfo->DestinationFile))
8334 
8335  //
8336  // Both the source and the target are remote and they're
8337  // both on the same remote machine. For this case, remote
8338  // the entire API using the file object pointers.
8339  //
8340 
8341  status = IopSetRemoteLink( FileObject, dstFileObject, trackingInfo );
8342 
8343  } // else if (!IopIsSameMachine( FileObject, trackingInfo->DestinationFile)) ... else
8344 
8345  } else { // if (trackingInfo->DestinationFile)
8346 
8347  //
8348  // The source file is remote and the object ID of the target is
8349  // contained w/in the tracking buffer. Simply remote the API
8350  // to the remote machine using the source file object pointer
8351  // and the object ID of the target in the buffer.
8352  //
8353 
8354  status = IopSetRemoteLink( FileObject, NULL, FileInformation );
8355 
8356  } // if (trackingInfo->DestinationFile) ... else
8357  } // if (IsFileLocal( FileObject )) ... else
8358 
8359  } finally {
8360 
8361  //
8362  // Ensure that everything has been cleaned up.
8363  //
8364 
8365  if (RequestorMode != KernelMode && trackingInfo) {
8366  ExFreePool( trackingInfo );
8367  }
8368 
8369  if (dstFileObject ) {
8370  ObDereferenceObject( dstFileObject );
8371  }
8372 
8373  KeSetEvent( Event, 0, FALSE );
8374  }
8375 
8376  return status;
8377 }
8378 
8379 VOID
8380 IopUserCompletion(
8381  IN PKAPC Apc,
8382  IN PKNORMAL_ROUTINE *NormalRoutine,
8383  IN PVOID *NormalContext,
8384  IN PVOID *SystemArgument1,
8385  IN PVOID *SystemArgument2
8386  )
8387 
8388 /*++
8389 
8390 Routine Description:
8391 
8392  This routine is invoked in the final processing of an IRP. Everything has
8393  been completed except that the caller's APC routine must be invoked. The
8394  system will do this as soon as this routine exits. The only processing
8395  remaining to be completed by the I/O system is to free the I/O Request
8396  Packet itself.
8397 
8398 Arguments:
8399 
8400  Apc - Supplies a pointer to kernel APC structure.
8401 
8402  NormalRoutine - Supplies a pointer to a pointer to the normal function
8403  that was specified when the APC was initialized.
8404 
8405  NormalContext - Supplies a pointer to a pointer to an arbitrary data
8406  structure that was specified when the APC was initialized.
8407 
8408  SystemArgument1, SystemArgument2 - Supplies a set of two pointers to
8409  two arguments that contain untyped data.
8410 
8411 Return Value:
8412 
8413  None.
8414 
8415 Note:
8416 
8417  If no other processing is ever needed, and the APC can be placed at the
8418  beginning of the IRP, then this routine could be replaced by simply
8419  specifying the address of the pool deallocation routine in the APC instead
8420  of the address of this routine.
8421 
8422 Caution:
8423 
8424  This routine is also invoked as a general purpose rundown routine for APCs.
8425  Should this code ever need to directly access any of the other parameters
8426  other than Apc, this routine will need to be split into two separate
8427  routines. The rundown routine should perform exactly the following code's
8428  functionality.
8429 
8430 --*/
8431 
8432 {
8433  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( NormalRoutine );
8434  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( NormalContext );
8435  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( SystemArgument1 );
8436  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER( SystemArgument2 );
8437 
8438  PAGED_CODE();
8439 
8440  //
8441  // Free the packet.
8442  //
8443 
8444  IoFreeIrp( CONTAINING_RECORD( Apc, IRP, Tail.Apc ) );
8445 }
8446 
8447 
8448 
8449 VOID
8450 IopUserRundown(
8451  IN PKAPC Apc
8452  )
8453 
8454 /*++
8455 
8456 Routine Description:
8457 
8458  This routine is invoked during thread termination as the rundown routine
8459  for it simply calls IopUserCompletion.
8460 
8461 Arguments:
8462 
8463  Apc - Supplies a pointer to kernel APC structure.
8464 
8465 Return Value:
8466 
8467  None.
8468 
8469 
8470 --*/
8471 
8472 {
8473  PAGED_CODE();
8474 
8475  //
8476  // Free the packet.
8477  //
8478 
8479  IoFreeIrp( CONTAINING_RECORD( Apc, IRP, Tail.Apc ) );
8480 }
8481 
8482 NTSTATUS
8483 IopXxxControlFile(
8484  IN HANDLE FileHandle,
8485  IN HANDLE Event OPTIONAL,
8486  IN PIO_APC_ROUTINE ApcRoutine OPTIONAL,
8487  IN PVOID ApcContext OPTIONAL,
8488  OUT PIO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock,
8489  IN ULONG IoControlCode,
8490  IN PVOID InputBuffer OPTIONAL,
8491  IN ULONG InputBufferLength,
8492  OUT PVOID OutputBuffer OPTIONAL,
8493  IN ULONG OutputBufferLength,
8494  IN BOOLEAN DeviceIoControl
8495  )
8496 
8497 /*++
8498 
8499 Routine Description:
8500 
8501  This service builds descriptors or MDLs for the supplied buffer(s) and
8502  passes the untyped data to the driver associated with the file handle.
8503  handle. It is up to the driver to check the input data and function
8504  IoControlCode for validity, as well as to make the appropriate access
8505  checks.
8506 
8507 Arguments:
8508 
8509  FileHandle - Supplies a handle to the file on which the service is being
8510  performed.
8511 
8512  Event - Supplies an optional event to be set to the Signaled state when
8513  the service is complete.
8514 
8515  ApcRoutine - Supplies an optional APC routine to be executed when the
8516  service is complete.
8517 
8518  ApcContext - Supplies a context parameter to be passed to the ApcRoutine,
8519  if an ApcRoutine was specified.
8520 
8521  IoStatusBlock - Address of the caller's I/O status block.
8522 
8523  IoControlCode - Subfunction code to determine exactly what operation is
8524  being performed.
8525 
8526  InputBuffer - Optionally supplies an input buffer to be passed to the
8527  driver. Whether or not the buffer is actually optional is dependent
8528  on the IoControlCode.
8529 
8530  InputBufferLength - Length of the InputBuffer in bytes.
8531 
8532  OutputBuffer - Optionally supplies an output buffer to receive information
8533  from the driver. Whether or not the buffer is actually optional is
8534  dependent on the IoControlCode.
8535 
8536  OutputBufferLength - Length of the OutputBuffer in bytes.
8537 
8538  DeviceIoControl - Determines whether this is a Device or File System
8539  Control function.
8540 
8541 Return Value:
8542 
8543  The status returned is success if the control operation was properly
8544  queued to the I/O system. Once the operation completes, the status
8545  can be determined by examining the Status field of the I/O status block.
8546 
8547 --*/
8548 
8549 {
8550  PIRP irp;
8551  NTSTATUS status;
8552  PFILE_OBJECT fileObject;
8553  PDEVICE_OBJECT deviceObject;
8554  PKEVENT eventObject = (PKEVENT) NULL;
8555  PIO_STACK_LOCATION irpSp;
8556  ULONG method;
8557  OBJECT_HANDLE_INFORMATION handleInformation;
8558  BOOLEAN synchronousIo;
8559  IO_STATUS_BLOCK localIoStatus;
8560  PFAST_IO_DISPATCH fastIoDispatch;
8561  POOL_TYPE poolType;
8562  PULONG majorFunction;
8563  KPROCESSOR_MODE requestorMode;
8564  PETHREAD CurrentThread;
8565 
8566  PAGED_CODE();
8567 
8568  //
8569  // Get the method that the buffers are being passed by.
8570  //
8571 
8572  method = IoControlCode & 3;
8573 
8574  //
8575  // Check the caller's parameters based on the mode of the caller.
8576  //
8577 
8578  CurrentThread = PsGetCurrentThread ();
8579  requestorMode = KeGetPreviousModeByThread(&CurrentThread->Tcb);
8580 
8581  if (requestorMode != KernelMode) {
8582 
8583  //
8584  // The caller's access mode is not kernel so probe each of the arguments
8585  // and capture them as necessary. If any failures occur, the condition
8586  // handler will be invoked to handle them. It will simply cleanup and
8587  // return an access violation status code back to the system service
8588  // dispatcher.
8589  //
8590 
8591  try {
8592 
8593  //
8594  // The IoStatusBlock parameter must be writeable by the caller.
8595  //
8596 
8597  ProbeForWriteIoStatus (IoStatusBlock);
8598 
8599  //
8600  // The output buffer can be used in any one of the following three ways,
8601  // if it is specified:
8602  //
8603  // 0) It can be a normal, buffered output buffer.
8604  //
8605  // 1) It can be a DMA input buffer.
8606  //
8607  // 2) It can be a DMA output buffer.
8608  //
8609  // Which way the buffer is to be used it based on the low-order two bits
8610  // of the IoControlCode.
8611  //
8612  // If the method is 0 we probe the output buffer for write access.
8613  // If the method is not 3 we probe the input buffer for read access.
8614  //
8615 
8616  if (method == METHOD_BUFFERED) {
8617  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( OutputBuffer )) {
8618  ProbeForWrite( OutputBuffer,
8619  OutputBufferLength,
8620  sizeof( UCHAR ) );
8621  } else {
8622  OutputBufferLength = 0;
8623  }
8624  }
8625 
8626  if (method != METHOD_NEITHER) {
8627  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( InputBuffer )) {
8628  ProbeForRead( InputBuffer,
8629  InputBufferLength,
8630  sizeof( UCHAR ) );
8631  } else {
8632  InputBufferLength = 0;
8633  }
8634  }
8635 
8636  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
8637 
8638  //
8639  // An exception was incurred while attempting to probe or write
8640  // one of the caller's parameters. Simply return an appropriate
8641  // error status code.
8642  //
8643 
8644  return GetExceptionCode();
8645 
8646  }
8647  }
8648 
8649  //
8650  // There were no blatant errors so far, so reference the file object so
8651  // the target device object can be found. Note that if the handle does
8652  // not refer to a file object, or if the caller does not have the required
8653  // access to the file, then it will fail.
8654  //
8655 
8656  status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle( FileHandle,
8657  0L,
8658  IoFileObjectType,
8659  requestorMode,
8660  (PVOID *) &fileObject,
8661  &handleInformation );
8662  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8663  return status;
8664  }
8665 
8666  //
8667  // If this file has an I/O completion port associated w/it, then ensure
8668  // that the caller did not supply an APC routine, as the two are mutually
8669  // exclusive methods for I/O completion notification.
8670  //
8671 
8672  if (fileObject->CompletionContext && IopApcRoutinePresent( ApcRoutine )) {
8673  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
8674  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
8675  }
8676 
8677  //
8678  // Now check the access type for this control code to ensure that the
8679  // caller has the appropriate access to this file object to perform the
8680  // operation.
8681  //
8682 
8683  if (requestorMode != KernelMode) {
8684 
8685  ULONG accessMode = (IoControlCode >> 14) & 3;
8686 
8687  if (accessMode != FILE_ANY_ACCESS) {
8688 
8689  //
8690  // This I/O control requires that the caller have read, write,
8691  // or read/write access to the object. If this is not the case,
8692  // then cleanup and return an appropriate error status code.
8693  //
8694 
8695  if (SeComputeGrantedAccesses( handleInformation.GrantedAccess, accessMode ) != accessMode ) {
8696  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
8697  return STATUS_ACCESS_DENIED;
8698  }
8699  }
8700  }
8701 
8702  //
8703  // Get the address of the event object and set the event to the Not-
8704  // Signaled state, if an event was specified. Note here, too, that if
8705  // the handle does not refer to an event, or if the event cannot be
8706  // written, then the reference will fail.
8707  //
8708 
8709  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( Event )) {
8710  status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle( Event,
8711  EVENT_MODIFY_STATE,
8712  ExEventObjectType,
8713  requestorMode,
8714  (PVOID *) &eventObject,
8715  NULL );
8716  if (!NT_SUCCESS( status )) {
8717  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
8718  return status;
8719  } else {
8720  KeClearEvent( eventObject );
8721  }
8722  }
8723 
8724  //
8725  // Make a special check here to determine whether this is a synchronous
8726  // I/O operation. If it is, then wait here until the file is owned by
8727  // the current thread.
8728  //
8729 
8730  if (fileObject->Flags & FO_SYNCHRONOUS_IO) {
8731  BOOLEAN interrupted;
8732 
8733  if (!IopAcquireFastLock( fileObject )) {
8734  status = IopAcquireFileObjectLock( fileObject,
8735  requestorMode,
8736  (BOOLEAN) ((fileObject->Flags & FO_ALERTABLE_IO) != 0),
8737  &interrupted );
8738  if (interrupted) {
8739  if (eventObject) {
8740  ObDereferenceObject( eventObject );
8741  }
8742  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
8743  return status;
8744  }
8745  }
8746  synchronousIo = TRUE;
8747  } else {
8748  synchronousIo = FALSE;
8749 
8750 #if defined(_WIN64)
8751  if (requestorMode != KernelMode) {
8752  try {
8753 
8754  //
8755  // If this is a 32-bit asynchronous IO, then mark the Iosb being sent as so.
8756  // Note: IopMarkApcRoutineIfAsyncronousIo32 must be called after probing
8757  // the IoStatusBlock structure for write.
8758  //
8759 
8760  IopMarkApcRoutineIfAsyncronousIo32(IoStatusBlock,ApcRoutine,FALSE);
8761 
8762  } except (EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
8763 
8764  //
8765  // Cleanup and return an appropriate status code.
8766  //
8767 
8768  if (eventObject) {
8769  ObDereferenceObject( eventObject );
8770  }
8771  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
8772  return GetExceptionCode ();
8773  }
8774  }
8775 #endif
8776  }
8777 
8778  //
8779  // Get the address of the target device object. If this file represents
8780  // a device that was opened directly, then simply use the device or its
8781  // attached device(s) directly.
8782  //
8783 
8784  if (!(fileObject->Flags & FO_DIRECT_DEVICE_OPEN)) {
8785  deviceObject = IoGetRelatedDeviceObject( fileObject );
8786  } else {
8787  deviceObject = IoGetAttachedDevice( fileObject->DeviceObject );
8788  }
8789 
8790  if (DeviceIoControl) {
8791 
8792  //
8793  // Also get the address of the Fast I/O dispatch structure.
8794  //
8795 
8796  fastIoDispatch = deviceObject->DriverObject->FastIoDispatch;
8797 
8798  //
8799  // Turbo device control support. If the device has a fast I/O entry
8800  // point for DeviceIoControlFile, call the entry point and give it a
8801  // chance to try to complete the request. Note if FastIoDeviceControl
8802  // returns FALSE or we get an I/O error, we simply fall through and
8803  // go the "long way" and create an Irp.
8804  //
8805 
8806  if (fastIoDispatch && fastIoDispatch->FastIoDeviceControl) {
8807 
8808  //
8809  // Before we actually call the fast I/O routine in the driver,
8810  // we must probe OutputBuffer if the method is METHOD_IN_DIRECT or METHOD_OUT_DIRECT.
8811  //
8812 
8813  if (requestorMode != KernelMode && ARGUMENT_PRESENT(OutputBuffer)) {
8814 
8815  try {
8816 
8817  if (method == METHOD_IN_DIRECT) {
8818  ProbeForRead( OutputBuffer,
8819  OutputBufferLength,
8820  sizeof( UCHAR ) );
8821  } else if (method == METHOD_OUT_DIRECT) {
8822  ProbeForWrite( OutputBuffer,
8823  OutputBufferLength,
8824  sizeof( UCHAR ) );
8825  }
8826 
8827  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
8828 
8829  //
8830  // An exception was incurred while attempting to probe
8831  // the output buffer. Clean up and return an
8832  // appropriate error status code.
8833  //
8834 
8835  if (synchronousIo) {
8836  IopReleaseFileObjectLock( fileObject );
8837  }
8838 
8839  if (eventObject) {
8840  ObDereferenceObject( eventObject );
8841  }
8842 
8843  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
8844 
8845  return GetExceptionCode();
8846  }
8847  }
8848 
8849  //
8850  // If we are dismounting a volume, increment the shared count. This
8851  // allows user-space applications to efficiently test for validity
8852  // of current directory handles.
8853  //
8854 
8855  if (IoControlCode == FSCTL_DISMOUNT_VOLUME) {
8856  InterlockedIncrement( (PLONG) &SharedUserData->DismountCount );
8857  }
8858 
8859 
8860  //
8861  // Call the driver's fast I/O routine.
8862  //
8863 
8864  if (fastIoDispatch->FastIoDeviceControl( fileObject,
8865  TRUE,
8866  InputBuffer,
8867  InputBufferLength,
8868  OutputBuffer,
8869  OutputBufferLength,
8870  IoControlCode,
8871  &localIoStatus,
8872  deviceObject )) {
8873 
8874  PVOID port;
8875  PVOID key;
8876 
8877  //
8878  // The driver successfully performed the I/O in it's
8879  // fast device control routine. Carefully return the
8880  // I/O status.
8881  //
8882 
8883  try {
8884 #if defined(_WIN64)
8885  //
8886  // If this is a32-bit thread, and the IO request is
8887  // asynchronous, then the IOSB is 32-bit. Wow64 always sends
8888  // the 32-bit IOSB when the I/O is asynchronous.
8889  //
8890  if (IopIsIosb32(ApcRoutine)) {
8891  PIO_STATUS_BLOCK32 UserIosb32 = (PIO_STATUS_BLOCK32)IoStatusBlock;
8892 
8893  UserIosb32->Information = (ULONG)localIoStatus.Information;
8894  UserIosb32->Status = (NTSTATUS)localIoStatus.Status;
8895  } else {
8896  *IoStatusBlock = localIoStatus;
8897  }
8898 #else
8899  *IoStatusBlock = localIoStatus;
8900 #endif
8901  } except( EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER ) {
8902  localIoStatus.Status = GetExceptionCode();
8903  localIoStatus.Information = 0;
8904  }
8905 
8906 
8907  //
8908  // If there is an I/O completion port object associated w/this request,
8909  // save it here. We cannot look at the fileobject after signaling the
8910  // event as that might result in the attachment of a completion port.
8911  // This makes the behavior consistent with the one in IopCompleteRequest.
8912  //
8913 
8914  if (fileObject->CompletionContext) {
8915  port = fileObject->CompletionContext->Port;
8916  key = fileObject->CompletionContext->Key;
8917  } else {
8918  port = NULL;
8919  key = NULL;
8920  }
8921 
8922  //
8923  // If an event was specified, set it.
8924  //
8925 
8926  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( Event )) {
8927  KeSetEvent( eventObject, 0, FALSE );
8928  ObDereferenceObject( eventObject );
8929  }
8930 
8931  //
8932  // Note that the file object event need not be set to the
8933  // Signaled state, as it is already set. Release the
8934  // file object lock, if necessary.
8935  //
8936 
8937  if (synchronousIo) {
8938  IopReleaseFileObjectLock( fileObject );
8939  }
8940 
8941  //
8942  // If this file object has a completion port associated with it
8943  // and this request has a non-NULL APC context then a completion
8944  // message needs to be queued.
8945  //
8946 
8947  if (port && ARGUMENT_PRESENT( ApcContext )) {
8948  if (!NT_SUCCESS(IoSetIoCompletion( port,
8949  key,
8950  ApcContext,
8951  localIoStatus.Status,
8952  localIoStatus.Information,
8953  TRUE ))) {
8954  localIoStatus.Status = STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
8955  }
8956  }
8957 
8958  //
8959  // Cleanup and return.
8960  //
8961 
8962  ObDereferenceObject( fileObject );
8963  return localIoStatus.Status;
8964  }
8965  }
8966 
8967  }
8968 
8969  //
8970  // Set the file object to the Not-Signaled state.
8971  //
8972 
8973  KeClearEvent( &fileObject->Event );
8974 
8975  //
8976  // Allocate and initialize the I/O Request Packet (IRP) for this operation.
8977 
8978  irp = IopAllocateIrp( deviceObject->StackSize, !synchronousIo );
8979 
8980  if (!irp) {
8981 
8982  //
8983  // An IRP could not be allocated. Cleanup and return an appropriate
8984  // error status code.
8985  //
8986 
8987  IopAllocateIrpCleanup( fileObject, eventObject );
8988 
8989  return STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES;
8990  }
8991  irp->Tail.Overlay.OriginalFileObject = fileObject;
8992  irp->Tail.Overlay.Thread = CurrentThread;
8993  irp->Tail.Overlay.AuxiliaryBuffer = (PVOID) NULL;
8994  irp->RequestorMode = requestorMode;
8995  irp->PendingReturned = FALSE;
8996  irp->Cancel = FALSE;
8997  irp->CancelRoutine = (PDRIVER_CANCEL) NULL;
8998 
8999  //
9000  // Fill in the service independent parameters in the IRP.
9001  //
9002 
9003  irp->UserEvent = eventObject;
9004  irp->UserIosb = IoStatusBlock;
9005  irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcRoutine = ApcRoutine;
9006  irp->Overlay.AsynchronousParameters.UserApcContext = ApcContext;
9007 
9008  //
9009  // Get a pointer to the stack location for the first driver. This will be
9010  // used to pass the original function codes and parameters. Note that
9011  // setting the major function here also sets:
9012  //
9013  // MinorFunction = 0;
9014  // Flags = 0;
9015  // Control = 0;
9016  //
9017 
9018  irpSp = IoGetNextIrpStackLocation( irp );
9019  majorFunction = (PULONG) (&irpSp->MajorFunction);
9020  *majorFunction = DeviceIoControl ? IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL : IRP_MJ_FILE_SYSTEM_CONTROL;
9021  irpSp->FileObject = fileObject;
9022 
9023  //
9024  // Copy the caller's parameters to the service-specific portion of the
9025  // IRP for those parameters that are the same for all three methods.
9026  //
9027 
9028  irpSp->Parameters.DeviceIoControl.OutputBufferLength = OutputBufferLength;
9029  irpSp->Parameters.DeviceIoControl.InputBufferLength = InputBufferLength;
9030  irpSp->Parameters.DeviceIoControl.IoControlCode = IoControlCode;
9031 
9032  //
9033  // Set the pool type based on the type of function being performed.
9034  //
9035 
9036  poolType = DeviceIoControl ? NonPagedPoolCacheAligned : NonPagedPool;
9037 
9038  //
9039  // Based on the method that the buffer are being passed, either allocate
9040  // buffers or build MDLs. Note that in some cases no probing has taken
9041  // place so the exception handler must catch access violations.
9042  //
9043 
9044  irp->MdlAddress = (PMDL) NULL;
9045  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer = (PVOID) NULL;
9046 
9047  switch ( method ) {
9048 
9049  case METHOD_BUFFERED:
9050 
9051  //
9052  // For this case, allocate a buffer that is large enough to contain
9053  // both the input and the output buffers. Copy the input buffer to
9054  // the allocated buffer and set the appropriate IRP fields.
9055  //
9056 
9057  irpSp->Parameters.DeviceIoControl.Type3InputBuffer = (PVOID) NULL;
9058 
9059  try {
9060 
9061  if (InputBufferLength || OutputBufferLength) {
9062  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer =
9063  ExAllocatePoolWithQuota( poolType,
9064  (InputBufferLength > OutputBufferLength) ? InputBufferLength : OutputBufferLength );
9065 
9066  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( InputBuffer )) {
9067  RtlCopyMemory( irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer,
9068  InputBuffer,
9069  InputBufferLength );
9070  }
9071  irp->Flags = IRP_BUFFERED_IO | IRP_DEALLOCATE_BUFFER;
9072  irp->UserBuffer = OutputBuffer;
9073  if (ARGUMENT_PRESENT( OutputBuffer )) {
9074  irp->Flags |= IRP_INPUT_OPERATION;
9075  }
9076  } else {
9077  irp->Flags = 0;
9078  irp->UserBuffer = (PVOID) NULL;
9079  }
9080 
9081  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
9082 
9083  //
9084  // An exception was incurred while either allocating the
9085  // the system buffer or moving the caller's data. Determine
9086  // what actually happened, cleanup accordingly, and return
9087  // an appropriate error status code.
9088  //
9089 
9090  IopExceptionCleanup( fileObject,
9091  irp,
9092  eventObject,
9093  (PKEVENT) NULL );
9094 
9095  return GetExceptionCode();
9096  }
9097 
9098  break;
9099 
9100  case METHOD_IN_DIRECT:
9101  case METHOD_OUT_DIRECT:
9102 
9103  //
9104  // For these two cases, allocate a buffer that is large enough to
9105  // contain the input buffer, if any, and copy the information to
9106  // the allocated buffer. Then build an MDL for either read or write
9107  // access, depending on the method, for the output buffer. Note
9108  // that the buffer length parameters have been jammed to zero for
9109  // users if the buffer parameter was not passed. (Kernel callers
9110  // should be calling the service correctly in the first place.)
9111  //
9112  // Note also that it doesn't make a whole lot of sense to specify
9113  // either method #1 or #2 if the IOCTL does not require the caller
9114  // to specify an output buffer.
9115  //
9116 
9117  irp->Flags = 0;
9118  irpSp->Parameters.DeviceIoControl.Type3InputBuffer = (PVOID) NULL;
9119 
9120  try {
9121 
9122  if (InputBufferLength && ARGUMENT_PRESENT( InputBuffer )) {
9123  irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer =
9124  ExAllocatePoolWithQuota( poolType,
9125  InputBufferLength );
9126  RtlCopyMemory( irp->AssociatedIrp.SystemBuffer,
9127  InputBuffer,
9128  InputBufferLength );
9129  irp->Flags = IRP_BUFFERED_IO | IRP_DEALLOCATE_BUFFER;
9130  }
9131 
9132  if (OutputBufferLength != 0) {
9133  irp->MdlAddress = IoAllocateMdl( OutputBuffer,
9134  OutputBufferLength,
9135  FALSE,
9136  TRUE,
9137  irp );
9138  if (irp->MdlAddress == NULL) {
9139  ExRaiseStatus( STATUS_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES );
9140  }
9141  IopProbeAndLockPages( irp->MdlAddress,
9142  requestorMode,
9143  (LOCK_OPERATION) ((method == 1) ? IoReadAccess : IoWriteAccess),
9144  deviceObject,
9145  *majorFunction);
9146  }
9147 
9148  } except(EXCEPTION_EXECUTE_HANDLER) {
9149 
9150  //
9151  // An exception was incurred while either allocating the
9152  // system buffer, copying the caller's data, allocating the
9153  // MDL, or probing and locking the caller's buffer. Determine
9154  // what actually happened, cleanup accordingly, and return
9155  // an appropriate error status code.
9156  //
9157 
9158  IopExceptionCleanup( fileObject,
9159  irp,
9160  eventObject,
9161  (PKEVENT) NULL );
9162 
9163  return GetExceptionCode();
9164  }
9165 
9166  break;
9167 
9168  case METHOD_NEITHER:
9169 
9170  //
9171  // For this case, do nothing. Everything is up to the driver.
9172  // Simply give the driver a copy of the caller's parameters and
9173  // let the driver do everything itself.
9174  //
9175 
9176  irp->Flags = 0;
9177  irp->UserBuffer = OutputBuffer;
9178  irpSp->Parameters.DeviceIoControl.Type3InputBuffer = InputBuffer;
9179  }
9180 
9181  //
9182  // Pass the read/write access granted bits down to the driver. This allows drivers to check
9183  // access for ioctls that were mistakenly defined as FILE_ANY_ACCESS and cannot be redefined for
9184  // compatibility reasons.
9185  //
9186 
9187  irpSp->Flags |= SeComputeGrantedAccesses( handleInformation.GrantedAccess, FILE_READ_DATA ) ? SL_READ_ACCESS_GRANTED : 0;
9188  irpSp->Flags |= SeComputeGrantedAccesses( handleInformation.GrantedAccess, FILE_WRITE_DATA ) ? SL_WRITE_ACCESS_GRANTED : 0;
9189 
9190  //
9191  // Defer I/O completion for FSCTL requests, but not for IOCTL requests,
9192  // since file systems set pending properly but device driver do not.
9193  //
9194 
9195  if (!DeviceIoControl) {
9196  irp->Flags |= IRP_DEFER_IO_COMPLETION;
9197  }
9198 
9199  //
9200  // If we are dismounting a volume, increment the shared count. This
9201  // allows user-space applications to efficiently test for validity
9202  // of current directory handles.
9203  //
9204 
9205  if (IoControlCode == FSCTL_DISMOUNT_VOLUME) {
9206  InterlockedIncrement( (PLONG) &SharedUserData->DismountCount );
9207  }
9208 
9209 
9210  //
9211  // Queue the packet, call the driver, and synchronize appropriately with
9212  // I/O completion.
9213  //
9214 
9215  return IopSynchronousServiceTail( deviceObject,
9216  irp,
9217  fileObject,
9218  (BOOLEAN)!DeviceIoControl,
9219  requestorMode,
9220  synchronousIo,
9221  OtherTransfer );
9222 }
9223 
9224 NTSTATUS
9225 IopLookupBusStringFromID (
9226  IN HANDLE KeyHandle,
9227  IN INTERFACE_TYPE InterfaceType,
9228  OUT PWCHAR Buffer,
9229  IN ULONG Length,
9230  OUT PULONG BusFlags OPTIONAL
9231  )
9232 /*++
9233 
9234 Routine Description:
9235 
9236  Translates INTERFACE_TYPE to its corresponding WCHAR[] string.
9237 
9238 Arguments:
9239 
9240  KeyHandle - Supplies a handle to the opened registry key,
9241  HKLM\System\CurrentControlSet\Control\SystemResources\BusValues.
9242 
9243  InterfaceType - Supplies the interface type for which a descriptive
9244  name is to be retrieved.
9245 
9246  Buffer - Supplies a pointer to a unicode character buffer that will
9247  receive the bus name. Since this buffer is used in an
9248  intermediate step to retrieve a KEY_VALUE_FULL_INFORMATION structure,
9249  it must be large enough to contain this structure (including the
9250  longest value name & data length under KeyHandle).
9251 
9252  Length - Supplies the length, in bytes, of the Buffer.
9253 
9254  BusFlags - Optionally receives the flags specified in the second
9255  DWORD of the matching REG_BINARY value.
9256 
9257 Return Value:
9258 
9259  The function value is the final status of the operation.
9260 
9261 --*/
9262 {
9263  NTSTATUS status;
9264  ULONG Index, junk, i, j;
9265  PULONG pl;
9266  PKEY_VALUE_FULL_INFORMATION KeyInformation;
9267  WCHAR c;
9268 
9269  PAGED_CODE();
9270 
9271  Index = 0;
9272  KeyInformation = (PKEY_VALUE_FULL_INFORMATION) Buffer;
9273 
9274  for (; ;) {
9275  status = ZwEnumerateValueKey (
9276  KeyHandle,
9277  Index++,
9278  KeyValueFullInformation,
9279  Buffer,
9280  Length,
9281  &junk
9282  );
9283 
9284  if (!NT_SUCCESS (status)) {
9285  return status;
9286  }
9287 
9288  if (KeyInformation->Type != REG_BINARY) {
9289  continue;
9290  }
9291 
9292  pl = (PULONG) ((PUCHAR) KeyInformation + KeyInformation->DataOffset);
9293  if ((ULONG) InterfaceType != pl[0]) {
9294  continue;
9295  }
9296 
9297  //
9298  // Found a match - move the name to the start of the buffer
9299  //
9300 
9301  if(ARGUMENT_PRESENT(BusFlags)) {
9302  *BusFlags = pl[1];
9303  }
9304 
9305  j = KeyInformation->NameLength / sizeof (WCHAR);
9306  for (i=0; i < j; i++) {
9307  c = KeyInformation->Name[i];
9308  Buffer[i] = c;
9309  }
9310 
9311  Buffer[i] = 0;
9312  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
9313  }
9314 }
9315 
9316 
9317 BOOLEAN
9318 IopSafebootDriverLoad(
9319  PUNICODE_STRING DriverId
9320  )
9321 /*++
9322 
9323 Routine Description:
9324 
9325  Checks to see if a driver or service is included
9326  in the current safeboot registry section.
9327 
9328 Arguments:
9329 
9330  DriverId - Specifies which driver is to be validated.
9331  The string should contain a driver executable name
9332  like foo.sys or a GUID for a pnp driver class.
9333 
9334 Return Value:
9335 
9336  TRUE - driver/service is in the registry
9337  FALSE - driver/service is NOT in the registry
9338 
9339 --*/
9340 {
9341  NTSTATUS status;
9342  HANDLE hSafeBoot,hGuid;
9343  UNICODE_STRING safeBootKey;
9344  UNICODE_STRING SafeBootTypeString;
9345 
9346 
9347 
9348  //
9349  // set the first part of the registry key name
9350  //
9351 
9352  switch (InitSafeBootMode) {
9353  case SAFEBOOT_MINIMAL:
9354  RtlInitUnicodeString(&SafeBootTypeString,SAFEBOOT_MINIMAL_STR_W);
9355  break;
9356 
9357  case SAFEBOOT_NETWORK:
9358  RtlInitUnicodeString(&SafeBootTypeString,SAFEBOOT_NETWORK_STR_W);
9359  break;
9360 
9361  case SAFEBOOT_DSREPAIR:
9362  return TRUE;
9363 
9364  default:
9365  KdPrint(("SAFEBOOT: invalid safeboot option = %d\n",InitSafeBootMode));
9366  return FALSE;
9367  }
9368 
9369  safeBootKey.Length = 0;
9370  safeBootKey.MaximumLength = DriverId->Length + SafeBootTypeString.Length + (4*sizeof(WCHAR));
9371  safeBootKey.Buffer = (PWCHAR)ExAllocatePool(PagedPool,safeBootKey.MaximumLength);
9372  if (!safeBootKey.Buffer) {
9373  KdPrint(("SAFEBOOT: could not allocate pool\n"));
9374  return FALSE;
9375  }
9376 
9377  RtlCopyUnicodeString(&safeBootKey,&SafeBootTypeString);
9378  status = RtlAppendUnicodeToString(&safeBootKey,L"\\");
9379  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
9380  ExFreePool (safeBootKey.Buffer);
9381  KdPrint(("SAFEBOOT: could not create registry key string = %x\n",status));
9382  return FALSE;
9383  }
9384  status = RtlAppendUnicodeStringToString(&safeBootKey,DriverId);
9385  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
9386  ExFreePool (safeBootKey.Buffer);
9387  KdPrint(("SAFEBOOT: could not create registry key string = %x\n",status));
9388  return FALSE;
9389  }
9390 
9391  status = IopOpenRegistryKey (
9392  &hSafeBoot,
9393  NULL,
9394  &CmRegistryMachineSystemCurrentControlSetControlSafeBoot,
9395  KEY_ALL_ACCESS,
9396  FALSE
9397  );
9398  if (NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
9399  status = IopOpenRegistryKey (
9400  &hGuid,
9401  hSafeBoot,
9402  &safeBootKey,
9403  KEY_ALL_ACCESS,
9404  FALSE
9405  );
9406  ObCloseHandle(hSafeBoot, KernelMode);
9407  if (NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
9408  ObCloseHandle(hGuid, KernelMode);
9409  ExFreePool(safeBootKey.Buffer);
9410  return TRUE;
9411  }
9412  }
9413 
9414  ExFreePool(safeBootKey.Buffer);
9415 
9416  return FALSE;
9417 }
9418 
9419 
9420 
9421 #ifdef ALLOC_DATA_PRAGMA
9422 #pragma data_seg("PAGEDATA")
9423 #endif
9424 static PBOOT_LOG_RECORD BootLogRecord;
9425 #ifdef ALLOC_DATA_PRAGMA
9426 #pragma data_seg()
9427 #endif
9428 
9429 VOID
9430 IopInitializeBootLogging(
9431  PLOADER_PARAMETER_BLOCK LoaderBlock,
9432  PCHAR HeaderString
9433  )
9434 /*++
9435 
9436 Routine Description:
9437 
9438  Initializes strings for boot logging.
9439 
9440 Arguments:
9441 
9442  LoaderBlock - the loader parameter block
9443 
9444 Return Value:
9445 
9446  VOID
9447 
9448 --*/
9449 {
9450  PKLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY DataTableEntry;
9451  PMESSAGE_RESOURCE_ENTRY MessageEntry;
9452  ANSI_STRING AnsiString;
9453  NTSTATUS Status;
9454  PLIST_ENTRY nextEntry;
9455  PKLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY driverEntry;
9456 
9457 
9458  PAGED_CODE();
9459 
9460  if (BootLogRecord != NULL) {
9461  return;
9462  }
9463 
9464  BootLogRecord = (PBOOT_LOG_RECORD) ExAllocatePool(NonPagedPool, sizeof(BOOT_LOG_RECORD));
9465 
9466  if (BootLogRecord == NULL) {
9467  return;
9468  }
9469 
9470  RtlZeroMemory(BootLogRecord, sizeof(BOOT_LOG_RECORD));
9471 
9472  ExInitializeResourceLite(&BootLogRecord->Resource);
9473 
9474  //
9475  // No need to do KeEnterCriticalRegion as this is called
9476  // from system process only.
9477  //
9478  ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite(&BootLogRecord->Resource, TRUE);
9479 
9480  DataTableEntry = CONTAINING_RECORD(LoaderBlock->LoadOrderListHead.Flink,
9481  KLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY,
9482  InLoadOrderLinks);
9483 
9484  Status = RtlFindMessage (DataTableEntry->DllBase, 11, 0, BOOTLOG_LOADED, &MessageEntry);
9485 
9486  if (NT_SUCCESS( Status )) {
9487  AnsiString.Buffer = (PCHAR) MessageEntry->Text;
9488  AnsiString.Length = (USHORT)strlen((const char *)MessageEntry->Text);
9489  AnsiString.MaximumLength = AnsiString.Length + 1;
9490 
9491  RtlAnsiStringToUnicodeString(&BootLogRecord->LoadedString, &AnsiString, TRUE);
9492 
9493  // whack the crlf at the end of the string
9494 
9495  if (BootLogRecord->LoadedString.Length > 2 * sizeof(WCHAR)) {
9496  BootLogRecord->LoadedString.Length -= 2 * sizeof(WCHAR);
9497  BootLogRecord->LoadedString.Buffer[BootLogRecord->LoadedString.Length / sizeof(WCHAR)] = UNICODE_NULL;
9498  }
9499  }
9500 
9501  Status = RtlFindMessage (DataTableEntry->DllBase, 11, 0, BOOTLOG_NOT_LOADED, &MessageEntry);
9502 
9503  if (NT_SUCCESS( Status )) {
9504  AnsiString.Buffer = (PCHAR) MessageEntry->Text;
9505  AnsiString.Length = (USHORT)strlen((const char *)MessageEntry->Text);
9506  AnsiString.MaximumLength = AnsiString.Length + 1;
9507 
9508  RtlAnsiStringToUnicodeString(&BootLogRecord->NotLoadedString, &AnsiString, TRUE);
9509 
9510  // whack the crlf at the end of the string
9511 
9512  if (BootLogRecord->NotLoadedString.Length > 2 * sizeof(WCHAR)) {
9513  BootLogRecord->NotLoadedString.Length -= 2 * sizeof(WCHAR);
9514  BootLogRecord->NotLoadedString.Buffer[BootLogRecord->NotLoadedString.Length / sizeof(WCHAR)] = UNICODE_NULL;
9515  }
9516  }
9517 
9518  // The header string (copied from DebugString in Phase1Initialization) appears to have a leading null byte
9519 
9520  HeaderString++;
9521 
9522  RtlCreateUnicodeStringFromAsciiz(&BootLogRecord->HeaderString, HeaderString);
9523 
9524  // Log the drivers loaded by the boot loader
9525 
9526  ExAcquireResourceSharedLite( &PsLoadedModuleResource, TRUE );
9527  nextEntry = PsLoadedModuleList.Flink;
9528  while (nextEntry != &PsLoadedModuleList) {
9529 
9530  //
9531  // Look at the next boot driver in the list.
9532  //
9533 
9534  driverEntry = CONTAINING_RECORD( nextEntry,
9535  KLDR_DATA_TABLE_ENTRY,
9536  InLoadOrderLinks );
9537 
9538  IopBootLog(&driverEntry->FullDllName, TRUE);
9539 
9540  nextEntry = nextEntry->Flink;
9541  }
9542 
9543  ExReleaseResourceLite( &PsLoadedModuleResource );
9544 
9545  ExReleaseResourceLite(&BootLogRecord->Resource);
9546 }
9547 
9548 VOID
9549 IopBootLog(
9550  PUNICODE_STRING LogEntry,
9551  BOOLEAN Loaded
9552  )
9553 /*++
9554 
9555 Routine Description:
9556 
9557  Create and write out a log entry. Before NtInitializeRegistry is called, log entries are spooled
9558  into the registry. When NtInitalizeRegistry is called by the session manager, the
9559  log file is created if necessary and truncated. Log entries in the registry are
9560  then copied into the log file and the registry entries are deleted.
9561 
9562 Arguments:
9563 
9564  LogEntry - the text to log.
9565  Loaded - indicates whether to prepend the "Loaded" string or the "Not Loaded" string.
9566 
9567 Return Value:
9568 
9569  VOID
9570 
9571 
9572 --*/
9573 {
9574  WCHAR NameBuffer[BOOTLOG_STRSIZE];
9575  UNICODE_STRING KeyName;
9576  UNICODE_STRING ValueName;
9577  UNICODE_STRING CrLf;
9578  UNICODE_STRING Space;
9579  NTSTATUS Status;
9580 
9581  WCHAR MessageBuffer[BOOTLOG_STRSIZE];
9582  UNICODE_STRING MessageString = {
9583  0,
9584  BOOTLOG_STRSIZE,
9585  &MessageBuffer[0]
9586  };
9587 
9588  PAGED_CODE();
9589 
9590  if (BootLogRecord == NULL) {
9591  return;
9592  }
9593 
9594  //
9595  // No need to do KeEnterCriticalRegion as this is called
9596  // from system process only.
9597  //
9598  ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite(&BootLogRecord->Resource, TRUE);
9599 
9600  if (Loaded) {
9601  RtlCopyUnicodeString(&MessageString, &BootLogRecord->LoadedString);
9602  } else {
9603  RtlCopyUnicodeString(&MessageString, &BootLogRecord->NotLoadedString);
9604  }
9605 
9606  // add a space after the message prefix
9607 
9608  RtlInitUnicodeString(&Space, L" ");
9609 
9610  RtlAppendUnicodeStringToString(&MessageString, &Space);
9611 
9612  RtlAppendUnicodeStringToString(&MessageString, LogEntry);
9613 
9614  // add a CR LF
9615 
9616  RtlInitUnicodeString(&CrLf, L"\r\n");
9617  RtlAppendUnicodeStringToString(&MessageString, &CrLf);
9618 
9619  swprintf(NameBuffer, L"%d", BootLogRecord->NextKey++);
9620 
9621  RtlCreateUnicodeString(&KeyName, NameBuffer);
9622  RtlInitUnicodeString(&ValueName, L"");
9623 
9624  if (!BootLogRecord->FileLogging) {
9625  HANDLE hLogKey, hBootKey;
9626 
9627  Status = IopOpenRegistryKey (
9628  &hBootKey,
9629  NULL,
9630  &CmRegistryMachineSystemCurrentControlSetControlBootLog,
9631  KEY_ALL_ACCESS,
9632  TRUE
9633  );
9634 
9635  if (NT_SUCCESS(Status)) {
9636  Status = IopOpenRegistryKey (
9637  &hLogKey,
9638  hBootKey,
9639  &KeyName,
9640  KEY_ALL_ACCESS,
9641  TRUE
9642  );
9643  if (NT_SUCCESS(Status)) {
9644  Status = IopSetRegistryStringValue(
9645  hLogKey,
9646  &ValueName,
9647  &MessageString
9648  );
9649  ZwClose(hLogKey);
9650  }
9651  ZwClose(hBootKey);
9652  }
9653 
9654  } else {
9655  IopBootLogToFile( &MessageString );
9656  }
9657 
9658  RtlFreeUnicodeString(&KeyName);
9659 
9660  ExReleaseResourceLite(&BootLogRecord->Resource);
9661 }
9662 
9663 VOID
9664 IopCopyBootLogRegistryToFile(
9665  VOID
9666  )
9667 /*++
9668 
9669 Routine Description:
9670 
9671  Copy the text in the registry entries into the log file and delete the registry entries. Set the
9672  flag that indicates direct logging to the log file.
9673 
9674 Arguments:
9675 
9676  NONE
9677 
9678 Return Value:
9679 
9680  VOID
9681 
9682 
9683 --*/
9684 {
9685  UNICODE_STRING KeyName;
9686  WCHAR NameBuffer[BOOTLOG_STRSIZE];
9687  NTSTATUS Status;
9688  HANDLE hLogKey, hBootKey;
9689  ULONG Index;
9690  PKEY_VALUE_FULL_INFORMATION Information;
9691  LARGE_INTEGER LocalTime;
9692  TIME_FIELDS TimeFields;
9693  CHAR AnsiTimeBuffer[256];
9694  ANSI_STRING AnsiTimeString;
9695  UNICODE_STRING UnicodeTimeString;
9696  UNICODE_STRING LogString;
9697  PKTHREAD CurrentThread;
9698 
9699  PAGED_CODE();
9700 
9701  if (BootLogRecord == NULL) {
9702  return;
9703  }
9704 
9705  CurrentThread = KeGetCurrentThread ();
9706  KeEnterCriticalRegionThread(CurrentThread);
9707  ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite(&BootLogRecord->Resource, TRUE);
9708 
9709  IopBootLogToFile(&BootLogRecord->HeaderString);
9710 
9711  ExSystemTimeToLocalTime(&KeBootTime, &LocalTime);
9712 
9713  RtlTimeToTimeFields(&LocalTime, &TimeFields);
9714 
9715  sprintf(
9716  AnsiTimeBuffer,
9717  "%2d %2d %4d %02d:%02d:%02d.%03d\r\n",
9718  TimeFields.Month,
9719  TimeFields.Day,
9720  TimeFields.Year,
9721  TimeFields.Hour,
9722  TimeFields.Minute,
9723  TimeFields.Second,
9724  TimeFields.Milliseconds
9725  );
9726 
9727  RtlInitAnsiString(&AnsiTimeString, AnsiTimeBuffer);
9728 
9729  RtlAnsiStringToUnicodeString(&UnicodeTimeString, &AnsiTimeString, TRUE);
9730 
9731  IopBootLogToFile(&UnicodeTimeString);
9732 
9733  RtlFreeUnicodeString(&UnicodeTimeString);
9734 
9735  //
9736  // Read all of the strings in the registry and write them to the log file.
9737  // Delete the registry keys when done.
9738  //
9739 
9740  Status = IopOpenRegistryKey (
9741  &hBootKey,
9742  NULL,
9743  &CmRegistryMachineSystemCurrentControlSetControlBootLog,
9744  KEY_ALL_ACCESS,
9745  FALSE
9746  );
9747 
9748  if (NT_SUCCESS(Status)) {
9749  for (Index = 0; Index < BootLogRecord->NextKey; Index++) {
9750  swprintf(NameBuffer, L"%d", Index);
9751 
9752  RtlCreateUnicodeString(&KeyName, NameBuffer);
9753 
9754  Status = IopOpenRegistryKey (
9755  &hLogKey,
9756  hBootKey,
9757  &KeyName,
9758  KEY_ALL_ACCESS,
9759  FALSE
9760  );
9761 
9762  if (NT_SUCCESS(Status)) {
9763  Status = IopGetRegistryValue(
9764  hLogKey,
9765  L"",
9766  &Information
9767  );
9768 
9769  if (NT_SUCCESS(Status)){
9770  RtlInitUnicodeString(&LogString, (PWSTR) ((PUCHAR)Information + Information->DataOffset));
9771  IopBootLogToFile(&LogString);
9772  }
9773  ExFreePool(Information);
9774  ZwDeleteKey(hLogKey);
9775  ZwClose(hLogKey);
9776  }
9777  }
9778  ZwDeleteKey(hBootKey);
9779  ZwClose(hBootKey);
9780 
9781  //
9782  // Write directly to the file from now on.
9783  //
9784 
9785  BootLogRecord->FileLogging = TRUE;
9786  }
9787 
9788  ExReleaseResourceLite(&BootLogRecord->Resource);
9789  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread(CurrentThread);
9790 }
9791 
9792 
9793 NTSTATUS
9794 IopBootLogToFile(
9795  PUNICODE_STRING String
9796  )
9797 /*++
9798 
9799 Routine Description:
9800 
9801  Write the buffer into the log file.
9802 
9803 Arguments:
9804 
9805  Buffer - pointer to the string to write out.
9806  Length - number of bytes to write
9807 
9808 Return Value:
9809 
9810  The function status is the final status of the operation.
9811 
9812 
9813 --*/
9814 {
9815  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES ObjA;
9816  NTSTATUS Status;
9817  IO_STATUS_BLOCK IoStatusBlock;
9818  HANDLE FileHandle;
9819  WCHAR UnicodeHeader = 0xfeff;
9820  PKTHREAD CurrentThread;
9821 
9822  PAGED_CODE();
9823 
9824  if (BootLogRecord == NULL) {
9825  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
9826  }
9827 
9828  CurrentThread = KeGetCurrentThread ();
9829  KeEnterCriticalRegionThread(CurrentThread);
9830  ExAcquireResourceExclusiveLite(&BootLogRecord->Resource, TRUE);
9831 
9832  if (BootLogRecord->LogFileName.Buffer == NULL) {
9833  RtlInitUnicodeString(&BootLogRecord->LogFileName, L"\\SystemRoot\\ntbtlog.txt");
9834  }
9835 
9836  InitializeObjectAttributes(&ObjA, &BootLogRecord->LogFileName, OBJ_CASE_INSENSITIVE|OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE, NULL, NULL);
9837 
9838  Status = ZwCreateFile(&FileHandle,
9839  GENERIC_WRITE,
9840  &ObjA,
9841  &IoStatusBlock,
9842  NULL,
9843  FILE_ATTRIBUTE_NORMAL,
9844  FILE_SHARE_READ,
9845  FILE_OPEN_IF,
9846  FILE_SYNCHRONOUS_IO_NONALERT | FILE_NON_DIRECTORY_FILE | FILE_SEQUENTIAL_ONLY,
9847  NULL,
9848  0
9849  );
9850 
9851  if (NT_SUCCESS(Status)) {
9852 
9853  //
9854  // If the file is created for the first time, write the header.
9855  //
9856 
9857  if (IoStatusBlock.Information == FILE_CREATED) {
9858 
9859  Status = ZwWriteFile(
9860  FileHandle,
9861  NULL,
9862  NULL,
9863  NULL,
9864  &IoStatusBlock,
9865  (PVOID) &UnicodeHeader,
9866  sizeof(WCHAR),
9867  NULL,
9868  NULL
9869  );
9870  }
9871 
9872  if (NT_SUCCESS(Status)) {
9873 
9874  LARGE_INTEGER EndOfFile;
9875 
9876  EndOfFile.HighPart = 0xffffffff;
9877  EndOfFile.LowPart = FILE_WRITE_TO_END_OF_FILE;
9878 
9879  Status = ZwWriteFile(
9880  FileHandle,
9881  NULL,
9882  NULL,
9883  NULL,
9884  &IoStatusBlock,
9885  (PVOID) String->Buffer,
9886  String->Length,
9887  &EndOfFile,
9888  NULL
9889  );
9890 
9891  }
9892 
9893  ZwClose(FileHandle);
9894  }
9895 
9896  ExReleaseResourceLite(&BootLogRecord->Resource);
9897  KeLeaveCriticalRegionThread(CurrentThread);
9898 
9899  return Status;
9900 }

9902 PLIST_ENTRY
9903 FASTCALL
9904 IopInterlockedInsertHeadList (
9905  IN PLIST_ENTRY ListHead,
9906  IN PLIST_ENTRY ListEntry
9907  )
9908 
9909 /*++
9910 
9911 Routine Description:
9912 
9913  This function inserts an entry at the head of a list using the I/O
9914  database lock for synchronization.
9915 
9916 Arguments:
9917 
9918  Listhead - Supplies a pointer to the list head.
9919 
9920  ListEntry - Supplies a pointer to the list entry.
9921 
9922 Return Value:
9923 
9924  If the list was previously empty, then NULL is returned as the function
9925  value. Otherwise, a pointer to the previous first entry in the list is
9926  returned as the function value.
9927 
9928 --*/
9929 
9930 {
9931 
9932  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
9933  KIRQL irql;
9934 
9935  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
9936  entry = ListHead->Flink;
9937  if ( entry == ListHead ) {
9938  entry = NULL;
9939  }
9940 
9941  InsertHeadList( ListHead, ListEntry );
9942  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
9943  return entry;
9944 }

9996 /*++
