10033 ULONG
10034 FASTCALL
10035 IopInterlockedDecrementUlong (
10036  IN KSPIN_LOCK_QUEUE_NUMBER Number,
10037  IN OUT PLONG Addend
10038  )
10039 
10040 /*++
10041 
10042 Routine Description:
10043 
10044  This function decrements the specified value using a queued spin lock
10045  for synchronization.
10046 
10047 Arguments:
10048 
10049  Number - Supplies the number of the queued spin lock.
10050 
10051  Addend - Supplies a pointer to the variable to be decremented.
10052 
10053 Return Value:
10054 
10055  The value of the variable before the decrement is applied.
10056 
10057 --*/
10058 
10059 {
10060 
10061  KIRQL irql;
10062  ULONG value;
10063 
10064 #if !DBG && defined(NT_UP)
10065  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (Number);
10066 #endif
10067 
10068  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( Number );
10069  *(LONG volatile *)Addend -= 1;
10070  value = *Addend;
10071  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( Number, irql );
10072  return value + 1;
10073 }
10074 
10075 ULONG
10076 FASTCALL
10077 IopInterlockedIncrementUlong (
10078  IN KSPIN_LOCK_QUEUE_NUMBER Number,
10079  IN OUT PLONG Addend
10080  )
10081 
10082 /*++
10083 
10084 Routine Description:
10085 
10086  This function increments the specified value using a queued spin lock
10087  for synchronization.
10088 
10089 Arguments:
10090 
10091  Number - Supplies the number of the queued spin lock.
10092 
10093  Addend - Supplies a pointer to the variable to be incremented.
10094 
10095 Return Value:
10096 
10097  The value of the variable before the increment is applied.
10098 
10099 --*/
10100 
10101 {
10102 
10103  KIRQL irql;
10104  ULONG value;
10105 
10106 #if !DBG && defined(NT_UP)
10107  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (Number);
10108 #endif
10109 
10110  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( Number );
10111  *(LONG volatile *)Addend += 1;
10112  value = *Addend;
10113  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( Number, irql );
10114  return value - 1;
10115 }

10117 BOOLEAN
10118 IopCallBootDriverReinitializationRoutines(
10119  VOID
10120  )
10121 
10122 /*++
10123 
10124 Routine Description:
10125 
10126  This routine processes the boot driver reinitialization list. It calls each
10127  entry and then removes it from the list.
10128 
10129 Arguments:
10130 
10131  NONE
10132 
10133 Returns:
10134 
10135  TRUE if any entries were processed.
10136 
10137 --*/
10138 
10139 {
10140  PLIST_ENTRY entry;
10141  PREINIT_PACKET reinitEntry;
10142  BOOLEAN routinesFound = FALSE;
10143 
10144  //
10145  // Walk the list reinitialization list in case this driver, or
10146  // some other driver, has requested to be invoked at a re-
10147  // initialization entry point.
10148  //
10149 
10150  while (entry = IopInterlockedRemoveHeadList( &IopBootDriverReinitializeQueueHead )) {
10151  routinesFound = TRUE;
10152  reinitEntry = CONTAINING_RECORD( entry, REINIT_PACKET, ListEntry );
10153  reinitEntry->DriverObject->DriverExtension->Count++;
10154  reinitEntry->DriverObject->Flags &= ~DRVO_BOOTREINIT_REGISTERED;
10155  reinitEntry->DriverReinitializationRoutine( reinitEntry->DriverObject,
10156  reinitEntry->Context,
10157  reinitEntry->DriverObject->DriverExtension->Count );
10158  ExFreePool( reinitEntry );
10159  }
10160 
10161  return routinesFound;
10162 }
10163 
10164 BOOLEAN
10165 IopCallDriverReinitializationRoutines(
10166  VOID
10167  )
10168 
10169 /*++
10170 
10171 Routine Description:

10173  This routine processes the driver reinitialization list. It calls each
10174  entry and then removes it from the list.

10176 Arguments:
10177 
10178  NONE
10179 
10180 Returns:
10181 
10182  TRUE if any entries were processed.
10183

10185 
10186 {

10189  BOOLEAN routinesFound = FALSE;
10190 
10191  PAGED_CODE();
10192 
10193  //
10194  // Walk the list reinitialization list in case this driver, or
10195  // some other driver, has requested to be invoked at a re-
10196  // initialization entry point.
10197  //
10198 
10199  while (entry = IopInterlockedRemoveHeadList( &IopDriverReinitializeQueueHead )) {
10200  routinesFound = TRUE;

10213 PDRIVER_OBJECT
10214 IopReferenceDriverObjectByName (
10215  IN PUNICODE_STRING DriverName
10216  )
10217 
10218 /*++
10219 
10220 Routine Description:
10221 
10222  This routine references a driver object by a given driver name.
10223 
10224 Arguments:
10225 
10226  DriverName - supplies a pointer to the name of the driver whose driver object is
10227  to be referenced.
10228 
10229 Returns:
10230 
10231  A pointer to a DRIVER_OBJECT if succeeds. Otherwise, a NULL value.
10232 
10233 --*/
10234 
10235 {
10236  OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES objectAttributes;
10237  HANDLE driverHandle;
10238  NTSTATUS status;
10239  PDRIVER_OBJECT driverObject;
10240 
10241  //
10242  // Make sure the driver name is valid.
10243  //
10244 
10245  if (DriverName->Length == 0) {
10246  return NULL;
10247  }
10248 
10249  InitializeObjectAttributes(&objectAttributes,
10250  DriverName,
10251  OBJ_CASE_INSENSITIVE | OBJ_KERNEL_HANDLE,
10252  NULL,
10253  NULL
10254  );
10255  status = ObOpenObjectByName(&objectAttributes,
10256  IoDriverObjectType,
10257  KernelMode,
10258  NULL,
10259  FILE_READ_ATTRIBUTES,
10260  NULL,
10261  &driverHandle
10262  );
10263  if (NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
10264 
10265  //
10266  // Now reference the driver object.
10267  //
10268 
10269  status = ObReferenceObjectByHandle(driverHandle,
10270  0,
10271  IoDriverObjectType,
10272  KernelMode,
10273  &driverObject,
10274  NULL
10275  );
10276  NtClose(driverHandle);
10277  if (NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
10278  return driverObject;
10279  }
10280  }
10281 
10282  return NULL;
10283 }

10286 PIRP
10287 IopAllocateReserveIrp(
10288  IN CCHAR StackSize
10289  )
10290 /*++
10291 
10292 Routine Description:
10293 
10294  This routine allocates a reserve IRP for paging reads.
10295 
10296 Arguments:
10297 
10298  StackSize - IRP stack size.
10299 
10300 Return Value:
10301 
10302  The function value is an IRP.
10303 
10304 --*/
10305 {
10306  PIOP_RESERVE_IRP_ALLOCATOR allocator = &IopReserveIrpAllocator;
10307 
10308  if (StackSize > allocator->ReserveIrpStackSize) {
10309  return NULL;
10310  }
10311 
10312 
10313  while (InterlockedExchange(&allocator->IrpAllocated, 1) == 1) {
10314 
10315  (VOID)KeWaitForSingleObject(&allocator->Event,
10316  Executive,
10317  KernelMode,
10318  FALSE,
10319  (PLARGE_INTEGER)0);
10320  }
10321 
10322  IoInitializeIrp(allocator->ReserveIrp, IoSizeOfIrp(StackSize), StackSize);
10323  return (allocator->ReserveIrp);
10324 }

10410 PVPB
10411 IopMountInitializeVpb(
10412  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
10413  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT AttachedDevice,
10414  IN ULONG RawMountOnly
10415  )
10416 /*++
10417 
10418 Routine Description:
10419 
10420  This routine initializes the mounted volume VPB holding the VPB lock.
10421 
10422 Arguments:
10423 
10424  DeviceObject - Disk device object
10425  AttachedDevice - Top of FS stack.
10426  RawMountOnly - Only allow raw mounts
10427 
10428 Return Value:
10429 
10430  none.
10431 
10432 --*/
10433 {
10434  KIRQL irql;
10435  PVPB vpb;
10436 
10437  IoAcquireVpbSpinLock(&irql);
10438 
10439  vpb = DeviceObject->Vpb;
10440 
10441  vpb->Flags = VPB_MOUNTED;
10442 
10443 
10444  //
10445  // We explicitly propagate VPB_RAW_MOUNT as the previous
10446  // statement that has been there for a long time in NT
10447  // could be clearing other flags which should be cleared.
10448  //
10449 
10450  if (RawMountOnly) {
10451  vpb->Flags |= VPB_RAW_MOUNT;
10452  }
10453 
10454  vpb->DeviceObject->StackSize = (UCHAR) (AttachedDevice->StackSize + 1);
10455 
10456  //
10457  // Set the reverse Vpb pointer in the filesystem device object's VPB.
10458  //
10459 
10460  vpb->DeviceObject->DeviceObjectExtension->Vpb = vpb;
10461 
10462  vpb->ReferenceCount += 1;
10463 
10464  IoReleaseVpbSpinLock(irql);
10465 
10466  return vpb;
10467 }
10468 
10469 BOOLEAN
10470 IopVerifyDeviceObjectOnStack(
10471  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT BaseDeviceObject,
10472  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT TopDeviceObject
10473  )
10474 /*++
10475 
10476 Routine Description:
10477 
10478  This routine checks if a device object is on a device stack.
10479 
10480 Arguments:
10481 
10482  BaseDeviceObject - Lowest device object on the stack.
10483  TopDeviceObject - Device which is to be tested.
10484 
10485 Return Value:
10486 
10487  Returns TRUE if TopDeviceObject is on stack.
10488 
10489 --*/
10490 {
10491  KIRQL irql;
10492  PDEVICE_OBJECT currentDeviceObject;
10493 
10494  //
10495  // Loop through all of the device object's attached to the specified
10496  // device. When the last device object is found that is not attached
10497  // to, return it.
10498  //
10499 
10500  ASSERT( BaseDeviceObject != NULL);
10501 
10502  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
10503  currentDeviceObject = BaseDeviceObject;
10504 
10505  do {
10506  if (currentDeviceObject == TopDeviceObject) {
10507  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
10508  return TRUE;
10509  }
10510  currentDeviceObject = currentDeviceObject->AttachedDevice;
10511  } while (currentDeviceObject);
10512 
10513  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
10514  return FALSE;
10515 }
10516 
10517 BOOLEAN
10518 IopVerifyDiskSignature(
10519  IN PDRIVE_LAYOUT_INFORMATION_EX DriveLayout,
10520  IN PARC_DISK_SIGNATURE LoaderDiskBlock,
10521  OUT PULONG DiskSignature
10522  )
10523 /*++
10524 
10525 Routine Description:
10526 
10527  This routine verifies disk signature that is present in the loader block
10528  and that retrieved by the storage drivers.
10529 
10530 Arguments:
10531 
10532  DriveLayout - Information obtained from the storage stack.
10533  LoaderDiskBlock - Signature info from loader
10534  SectorBuffer - Buffer containing sector 0 on the disk.
10535  DiskSignature - If successful contains disk signature.
10536 
10537 Return Value:
10538 
10539  Returns TRUE if signature matches.
10540 
10541 --*/
10542 {
10543  ULONG diskSignature;
10544 
10545  if (!LoaderDiskBlock->ValidPartitionTable) {
10546  return FALSE;
10547  }
10548 
10549  //
10550  // Save off the signature in local variable if
10551  // its a MBR disk
10552  //
10553 
10554  if (DriveLayout->PartitionStyle == PARTITION_STYLE_MBR) {
10555  diskSignature = DriveLayout->Mbr.Signature;
10556  if (LoaderDiskBlock->Signature == diskSignature) {
10557  if (DiskSignature) {
10558  *DiskSignature = diskSignature;
10559  }
10560  return TRUE;
10561  }
10562  }
10563 
10564  //
10565  // Get hold of the signature from MBR if its GPT disk
10566  //
10567 
10568  if (DriveLayout->PartitionStyle == PARTITION_STYLE_GPT) {
10569 
10570  if (!LoaderDiskBlock->IsGpt) {
10571  return FALSE;
10572  }
10573 
10574  if (!RtlEqualMemory(LoaderDiskBlock->GptSignature, &DriveLayout->Gpt.DiskId, sizeof(GUID))) {
10575  return FALSE;
10576  }
10577 
10578  if (DiskSignature) {
10579  *DiskSignature = 0;
10580  }
10581  return TRUE;
10582  }
10583 
10584  return FALSE;
10585 }

10587 NTSTATUS
10588 IopGetDriverPathInformation(
10589  IN PFILE_OBJECT FileObject,
10590  IN PFILE_FS_DRIVER_PATH_INFORMATION FsDpInfo,
10591  IN ULONG Length
10592  )
10593 /*++
10594 
10595 Routine Description:
10596 
10597  This routine returns true if a driver specified by name is present in the IO path
10598  for the fileobject.
10599 
10600 Arguments:
10601 
10602  FileObject - FileObject to which IO is issued.
10603  FsDpInfo - Info that contains driver name.
10604 
10605 Return Value:
10606 
10607  NTSTATUS
10608 
10609 --*/
10610 {
10611  UNICODE_STRING driverString;
10612  PDRIVER_OBJECT driverObject;
10613  NTSTATUS status;
10614  KIRQL irql;
10615 
10616  if ((ULONG) (Length - FIELD_OFFSET( FILE_FS_DRIVER_PATH_INFORMATION, DriverName[0] )) < FsDpInfo->DriverNameLength) {
10617  return STATUS_INVALID_PARAMETER;
10618  }
10619 
10620  driverString.Buffer = FsDpInfo->DriverName;
10621  driverString.Length = (USHORT)FsDpInfo->DriverNameLength;
10622  driverString.MaximumLength = (USHORT)FsDpInfo->DriverNameLength;
10623 
10624  status = ObReferenceObjectByName(&driverString,
10625  OBJ_CASE_INSENSITIVE,
10626  NULL, // access state
10627  0, // access mask
10628  IoDriverObjectType,
10629  KernelMode,
10630  NULL, // parse context
10631  &driverObject);
10632  if (!NT_SUCCESS(status)) {
10633  return status;
10634  }
10635 
10636  irql = KeAcquireQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock );
10637 
10638 
10639  if (FileObject->Vpb != NULL && FileObject->Vpb->DeviceObject != NULL) {
10640 
10641  //
10642  // Check the disk filesystem stack.
10643  //
10644 
10645  if (IopVerifyDriverObjectOnStack(FileObject->Vpb->DeviceObject, driverObject)) {
10646 
10647  FsDpInfo->DriverInPath = TRUE;
10648  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
10649  ObDereferenceObject(driverObject);
10650  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
10651  }
10652  }
10653 
10654  //
10655  // Check the storage stack or non disk filesystem stack.
10656  //
10657 
10658  FsDpInfo->DriverInPath = IopVerifyDriverObjectOnStack(FileObject->DeviceObject, driverObject);
10659  KeReleaseQueuedSpinLock( LockQueueIoDatabaseLock, irql );
10660 
10661  ObDereferenceObject(driverObject);
10662  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
10663 }
10664 
10665 BOOLEAN
10666 IopVerifyDriverObjectOnStack(
10667  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
10668  IN PDRIVER_OBJECT DriverObject
10669  )
10670 /*++
10671 
10672 Routine Description:
10673 
10674  This routine returns true if a driver specified by driverObject is present in the IO path
10675  for the deviceobject.
10676 
10677 Arguments:
10678 
10679  DeviceObject - DeviceObject to which IO is issued.
10680  Driverobject - DriverObject to be checked.
10681 
10682 Return Value:
10683 
10684  TRUE if the driverObject is in the IO path
10685 
10686 --*/
10687 {
10688  PDEVICE_OBJECT currentDeviceObject;
10689 
10690  currentDeviceObject = IopGetDeviceAttachmentBase(DeviceObject);
10691 
10692  while (currentDeviceObject) {
10693  if (currentDeviceObject->DriverObject == DriverObject) {
10694  return TRUE;
10695  }
10696  currentDeviceObject = currentDeviceObject->AttachedDevice;
10697  }
10698  return FALSE;
10699 }

10718 NTSTATUS
10719 IopInitializeIrpStackProfiler(
10720  VOID
10721  )
10722 /*++
10723 
10724 Routine Description:
10725 
10726  This routine initializes the Irp stack profiler.
10727 
10728 Arguments:
10729 
10730 
10731 Return Value:
10732 
10733  NTSTATUS
10734 
10735 --*/
10736 {
10737  LARGE_INTEGER dueTime;
10738 
10739  RtlZeroMemory(IopIrpStackProfiler.Profile, MAX_LOOKASIDE_IRP_STACK_COUNT * sizeof(ULONG));
10740 
10741  KeInitializeTimer(&IopIrpStackProfiler.Timer);
10742  KeInitializeDpc(&IopIrpStackProfiler.Dpc, IopIrpStackProfilerTimer, &IopIrpStackProfiler);
10743 
10744  dueTime.QuadPart = - IOP_PROFILE_TIME_PERIOD * 10 * 1000 * 1000; // 1 Minute with a recurring period of a minute
10745  IopIrpStackProfiler.TriggerCount = 0;
10746 
10747  KeSetTimerEx(&IopIrpStackProfiler.Timer, dueTime, IOP_PROFILE_TIME_PERIOD * 1000, &IopIrpStackProfiler.Dpc);
10748 
10749  return STATUS_SUCCESS;
10750 }
10751 
10752 VOID
10753 IopIrpStackProfilerTimer(
10754  IN struct _KDPC *Dpc,
10755  IN PVOID DeferredContext,
10756  IN PVOID SystemArgument1,
10757  IN PVOID SystemArgument2
10758  )
10759 /*++
10760 
10761 Routine Description:
10762 
10763  This routine is the timer DPC routine.
10764 
10765 Arguments:
10766 
10767  DeferredContext - Pointer to the profiler structure.
10768 
10769 Return Value:
10770 
10771  None
10772 
10773 --*/
10774 {
10775  PIOP_IRP_STACK_PROFILER profiler = DeferredContext;
10776  LONG i;
10777  ULONG totalIrpsCounted;
10778 
10779  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (Dpc);
10780  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (SystemArgument1);
10781  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (SystemArgument2);
10782 
10783  //
10784  // If profile stack count is now enabled, we wait for ProfileDuration * 60 secs to stop
10785  // it. Once stopped, IopProcessIrpStackProfiler will tally the counts and find the top two
10786  // stack counts.
10787  //
10788 
10789  if (profiler->Flags & IOP_PROFILE_STACK_COUNT) {
10790  totalIrpsCounted = 0;
10791  for (i = 0; i < MAX_LOOKASIDE_IRP_STACK_COUNT; i++) {
10792  totalIrpsCounted += profiler->Profile[i];
10793  }
10794  if (totalIrpsCounted > NUM_SAMPLE_IRPS) {
10795  profiler->Flags &= ~IOP_PROFILE_STACK_COUNT; // Stop the profiling.
10796  IopProcessIrpStackProfiler();
10797  }
10798  return;
10799  }
10800 
10801  //
10802  // Every IOP_PROFILE_TRIGGER_INTERVAL * 60 seconds we turn on the profiling
10803  //
10804 
10805  profiler->TriggerCount++;
10806  if ((profiler->TriggerCount % IOP_PROFILE_TRIGGER_INTERVAL) == 0) {
10807  profiler->Flags |= IOP_PROFILE_STACK_COUNT; // Enable profiling
10808  }
10809 }
10810 
10811 VOID
10812 IopProcessIrpStackProfiler(
10813  VOID
10814  )
10815 /*++
10816 
10817 Routine Description:
10818 
10819  This routine profiles and resets the per-processor counters. It sets the variables
10820  IopLargeIrpStackLocations and IopSmallIrpStackLocations with the values learned from
10821  counters.
10822 
10823 Arguments:
10824 
10825  None
10826 
10827 Return Value:
10828 
10829  None
10830 
10831 --*/
10832 {
10833  PIOP_IRP_STACK_PROFILER profiler = &IopIrpStackProfiler;
10834  ULONG i;
10835  LONG bucket = 0;
10836  ULONG stackCount = 0;
10837  LONG numRequests;
10838 
10839  numRequests = 0;
10840  for (i = BASE_STACK_COUNT; i < MAX_LOOKASIDE_IRP_STACK_COUNT; i++) {
10841  numRequests += profiler->Profile[i];
10842  profiler->Profile[i] = 0;
10843  if (numRequests > bucket) {
10844  stackCount = i;
10845  bucket = numRequests;
10846  }
10847  numRequests = 0;
10848  }
10849 
10850 
10851  //
10852  // If the top allocation is less than the minimum threshold do nothing.
10853  //
10854 
10855  if (bucket < MIN_IRP_THRESHOLD) {
10856  return;
10857  }
10858 
10859  //
10860  // Update the global variables. This should cause IoAllocateIrp to start using the new IRPs
10861  // right away.
10862  //
10863 
10864  if (IopLargeIrpStackLocations != stackCount) {
10865  IopLargeIrpStackLocations = stackCount;
10866  }
10867 }
10868 
10869 BOOLEAN
10870 IopReferenceVerifyVpb(
10871  IN PDEVICE_OBJECT DeviceObject,
10872  OUT PVPB *Vpb,
10873  OUT PDEVICE_OBJECT *FsDeviceObject
10874  )
10875 /*++
10876 
10877 Routine Description:
10878 
10879  This routine tests if a device object is mounted and if so retrieves
10880  the fs device object and returns it along with the VPB. Its called
10881  from IoVerifyVolume. It takes a reference so that the VPB and the fsDeviceObject
10882  don't vanish.
10883 
10884 Arguments:
10885 
10886  DeviceObject - DeviceObject of the drive we have to verify.
10887  Vpb - The vpb is returned here.
10888  FsDeviceObject - The fs deviceobject is returned here.
10889 
10890 Return Value:
10891 
10892  TRUE if mounted, FALSE otherwise.
10893 
10894 --*/
10895 {
10896  KIRQL irql;
10897  BOOLEAN isMounted = FALSE;
10898  PVPB vpb;
10899 
10900  IoAcquireVpbSpinLock(&irql);
10901 
10902  *Vpb = NULL;
10903  *FsDeviceObject = NULL;
10904 
10905  vpb = DeviceObject->Vpb;
10906 
10907  if (vpb && vpb->Flags & VPB_MOUNTED) {
10908  *FsDeviceObject = vpb->DeviceObject;
10909  isMounted = TRUE;
10910  *Vpb = vpb;
10911  vpb->ReferenceCount++;
10912  }
10913 
10914  IoReleaseVpbSpinLock(irql);
10915 
10916  return isMounted;
10917 }
